ed in late January,<ref name=Ball31Jan2020 /> transmission within the UK was confirmed in late February,<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\"/> and the number of cases increased rapidly in March.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\" /> As of 13 April, there have been 88,621 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK,{{refn|group=\"nb\"|name=\"nb04\"|In addition to this figure, there have been eight confirmed cases in the [[British Overseas Territories]] (including in [[Gibraltar]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2020/03/04/covid-19-politicians-respond-to-coronavirus-case-in-gibraltar/ |title=COVID-19: Politicians respond to Coronavirus case in Gibraltar |last=Thomas |first=Diexter |date=4 March 2020 |website=Olive Press News Spain |access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305135905/https://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2020/03/04/covid-19-politicians-respond-to-coronavirus-case-in-gibraltar/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Army likely to embed medics in NHS hospitals to help fight coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/army-likely-to-embed-medics-in-nhs-hospitals-to-help-fight-coronavirus-operation-broadshare |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318093507/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/army-likely-to-embed-medics-in-nhs-hospitals-to-help-fight-coronavirus-operation-broadshare |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Bermuda]],<ref>[http://www.royalgazette.com/editorials/article/20200320/time-to-work-together A time to work together] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122653/http://www.royalgazette.com/editorials/article/20200320/time-to-work-together |date=20 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.royalgazette.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref> the [[Cayman Islands]],<ref>[https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/19/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed/ Two new coronavirus cases confirmed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122702/https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/19/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed/ |date=20 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.caymancompass.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref> and [[Montserrat]]).<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Montserrat_registers_first_case_of_coronavirus?profile=1228 Montserrat registers first case of coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318144959/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Montserrat_registers_first_case_of_coronavirus?profile=1228 |date=18 March 2020 }} ''www.jamaicaobserver.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref>}}<ref name=ArcGISUK /> and 11,329 people with confirmed infection have died.<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb02\" /><ref name=ArcGISUK />\n\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] had caused a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei|Hubei Province]], China, which had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=gov.uk2Update>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004037/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|archive-date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The UK subsequently developed a prototype [[COVID-19 testing|specific laboratory test for the disease]].<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> The four UK [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officers]] (CMOs) raised the UK risk level from low to moderate on 30 January, upon the WHO's announcement of the disease as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern|Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC)]].<ref name=Russell13Feb2020>{{cite web |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/924664 |title=New Coronavirus: UK Public Health Campaign Launched |last=Russell |first=Peter |date=3 February 2020 |website=[[Medscape]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301185825/https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/924664|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After confirmed cases appeared in the UK on 31 January a public health information campaign was launched to advise people how to lessen the risk of spreading the virus.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Further cases in early February prompted the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], to introduce the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]] [[statutory instrument]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Guidance on infection prevention and control, how to detect and diagnose COVID-19, and daily updates, including advice to travellers, have been published by the UK's [[Department of Health and Social Care]] (DHSC) and [[Public Health England]] (PHE).<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> In addition, the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS) set up COVID-19 drive-through screening centres at some hospitals.<ref name=\"clch29Feb2020\"/><ref name=\"BBCSct29Feb2020\"/> The Chief Medical Officer for England, [[Chris Whitty]], explained a four-pronged strategy to tackle the outbreak: contain, delay, research and mitigate.<ref name=Kobie/>\n\nThe earliest documented transmission within the UK appeared on 28 February 2020; all of the cases detected previously are believed to have been infected abroad.<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\"/> By 1 March, cases had been detected in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England|England]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales|Wales]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland|Scotland]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=gov.scotCOVID-19>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirusin Scotland - gov.scot |last= |first= |date= |website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305145636/https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=5 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] unveiled the Coronavirus Action Plan,<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> and the government declared the outbreak a \"level 4 incident\".<ref name=Discombe3March2020/> On 11 March, the WHO declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\">{{cite web |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11&nbsp;March 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other responses included some schools in England choosing to close.<ref name=Bedingfield/> Airlines announced a number of flight cancellations,<ref name=BBCNews2March2020/> and some online retailers reported consumers placing unusually large orders.<ref name=guardi/> On 12 March, the UK risk level was raised from moderate to high.<ref name=Gov.UK12March2020/> Four days later, following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|outbreak in Italy]],<ref name=avoid/> whose health system shares similar values and organisation to the NHS,<ref name=Remuzzi13March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Remuzzi |first=Andrea |last2=Remuzzi |first2=Giuseppe |date=13 March 2020 |title=COVID-19 and Italy: what next? |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930627-9 |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=English |volume=0 |issue=10231 |pages=1225\u20131228 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30627-9 |pmid=32178769 |pmc=7102589 |issn=0140-6736}}</ref> and based on evidence including forecasting by epidemiologists at [[Imperial College London]],<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\">{{cite web |last1=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team |title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf |website=Imperial College London |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316223332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> the government advised on further measures on [[social distancing]] and advised people in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70, and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and were asked to [[Self-isolation|self-isolate]].<ref name=avoid/>\n\nOn 18 March, it was announced that the UK would [[2020 UK education shutdown|close all schools]] except for children of [[Key worker|key workers]] and vulnerable children.<ref name=bbcnews18March2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318174202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|archive-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, all restaurants, pubs, clubs, and indoor sport and leisure facilities were ordered to close, though delivery and take-out chains were allowed to remain open.<ref name=2020_327_pdfs>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/pdfs/uksi_20200327_en.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323004800/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/pdfs/uksi_20200327_en.pdf|url-status=dead |title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020 |archivedate=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, the government announced that in order to protect the NHS, these measures were to be tightened further, with wide-ranging restrictions made on freedom of movement, enforceable in law,<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23>\n{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432 |title=PM announces strict new curbs on life in UK |date=23 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2020}}\n</ref>\nresulting in the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]], the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]] and other similar [[statutory instrument]]s covering the other [[home nations]].\n\nIn late March, Boris Johnson developed COVID-19 symptoms and tested positive for the virus. On 5 April, he was hospitalised due to the disease and was moved to an [[intensive care unit]] the following day. He nominated his [[First Secretary of State]], [[Dominic Raab]], to deputise for him.<ref name=BorisJohnsonICU>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-from-downing-street-6-april-2020 |title=Statement from Downing Street: 6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Johnson was released from intensive care on 9 April, and left hospital on 12 April.\n\n==Background==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/> From 19 March, [[Public Health England]] no longer classified COVID-19 as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases chart}}\n\n===Late January 2020 \u2013 first cases===\nOn 22 January, following a confirmed [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|case of COVID-19 in the United States]] the previous day, in a man returning to Washington from Wuhan, China, where there were 440 confirmed cases at the time, the DHSC and PHE raised the risk level from \"very low\" to \"low\". As a result, [[Heathrow Airport]] received additional clinical support and tightened surveillance of the three direct flights that it received from Wuhan every week; each were to be met by a Port Health team with Mandarin and Cantonese language support. In addition, all airports in the UK were to make written guidance available for unwell travellers.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\">{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=22 January 2020 |title=Coronavirus: UK screens direct flights from Wuhan after US case |url=http://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m265 |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=368 |pages=m265 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m265 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=31969317|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222041142/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m265|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\"PHE23Jan2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-and-avian-flu-advice-for-travel-to-china |title=Wuhan novel coronavirus and avian flu: advice for travel to China |date=23 January 2020 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120181905/http://www.gov.uk/government/news/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-and-avian-flu-advice-for-travel-to-china|archive-date=20 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Simultaneously, efforts to trace 2,000 people who had flown into the UK from Wuhan over the previous 14 days were made.<ref name=BBC24Jan2020>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51232163 |title=China coronavirus: UK tracing up to 2,000 Wuhan visitors |date=24 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124064253/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51232163|archive-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, two members of a family of Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]], one of whom studied at the [[University of York]], became the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK. Upon confirmation, they were transferred from [[Hull University Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust|Hull University Teaching Hospital]] to a specialist isolation facility, a designated High Consequence Infectious Diseases Unit in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref name=Ball31Jan2020/><ref name=Lancet14March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Moss |first=Peter |last2=Barlow |first2=Gavin |last3=Easom |first3=Nicholas |last4=Lillie |first4=Patrick |last5=Samson |first5=Anda |date=14 March 2020 |title=Lessons for managing high-consequence infections from first COVID-19 cases in the UK |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930463-3 |journal=The Lancet |volume=395 |issue=10227 |pages=e46 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30463-3 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32113507|pmc=7133597 }}</ref> The [[index case]] for the UK, a 50-year-old female who had travelled from Hubei province and entered the UK on 23 January, had developed fever and fatigue after three days. Her close household contact, a 23-year-old student who had travelled from Hubei province on 6 January, developed symptoms on 28 January.<ref name=Lillie28Feb2020>{{Cite journal|last=Lillie|first=Patrick J.|last2=Samson|first2=Anda|last3=Li|first3=Ang|last4=Adams|first4=Kate|last5=Capstick|first5=Richard|last6=Barlow|first6=Gavin D.|last7=Easom|first7=Nicholas|last8=Hamilton|first8=Eve|last9=Moss|first9=Peter J.|last10=Evans|first10=Adam|last11=Ivan|first11=Monica|date=28 February 2020|title=Novel coronavirus disease (Covid-19): The first two patients in the UK with person to person transmission|url=https://www.journalofinfection.com/article/S0163-4453(20)30102-X/abstract|journal=Journal of Infection|language=English|volume=0|doi=10.1016/j.jinf.2020.02.020|issn=0163-4453|pmid=32119884|pmc=7127394}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, an [[evacuations related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|evacuation flight]] from Wuhan landed at [[RAF Brize Norton]] and the passengers, none of whom were showing symptoms, were taken to quarantine, in a staff residential block at [[Arrowe Park Hospital]] on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\">{{cite web |title=Britons in Wuhan to return home on Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131024212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> There had previously been contention over whether the government should assist the repatriation of UK passport holders from the most affected areas in China, or restrict travel from affected regions altogether.<ref name=\"Standard27Jan2020\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html |title=Ministers came under growing pressure today to evacuate Britons from the Chinese region shut down by the killer coronavirus. |date=27 January 2020 |work=London Evening Standard|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222145256/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"McHutchon25Jan2020\">{{Cite news |last=McHutchon |first=David |url=https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/ |title=Too Weak, Too Slow: The UK Government's Dithering Response to the Wuhan Coronavirus Increases the Risk of Major Loss of Life |date=25 January 2020 |work=|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222131735/https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|archive-date=22 February 2020 |publisher=Technical Politics}}</ref> Some British nationals in Wuhan had been informed that they could be evacuated but any spouses or children with mainland Chinese passports could not.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350 |title=British mum told to leave son behind in Wuhan |date=30 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later overturned, but the delay meant that some people missed the flight.<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\" />\n\n===February 2020 \u2013 early spread===\nOn 6 February, a third confirmed case, a man who had recently travelled to Singapore and then France, was reported in [[Brighton]]. He had been the source of infection to six of his relatives in France, before returning to the UK on 28 January.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus |title=First British national to contract coronavirus had been in Singapore |first1=Sarah |last1=Boseley |first2=Denis |last2=Campbell |first3=Simon |last3=Murphy |date=6 February 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207020202/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|archive-date=7 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mohdin>{{Cite news |last=Mohdin |first=Kim Willsher Aamna |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals |title=Coronavirus: British nine-year-old in hospital in France |date=8 February 2020 |work=The Observer|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live |last2=Madrid |first2=and Sam Jones in |issn=0029-7712|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226161959/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of his result, the UK's CMOs expanded the number of countries where a history of previous travel associated with flu-like symptoms \u2013 such as fever, cough, and difficulty breathing \u2013 in the previous 14 days would require self-isolation and calling [[NHS 111]]. These countries included China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan, and Thailand.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector |title=COVID-19: guidance for staff in the transport sector |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220133756/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the total number of cases in the UK reached eight as four further cases were confirmed in people linked to the affected man from Brighton.<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761 |title=Coronavirus closes Brighton GP practice |date=11 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PHE10Feb2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases |title=Chief Medical Officer for England announces four further coronavirus cases |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223522/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Globally, the virus had spread to 28 countries.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> That day, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], announced the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]], to give public health professionals \"strengthened powers\" to keep affected people and those believed to be a possible risk of having the virus, in isolation.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> The following day, two of the eight confirmed cases in the UK were reported by BBC News to be [[general practitioners]] (GPs).<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020/> A ninth case was confirmed in London on 11 February.<ref name=BBC12Feb2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469 |title=Ninth coronavirus case found in UK |date=12 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=12 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212193433/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, the [[Department of Health and Social Care|DHSC]] confirmed a total of 13 cases in the UK as four new cases in passengers on the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' were detected. They were transferred to hospitals in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51606368 |title=Four new UK coronavirus cases among ship evacuees |date=23 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223210057/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51606368 |archive-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, the total number of confirmed cases in the UK were reported as 16, including the first case in Northern Ireland \u2013 a woman who had travelled from the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|outbreak area in northern Italy]], and flew from Milan to Dublin and by train to Belfast.<ref name=EveningStandard>{{Cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html |title=Coronavirus news LIVE: Number of UK patients hits 16 as Northern Ireland confirms first case |date=27 February 2020 |work=standard.co.uk|access-date=27 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227203043/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html|archive-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Independent.ie>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/coronavirus-ireland-passengers-who-travelled-with-northern-irish-patient-traced-in-bid-to-prevent-outbreak-38997601.html |title=Coronavirus Ireland: Passengers who travelled with Northern Irish patient traced in bid to prevent outbreak |date=27 February 2020 |work=independent.ie|access-date=28 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228202902/https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/coronavirus-ireland-passengers-who-travelled-with-northern-irish-patient-traced-in-bid-to-prevent-outbreak-38997601.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, the first case in Wales was confirmed in a person who had returned from Northern Italy.<ref name=BBC>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068 |title=First case confirmed in Wales |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228153606/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Shankar4March2020>{{cite web |url=https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/ |title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel coronavirus pandemic in China \u2013 Public Health Wales |last=Shankar |first=Giri |date= |website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304175055/https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|archive-date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=PublicHealthWales>{{cite web |url=https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Latest information on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) \u2013 Public Health Wales |last= |first= |date= |website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229190227/https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=29 February 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, two further cases were confirmed in England, one of whom was a man who became the 20th case of COVID-19 in the UK and the first case who did not contract the disease from abroad. He was a resident in [[Surrey]] and registered at the Haslemere Health Centre, which had previously been closed for \"deep cleaning\".<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51683428.html |title=Coronavirus: Latest patient was first to be infected in UK |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=28 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229001409/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51683428.html|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, three further cases of the virus were confirmed, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 23, after 10,483 people had been tested.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Two of the three affected people had recently returned from Italy while the third had come back from Asia.<ref name=\"BBC29Feb2020\">{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51684624 |title=Three more cases of coronavirus in England |date=29 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229024922/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51684624|archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Scottish CMO, [[Catherine Calderwood]] announced that surveillance would begin at some hospitals and 41 GP surgeries in Scotland.<ref name=BBC1Mar2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868 |title=Surveillance testing system for Covid-19 begins |date=1 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301034710/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868|archive-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> Around 442,675 calls were made to the [[NHS 111|non-emergency line 111]] in the last week of February.<ref name=Discombe5March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/acute-care/medical-students-and-new-doctors-could-be-drafted-in-to-fight-coronavirus/7027060.article |title=Medical students and new doctors could be drafted in to fight coronavirus |last=Discombe |first=Matt |website=Health Service Journal |access-date=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Early to mid-March 2020===\n[[File:Looking for soap, Sainsbury's, north London 12_March_2020.jpg|thumb|upright|Soap almost sold out, London, 12 March]]\nOn 1 March, a further 13 cases were reported, adding [[Greater Manchester]] and Scotland to the list of areas affected and bringing the total to 36, three of which were believed to be contacts of the case in Surrey who had no history of travel abroad.<ref name=\"ITV1Mar2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/ |title=Twelve more people test positive for coronavirus bringing UK Covid-19 total to 35 |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301144252/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews1March2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html |title=Coronavirus: Twelve more cases confirmed in England |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=bbc.co.uk/news|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, four further people in England tested positive; all four had recently travelled from Italy.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The total number of UK cases was reported as being 39.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550 |title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150239/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, when the total number of confirmed cases in the UK stood at 51, the UK Government unveiled their ''Coronavirus Action Plan'', which outlined what the UK had done and what it planned to do next.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/>\n\nOn 4 March, the total number of confirmed cases increased to 85.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> On 5 March, three further cases in Scotland were announced.<ref name=gov.scotCOVID-19/> That day, the total number of confirmed cases in the UK was reported by officials as 115,<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> and a woman in her 70s with an existing medical condition, was reported to be the first fatality in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Woman in 70s becomes first virus fatality in UK' |date=5 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305174247/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> A further 48 cases were confirmed on 6 March,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-47-new-cases-confirmed-taking-uk-total-to-163-11950718 |title=Coronavirus: 48 new cases confirmed in UK's biggest daily jump \u2013 taking total to 164 |website=Sky News|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307191328/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-47-new-cases-confirmed-taking-uk-total-to-163-11950718|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the total being over 200 the next day,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-cases-number-206-locations-latest-a9384586.html |title=Coronavirus cases in UK rise to 206 today |date=7 March 2020 |website=The Independent|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308153244/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-cases-number-206-locations-latest-a9384586.html|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and adding a further 64 new cases on 8 March, the biggest increase in cases until that day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-latest-news-cases-update-covid-19-death-toll/ |title=Coronavirus latest news: UK case count rises by 64 as 273 test positive for the disease |first1=Verity |last1=Bowman |first2=Jordan |last2=Kelly-Linden |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=8 March 2020 |via=www.telegraph.co.uk|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121935/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-latest-news-cases-update-covid-19-death-toll/|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 March, the first three cases were discovered in [[Dorset]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/18291277.coronavirus-dorset-updates-developing-situation/|title=Coronavirus updates: three cases confirmed in Dorset and surgery closes|website=Bournemouth Echo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rationing notice, Sainsbury's north London.jpg|thumb|Some supermarkets began to limit purchases of items in high demand. 12 March.]]\nOn 10 March, it was announced that mental health minister [[Nadine Dorries|Nadine Dorries MP]] had tested positive for the virus and was self-isolating.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |date=10 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311153820/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51827356|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=HJ12March2020/> On 11 March, 83 more cases were discovered in the UK bringing the total to 456.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-11/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-wales-bringing-total-to-19/ |title=Four new coronavirus cases confirmed in Wales bringing the total to 19 |date=11 March 2020 |work=ITV News|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312133743/https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-11/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-wales-bringing-total-to-19/|archive-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the WHO declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]],<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\"/> and it was discussed in the [[Budget of the United Kingdom|UK government's annual budget]].<ref name=HJ12March2020/>\n\nOn 12 March, the total of cases in the UK was reported to be 590.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> On the same day, the UK CMOs raised the risk to the UK from moderate to high.<ref name=Gov.UK12March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/covid-19-government-announces-moving-out-of-contain-phase-and-into-delay |title=COVID-19: government announces moving out of contain phase and into delay |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316093859/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/covid-19-government-announces-moving-out-of-contain-phase-and-into-delay|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The government advised that anyone with a new continuous cough or a fever should self-isolate for seven days. Schools were asked to cancel trips abroad, and people over 70 and those with pre-existing medical conditions were advised to avoid cruises.<ref name=BBCNews12March2020/><ref name=Mahase13March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=13 March 2020 |title=Covid-19: UK holds off closing schools and restricts testing to people in hospital |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1060 |journal=British Medical Journal |language=en |volume=368 |pages=m1060 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m1060 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32169967 |via=|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317052257/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1060|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n[[File:Shopping in rubber gloves and a face mask Sainsbury's north Finchley London 15 March 2020 coronavirus COVID 19 scare.jpg|thumb|upright|Shopping in rubber gloves and a face mask, London, 15 March|alt=]]\n\nOn 13 March, the number of confirmed cases rose by 208 to 798,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberts |first=Lizzie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-news-uk-cases-delay-phase-self-isolate-latest-live/ |title=Coronavirus latest news: UK cases rise to 798, as Foreign Office tells Britons not to travel to Spain unless it is essential |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph|access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Davies |first2=Gareth |issn=0307-1235 |last3=Gartner |first3=Annelies |last4=Team |first4=Global Health Security|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313073312/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-news-uk-cases-delay-phase-self-isolate-latest-live/|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the first death from coronavirus being reported in Scotland.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |title=Coronavirus: Death of first Scottish patient with Covid-19 confirmed |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140926/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The UK Government restricted the export of three drugs being administered to COVID-19 patients in clinical trials in China: [[Kaletra]], [[Chloroquine|Chloroquine phosphate]], and [[Hydroxychloroquine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/comment/parallel-export-covid-19/|title=UK bans parallel export and hoarding of three Covid-19 drugs|last=GlobalData|first=Healthcare|date=13 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316203117/https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/comment/parallel-export-covid-19/|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany sporting fixtures, including the [[London Marathon]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313171937/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] Wales vs Scotland fixture,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313141835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and all [[Premier League]] and [[English Football League|EFL]] football games<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended in England \u2013 Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland halt games |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313111939/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> were postponed and the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections]] were postponed for a year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=English local elections postponed over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313194513/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[C2C: Country to Country|Country to Country music festival]], due to take place on 13-15 March in London, was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Freeman |first=Jon |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/c2c-festival-postponed-coronavirus-966263/ |title=C2C Festival Postponed Over Coronavirus Pandemic |work=Rolling Stone |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321171800/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/c2c-festival-postponed-coronavirus-966263/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, the [[Cheltenham Festival|Cheltenham National Hunt]] four-day racing festival on 10-13 March went ahead, attracting over 250,000 racegoers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/horse-racing/52164004|title=Shadow sports minister says there are 'serious questions' over why Cheltenham went ahead|date=2020-04-04|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the number of confirmed cases rose to 1,140 and the total number of people who had died in the UK had increased to 21.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51889957 |title=Coronavirus: UK deaths double in 24 hours |work=BBC News |date=14 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143746/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51889957|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]] announced that everyone in Britain over the age of 70 would be told to self-isolate \"within the coming weeks\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020 |work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315090139/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That day, the number of cases rose to 1,372 and the number of deaths increased to 35.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-15/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-rises-to-35-as-14-more-patients-die-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19/ |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 35 and cases of Covid-19 hits 1,372 as elderly face four months of self-isolation |work=ITV News |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315164212/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-15/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-rises-to-35-as-14-more-patients-die-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19/ |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the UK death toll rose to 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182658/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The deaths included the first to be reported in Wales.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |title=Coronavirus in Wales: First Covid-19 death confirmed |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316140423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also on 16 March, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] advised everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and would be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/> On the same day, a second MP, [[Kate Osborne]], tested positive after a period of self-isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-51906813 |title=Second MP diagnosed with coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=18 March 2020 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317213024/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-51906813|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/kate-osborne-coronavirus-labour-mp-second-nadine-dorries-a9403786.html |title=Labour MP is second to test positive for coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/kate-osborne-coronavirus-labour-mp-second-nadine-dorries-a9403786.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-labour-mp-kate-osborne-reveals-she-is-infected-with-call-to-band-together-11958194 |title=Coronavirus: Labour MP Kate Osborne reveals she is infected with call to 'band together' |website=Sky News |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-labour-mp-kate-osborne-reveals-she-is-infected-with-call-to-band-together-11958194|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/labours-kate-osborne-becomes-second-mp-to-test-positive-for-coronavirus |title=Labour's Kate Osborne becomes second MP to test positive for coronavirus |date=17 March 2020 |website=Politics Home |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/labours-kate-osborne-becomes-second-mp-to-test-positive-for-coronavirus|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Elderly shopping hour at New Barnet Sainsbury's.jpg|thumb|Supermarkets introduced early shopping hours for the elderly and vulnerable]]\nOn 17 March, [[NHS England]] announced that all non-urgent operations in England would be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317152225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also on 17 March, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Rishi Sunak]] announced that \u00a3330bn would be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317174307/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On that day the UK death toll rose to 71, while the number of confirmed cases increased to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317203339/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |title=Coronavirus: 14 more deaths in England \u2013 UK total now 71 |publisher=Sky UK |work=Sky News |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173124/https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the government provided a \u00a33.2million emergency support package to help rough sleepers into accommodation.<ref name=homeless>{{cite news |last=Faleiro |first=Sonia |title=How do you self-isolate when you live on the street? |newspaper=politico.eu |location=United Kingdom |pages= |language=English |publisher=politico |date=22 March 2020 |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-homeless-self-isolation/| access-date = 26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=homeless2>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-local-government |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): guidance for local government |last= |first= |date=17 March 2020 |website=gov.co.uk}}</ref> With complex physical and mental health needs, in general, [[Homelessness in the United Kingdom|homeless people]] are at a significant risk of catching the virus.<ref name=homeless/>\n\nOn 18 March, MP [[Lloyd Russell-Moyle]] announced that he had tested positive for with the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-51952997 |title=Coronavirus: MP Lloyd Russell-Moyle tests positive for Covid-19 |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318230404/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-51952997|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. Boris Johnson made a statement on his daily briefing, announcing that all schools in the UK were to close on Friday to everyone except those who have parents with important jobs that they can't do from home. On 19 March, the first death was confirmed in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-03-19/first-coronavirus-death-in-northern-ireland/ |title=First coronavirus death in Northern Ireland |work=ITV News |date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319201706/https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-03-19/first-coronavirus-death-in-northern-ireland/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Ministry of Defence also announced the formation of the COVID Support Force, enabling the military to support public services and civilian authorities in tackling the outbreak.<ref name=\"Rescript1\">{{cite news |title=Military stands up COVID Support Force |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/military-stands-up-covid-support-force |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=GOV.UK |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160303/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/military-stands-up-covid-support-force |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two military operations were also announced: [[Operation Rescript]], which focuses on the outbreak in the United Kingdom; and Operation Broadshare, which focuses on British military activities overseas.<ref name=\"Rescript2\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Up to 20,000 troops on standby to help deal with COVID-19 outbreak |url= https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-up-to-20-000-troops-on-standby-to-help-deal-with-covid-19-outbreak-11959977 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319234118/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-up-to-20-000-troops-on-standby-to-help-deal-with-covid-19-outbreak-11959977 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Late March 2020===\n[[File:NEXT Enfield still trading during the Coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Next closed its 700 stores on 23 March, having previously traded with warning notices about the virus]]\nOn 20 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson requested the closure of pubs, restaurants, gyms, entertainment venues, museums and galleries that evening, though with some regret saying \"We\u2019re taking away the ancient, inalienable right of free-born people of the United Kingdom to go to the pub\".<ref name=telegraph-20200320>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/20/boris-johnson-announces-extraordinary-closure-uks-pubs-restaurants/ |title=Boris Johnson announces 'extraordinary' closure of UK's pubs and restaurants in coronavirus shutdown |last=Mendick |first=Robert |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=guardian-20200411>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/apr/11/coronavirus-exposed-myth-british-exceptionalism |title=Coronavirus has exposed the myth of British exceptionalism |last=O\u2019Toole |first=Fintan |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 April 2020 |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency]] announced that all pending practical and driving theory tests were to be postponed, for at least 3 months in the case of practical tests, and up to and including 20 April for theory tests. All candidates were to receive notification of when their tests were rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-driving-tests-and-theory-tests |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): driving tests and theory tests |website=GOV.UK |language=en|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200321011055/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-driving-tests-and-theory-tests|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motoringresearch.com/car-news/driving-tests-cancelled-coronavirus/ |title=Driving tests CANCELLED due to coronavirus |last=Braithwaite-Smith |first=Gavin |date=20 March 2020 |website=Motoring Research |language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200321011100/https://www.motoringresearch.com/car-news/driving-tests-cancelled-coronavirus/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the UK death toll reached 281, including what was reported to be the virus's youngest British victim so far, an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, [[Next (retailer)|Next]] was the latest retailer to announce that it was temporarily closing its 700 stores due to the pandemic. It predicted a \u00a31bn loss in revenue due to the virus.<ref>[https://www.marketingweek.com/morrisons-next-coronavirus-5-things-that-mattered-this-week-and-why/ Morrisons, Next, coronavirus: 5 things that mattered this week and why] ''www.marketingweek.com'' accessed 25 March 2020</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/19/next-facing-unprecedented-crisis-as-firms-warn-of-coronavirus-fallout |title=Next warns of unprecedented high street crisis over coronavirus |work=The Guardian |date=}}</ref> On the same day, [[Downing Street]] confirmed [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom|Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] would act in place of Prime Minister Boris Johnson if he became \"incapacitated\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-boris-johnson-dominic-raab-prime-minister-a9418246.html |title=Dominic Raab to become acting PM if Boris Johnson incapacitated due to coronavirus |date=23 March 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Boris Johnson announced in a television broadcast that measures to mitigate the virus were to be tightened further in order to protect the NHS, with wide-ranging restrictions made on freedom of movement, [[Coronavirus Act 2020|enforceable in law]],<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23/> for a planned \"lockdown\" period intended to last for at least three weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-23/boris-johnson-downing-street-coronavirus-update/ |title=Boris Johnson orders three-week lockdown of UK to tackle coronavirus spread |website=ITV News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The government directed people to stay at home throughout this period except for essential purchases, essential work travel (if remote work was not possible), medical needs, one exercise per day (alone or with household members), and providing care for others.<ref name=PM-address-in-full-2020-03-23>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full |title=Boris Johnson's address to the nation in full |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323204915/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many other non-essential activities, including all public gatherings and social events except funerals, were prohibited, with many categories of retail businesses ordered to be closed.<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-businesses-and-premises-to-close |title=Further businesses and premises to close |website=GOV.UK |language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] closed on 24 March, with plans to reconvene on 1 April to discuss emergency legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-52018354 |title=FMQs cancelled as Holyrood chamber shuts for a week |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The [[National Assembly for Wales]] closed to the public on 17 March, it reconvened on 1 April using 'Zoom', for a virtual 'emergency [[Senedd Cymru|Senedd]]' meeting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assembly.wales/en/newhome/pages/newsitem.aspx?itemid=2092|title=Plenary meetings continue, but Senedd buildings will stay closed until June|website=National Assembly for Wales|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] reduced it's workload by suspending all non-essential Assembly business on 18 March, it closed to the public on 19 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/news-and-media/press-releases/session-2019--2020/assembly-business-and-covid-19/|title=Assembly Business and Covid-19|website=www.niassembly.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> From the 7 April it held Ad-hoc COVID-19 Response Committees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/news-and-media/press-releases/session-2019--2020/speaker-announces-new-ad-hoc-covid-19-response-committee-meeting/|title=Speaker Announces New Ad-Hoc COVID-19 Response Committee Meeting|website=www.niassembly.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] closed on 25 March, with the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker]] and the [[Leader of the House of Commons|Leader of the House]] hopeful to set up a 'virtual parliament' by 21 April.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52032188 |title=Parliament expected to close on Wednesday evening |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/01/uk-set-up-virtual-parliament-during-coronavirus-shutdown|title=UK to set up virtual parliament during coronavirus shutdown|date=2020-04-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, it was announced that NHS England would establish a [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|temporary critical care hospital]], [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], in the [[Excel London]] conference centre.<ref name=\"bbc_52018477\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477 |title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital |date=24 March 2010 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Also on 24 March, it was reported that NHS Wales were looking at the [[Principality Stadium]] in Cardiff for a similar purpose.<ref name=\"itv_2020-03-25\">{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-25/principality-stadium-could-be-used-by-welsh-nhs-to-tackle-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Principality Stadium could be used by NHS Wales to tackle coronavirus outbreak |date=25 March 2020 |work=ITV News}}</ref> On 25 March, it was confirmed that NHS Scotland had identified Glasgow's [[SEC Centre]] exhibition and conference facility as a potential site for a similar hospital in Scotland.<ref name=\"bbc_52045977\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52045977 |title=Coronavirus: NHS field hospital plans for Scotland |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref> On 26 March it was reported that the Northern Ireland health service was also looking for potential sites to use for temporary hospitals.<ref name=\"bt_20200327\">{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/plans-for-field-hospitals-for-coronavirus-patients-in-ni-39079578.html |title=Plans for field hospitals for coronavirus patients in NI |last1=Young |first1=David |last2=Black |first2=Rebecca |work=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref> On 27 March, NHS England announced that they would be establishing more [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals]] in major conference centres to help to deal with the large number of cases expected.<ref name=\"ITV-2020-03-27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/birmingham-nec-and-manchester-central-convention-complex-to-be-converted-into-coronavirus-hospitals |title=Two more UK facilities to be converted into 'NHS Nightingale' coronavirus hospitals |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to official data released on 24 March, there had been 87 new coronavirus deaths in the previous 24 hours, bringing the total number of deaths to 422.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK coronavirus death toll jumps to 422 after biggest daily increase |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/coronavirus-deaths-uk/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, British diplomat [[Steven Dick]], deputy ambassador to Hungary, died in Budapest after contracting the virus.<ref name=\"Walker\">{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=British diplomat dies of coronavirus in Hungary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/25/british-diplomat-dies-of-coronavirus-in-hungary |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced the police would be given the power to use \"reasonable force\" to enforce the regulations.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Police |first=Vikram Dodd |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-lockdown-will-be-imposed-by-force-in-england |title=England: police to get power to use force to impose coronavirus lockdown |date=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=correspondent |first2=crime |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The first two working NHS doctors died from COVID-19 on the same day, one a GP, the other a surgeon.<ref name=\"NHSDied\">{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Victoria |last2=Lyons |first2=Izzy |title=These are the NHS workers who have died from coronavirus |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/03/nhs-staff-died-coronavirus-frontline-workers-victims/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=4 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404214732/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/03/nhs-staff-died-coronavirus-frontline-workers-victims/ |archivedate=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the number of UK coronavirus deaths jumped by more than 100 in a day for the first time, rising to 578, while a total of 11,568 had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52056534 |title=UK virus deaths rise by more than 100 in a day |work=BBC News |date=26 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At 8pm that day, people from across the UK took part in [[Clap for our Carers|national applause in appreciation of health workers]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bowman |first=Verity |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/26/thank-nhs-tonights-clap-carers/ |title=Clap For Our Carers: How thousands of Britons thanked the NHS with a national round of applause |date=26 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-03-26 |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> This applause was repeated the following week.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52130552 |title=Coronavirus: Applause for key workers rings out across the UK |date=2 April 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-03-02 |language=en-GB }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Belfast COVID19 Traffic Management Sign.jpg|thumb|Electronic display sign normally used for traffic management displays COVID19-related advices on an almost deserted Chichester Street in Belfast City Centre, 24 March.]]\nOn 27 March, Boris Johnson and Matt Hancock announced that they had tested positive for the virus.<ref name=Boris>{{cite news |title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/27/health-secretary-matt-hancock-tests-positive-coronavirus-12466332/ |title=Coronavirus strikes heart of Government as PM and health secretary test positive |work=Metro |date=27 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Labour MP [[Angela Rayner]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]], confirmed she had been suffering symptoms and was self-isolating.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/ |title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating |work=ITV News |date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Chief Medical Adviser Chris Whitty also reported suffering from symptoms and would be self-isolating, while continuing to advise the UK government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Chief medical officer Chris Whitty self-isolates with symptoms |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-chief-medical-officer-chris-whitty-self-isolates-with-symptoms-11964697 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Sky News |date=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> That day also saw the largest increase in the number of deaths, with the figure rising by 181 from the previous day, bringing the total to 759, while 14,579 cases had been confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-cases-uk-how-many-covid-19-a9430221.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 759 |date=27 March 2020 |website=The Independent}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Royal Mint]] announced that it was manufacturing medical visors for medical staff working during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-royalmint-idUSKBN21E2XK |title=UK's Royal Mint making coronavirus protective gear for health staff |date=27 March 2020 |work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-27 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-27/royal-mint-makes-medical-visors-to-protect-nhs-staff-from-coronavirus/ |title=Royal Mint makes medical visors to help protect NHS staff from coronavirus |website=ITV News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The National Police Chiefs' Council said police had issued their first fines for people breaking lockdown rules. The [[fixed penalty notice]]s are \u00a360 but will be reduced to \u00a330 if paid within 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/police-issue-fines-for-breach-of-coronavirus-lockdown-rules-as-visitors-warned-off-tourist-hotspots/ |title=Police issue first fines for breach of coronavirus lockdown rules as visitors warned off tourist hotspots |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the [[Scottish Secretary]] [[Alister Jack]] announced that he was self-isolating after experiencing coronavirus symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-scottish-secretary-alister-jack-self-isolating-after-showing-symptoms-11965001 |title=Coronavirus: Scottish Secretary Alister Jack self-isolating after showing symptoms |website=Sky News}}</ref> A further 260 deaths also took the number of fatalities past 1,000, with a total of 1,019 deaths having occurred so far, and 17,089 people having tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52077997 |title=Number of UK coronavirus deaths rises above 1,000 |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> That evening, new regulations came into force in Northern Ireland giving authorities the power to force businesses to close, and impose fines on them if they refused, as well as on people leaving their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\". The measures, introduced by the [[Northern Ireland Executive]], brought Northern Ireland into line with the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=New NI Covid-19 regulations come into force |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-28/new-regulations-to-enforce-coronavirus-restrictions-agreed-by-stormont/ |title=Northern Ireland imposes fines up to \u00a35,000 for those breaching social distancing rules |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Social distancing queueing for the supermarket J. Sainsbury's north London Coronavirus Covid 19 pandemic - 30 March 2020.jpg|thumb|Social distancing while queueing to enter a British supermarket 30 March 2020]]\nOn 29 March, it was reported that the government would send a letter to 30 million households warning that things would \"get worse before they get better\" and that tighter restrictions could be implemented if necessary. The letter would also be accompanied by a leaflet setting out the government's lockdown rules along with health information.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52079922 |title=Things to get worse, PM says in letter to Britons |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Dr [[Jenny Harries]], England's deputy chief medical officer, suggested it could be six months before life could return to \"normal\", because social distancing measures would have to be reduced \"gradually\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52084517|title=Six months before UK life 'returns to normal'|work=BBC News|date=29 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The first NHS nurse died of COVID-19.<ref name=\"NHSDied\"/>\n\nOn 30 March, [[Dominic Cummings]], the [[10 Downing Street|Prime Minister's Chief Adviser]], was reported to be self-isolating after experiencing coronavirus symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rajeev Syal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/30/dominic-cummings-self-isolates-after-experiencing-coronavirus-symptoms |title=Dominic Cummings self-isolates after experiencing coronavirus symptoms &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> As the number of reported deaths rose to 1,408, Sir [[Patrick Vallance]], the UK's chief scientific adviser said that there were early signs social distancing measures were \"making a difference\". Transmission of the virus within the community was thought to be decreasing, and hospital admission data suggested cases were not rising as fast as anticipated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52096049|title=Coronavirus: UK measures 'making a difference'|first=Michelle|last=Roberts|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Dominic Raab announced an arrangement between the government and major UK airlines to fly home tens of thousands of British nationals who had been stranded abroad by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52099252|title=Rescue flights for stranded Britons|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March the largest UK death toll of the outbreak so far was reported, with 381 deaths taking the total to 1,789.<ref name=youngest>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52114476|title=13-year-old boy dies with coronavirus|date=31 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Early April 2020 ===\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:UK Government correspondence on Coronavirus in English.jpg|thumb|A letter sent by the Prime Minister to every household in the UK along with government guidance on coronavirus, 3 April.|alt=]]\nOn 1 April, the government confirmed that a total of 2,000 NHS staff had been tested for coronavirus since the outbreak began, but Cabinet Office Minister Michael Gove said a shortage of chemical reagents needed for the test meant it was not possible to screen the NHS's 1.2 million workforce.<ref name=\"BBC52122761\"/> Gove's statement was contradicted by the [[Chemical Industries Association]], which said there was not a shortage of the relevant chemicals and that at a meeting with a business minister the week before the government had not tried to find out about potential supply problems.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=Robert |authorlink1=Robert Peston |title=Robert Peston: Is Michael Gove right that there is a shortage of coronavirus test kit ingredients? |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401160117/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-31/robert-peston-is-gove-right-that-there-is-a-shortage-of-test-kit-ingredients/ |archivedate=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 April the number of deaths was confirmed to have increased by 563 to 2,362, while a total of 29,474 cases had been diagnosed, 4,324 over the previous 24 hours.<ref name=\"BBC52122761\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52122761|title=PM vows more virus tests as UK deaths exceed 2,000|date=1 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Health Secretary Matt Hancock, after his seven-day period of isolation, announced a \"five pillar\" plan for testing people for the virus, with the aim of conducting 100,000 tests a day by the end of April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52140376|title=Hancock aims for 100,000 tests a day by May|date=2 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> At 8pm on 2 April the UK gave another national round of applause for NHS staff and other key workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-52143223/clap-for-carers-uk-applauds-nhs-staff-and-key-workers|title=Clap for Carers: UK applauds key workers|date=2 April 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nWith warm weather forecast for some areas during the upcoming weekend, on 3 April Hancock warned people to stay at home, telling them this was an instruction \"not a request\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52155430 |title=Coronavirus: Staying home this weekend 'not a request', UK told |work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> On 4 April it was announced that a five-year-old had died from the virus, believed to be the youngest victim to date.<ref name=youngest0404/> The death total was reported as 4,313, having risen by 708 from the previous day's figure. Michael Gove dismissed a growing [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conspiracy theory]] that COVID-19 was spread by [[5G]] wireless networks \u2014 leading to the vandalism and torching of several cell towers. He argued that this theory was \"dangerous nonsense\"; mobile operator [[Vodafone]] considered the vandalism a matter of national security.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Faulconbridge |first1=Guy |last2=Holton |first2=Kate |title=5G coronavirus conspiracy theory is dangerous fake nonsense, UK says |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-5g/5g-coronavirus-conspiracy-theory-is-dangerous-fake-nonsense-uk-says-idUSKBN21M0MS |work=Reuters |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=youngest0404>{{cite news |title=Five-year-old child becomes youngest known coronavirus victim as people are urged to stay home |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-04/coronavirus-deaths-total-up-to-4-313-after-further-708-die/ |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=4 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404162630/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-04/coronavirus-deaths-total-up-to-4-313-after-further-708-die/ |archivedate=4 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] [[Royal_address_to_the_nation#Elizabeth_II|addressed the nation]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she had done on only four previous occasions (except for the [[Royal Christmas Message]] and her [[diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Diamond Jubilee]]). She thanked people for following the government's social distancing rules and paid tribute to key workers, and said the UK would succeed in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> That day, Boris Johnson was admitted to hospital as a \"precautionary measure\" after suffering from symptoms for more than a week with no improvement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> [[Catherine Calderwood]], Scotland's chief medical officer, resigned from her post after it emerged she had been spoken to by police for visiting her second home during lockdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52177171 |title=Coronavirus: Scotland's chief medical officer resigns over lockdown trip |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Boris Johnson was moved to the intensive care unit at [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in London as his symptoms worsened. Dominic Raab assumed Johnson's duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-06/prime-minister-boris-johnson-moved-to-intensive-care-after-being-admitted-to-hospital-with-coronavirus/ |title=Prime Minister Boris Johnson moved to intensive care after being admitted to hospital with coronavirus |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April the number of reported deaths increased by 786, taking the total to 6,159. The figure compared with 439 deaths for the previous day. Sir Patrick Vallance, the government's chief scientific adviser, said that the figures were not accelerating as had been predicted but that it was too early to tell whether the outbreak was peaking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52206510|title=UK cases 'could be moving in the right direction'|work=BBC News|date=7 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-britain-curve-idUSS8N2BU035|title=UK coronavirus cases not accelerating but too early to call a peak - chief science adviser|newspaper=Reuters|date=7 April 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, [[Mark Drakeford]], the [[First Minister of Wales]], confirmed the [[Welsh Government]] would extend the lockdown beyond the initial three-week period for Wales.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52215421 Coronavirus: Lockdown in Wales to be extended next week] 8 April 2020, ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref> On that day a further 938 deaths were reported in the UK, taking the total to 7,097.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52221724 Coronavirus: Boris Johnson 'improving' as intensive care treatment continues] 8 April 2020, ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Sunak announced \u00a3750m of government spending to help small charities.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52221402 Coronavirus: Chancellor announces aid for charities] 8 April 2020, ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref>\n\nOn 9 April the number of recorded deaths increased by 881, taking the total to 7,978. Dominic Raab said the UK was \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it was \"too early\" to lift them, and urged people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|work=BBC News|date=9 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> With warm weather forecast again for Easter, this message was echoed by police and tourist destinations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52219250|title=Easter warnings from police, parks and councils|work=BBC News|date=9 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Boris Johnson was moved out of intensive care, but remained in hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|work=BBC News|date=9 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At 8pm on 9 April the nation staged a third round of applause for NHS staff and other key workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-nhs-clap-for-our-carers-video-charity-time-a9458606.html|title=Nation applauds NHS workers fighting coronavirus for third week running|date=9 April 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April the UK recorded another 980 deaths taking the total to 8,958. [[Jonathan Van-Tam]], England's deputy chief medical officer, told the government's daily briefing the lockdown was \"beginning to pay off\" but the UK was still in a \"dangerous situation\", and although [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in London|cases in London]] had started to drop they were still rising in Yorkshire and the North East.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/10/number-people-hospital-beds-london-drops-12540759/ | title=Number of people in hospital beds in London drops| date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Matt Hancock told the briefing a \"Herculean effort\" was being made to ensure daily deliveries of [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) to frontline workers, including the establishment of a domestic manufacturing industry to produce the equipment. Fifteen drive-through centres had also been opened around the UK to test frontline workers.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52248423 |title = 'Herculean effort' to provide NHS protective gear|work = BBC News|date = 10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April the number of reported deaths increased by 917, taking the total to 9,875. After some NHS workers said they still did not have the correct personal protective equipment to treat patients, [[Home Secretary]] [[Priti Patel]] told that day's Downing Street briefing she was \"sorry if people feel there have been failings\" in providing kit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52256169|title=917 new coronavirus deaths as UK told to stay home|work=BBC News|date=11 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The Queen released an Easter message, the first time she had done so, in which she spoke of hope and said \"coronavirus will not overcome us\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52255054|title='We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen|work=BBC News|date=11 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nBoris Johnson left hospital on Sunday 12 April.<ref name=\"Mason-12Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |title=Boris Johnson leaves hospital as he continues recovery from coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/12/boris-johnson-leaves-hospital-as-he-continues-recovery-from-coronavirus |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Guardian |date=12 April 2020}}</ref> On that day a further 737 coronavirus-related deaths were reported, taking the total past 10,000 to 10,612. Matt Hancock described it as a \"sombre day\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |date=12 April 2020 |work=BBC News |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 April the number of reported deaths increased by 717 to 11,329. Dominic Raab told the Downing Street briefing the government did not expect to make any immediate changes to the lockdown restrictions and that the UK's plan \"is working\" but that \"we are still not past the peak of this virus\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52273774|title='Don't expect changes to UK virus lockdown yet'|date=13 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Testing and surveillance==\n[[File:Doctor's surgery entrance north London.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Warning notices at a London doctor's surgery, 13 March 2020]]\nShortly after confirming that the cause of the cluster of [[pneumonia]] in [[Wuhan]] was a new coronavirus, Chinese authorities had shared its genetic sequence for international developments of diagnostic kits.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\"/> By 10 January,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-britain-modelling-idUKKCN21R2UF|title=UK defends coronavirus response after Reuters investigation|date=2020-04-09|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-12|url-status=live|language=en|quote=After developing a test for the new virus by Jan. 10}}</ref> the UK had developed a prototype specific laboratory test for the new disease, performed on a sample from the nose, throat, and respiratory tract and tested at PHE's Colindale laboratories in London.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> Testing of patients began within days,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51221915|title='Increased likelihood' of China virus reaching UK|date=23 January 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=30 March 2020|language=en-GB|postscript=none}}; {{Cite web|url=https://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/news-and-analysis/news/phe-tells-patients-with-suspected-coronavirus-to-call-gp-or-nhs-111/20207619.article|title=PHE tells patients with suspected coronavirus to call GP or NHS 111|date=27 January 2020|publisher=The Pharmaceutical Journal|language=en|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> and by 3 February 326 tests had been performed in the UK.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Over the following few weeks, PHE made the test available to 12 other laboratories in the UK, making it possible to test 1,000 people a day.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/phe-novel-coronavirus-diagnostic-test-rolled-out-across-uk|title=PHE novel coronavirus diagnostic test rolled out across UK|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nFollowing 300 staff being asked to work from home on 26 February 2020 in London, while a suspected person was awaiting a test result for the virus, PHE announced it was to increase surveillance by widening testing around the UK to include people with flu-like symptoms at 100 GP surgeries and eight hospitals: the [[Royal Brompton and Harefield NHS Foundation Trust|Royal Brompton and Harefield]], [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust|Guy's and St Thomas']] and [[Addenbrookes Hospital]], as well as hospitals at [[Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust|Brighton and Sussex]], [[Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust|Nottingham]], [[University Hospital of South Manchester NHS Foundation Trust|South Manchester]], [[Sheffield Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|Sheffield]], [[University Hospitals of Leicester NHS Trust|Leicester]].<ref name=BBC26Feb2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51641243 |title=Hundreds of flu patients to get coronavirus tests |date=26 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227000207/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51641243|archive-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=PHE27Feb2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-surveillance-system-for-early-detection-of-covid-19 |title=New surveillance system for early detection of COVID-19 |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227080745/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-surveillance-system-for-early-detection-of-covid-19|archive-date=27 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> Surveillance was shortly extended to some hospitals and GP surgeries in Scotland.<ref name=BBC1Mar2020/>\n\nDrive-through screening centres were set up by Central London Community Healthcare NHS Trust at Parsons Green Health Centre on 24 February 2020,<ref name=\"clch29Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://clch.nhs.uk/about-us/news/parsons-green-drive-through-swabbing-hub-covid-19 |title=Central London Community Healthcare NHS Trust :: Parsons Green drive through swabbing hub for Covid-19 |website=clch.nhs.uk|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229015242/https://clch.nhs.uk/about-us/news/parsons-green-drive-through-swabbing-hub-covid-19|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and by NHS Lothian at the [[Western General Hospital]] in Edinburgh.<ref name=\"BBCSct29Feb2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51678008 |title=Drive-through coronavirus tests begin in Scotland |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229033108/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51678008|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further drive-through testing station was set up by the [[Sheffield Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]] at a site just off the [[A57 road|A57]] [[Sheffield Parkway]] dual-carriageway on 10 March; in this case, patients ringing NHS 111 with coronavirus-like symptoms in the [[Sheffield]] area will be told to drive, if possible, to the testing centre at an allotted time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-03-10/drive-through-centre-set-up-to-test-for-coronavirus-in-sheffield/|title=Drive through centre set up to test for coronavirus in Sheffield|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320200915/https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-03-10/drive-through-centre-set-up-to-test-for-coronavirus-in-sheffield/|archive-date=20 March 2020|date=10 March 2020|website=www.itv.com|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March NHS England announced that testing in NHS laboratories would increase from testing 1,500 to 10,000 per day.<ref name=HJ12March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/daily-insight/daily-insight-budget-day-maths/7027096.article |title=Daily Insight: Budget day maths |last= |first= |date= |website=Health Service Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316055806/https://www.hsj.co.uk/daily-insight/daily-insight-budget-day-maths/7027096.article|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The test consists of taking a sample from the nose, throat, deeper lung samples, blood or stool, and transporting the packed samples to the listed PHE regional laboratory designated for the referring laboratory region.<ref name=Gov.ukTesting>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-guidance-for-clinical-diagnostic-laboratories/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-who-to-call-to-request-laboratory-testing |title=COVID-19: how to arrange laboratory testing |website=GOV.UK|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215201/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-guidance-for-clinical-diagnostic-laboratories/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-who-to-call-to-request-laboratory-testing|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=nhs.ukTesting>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/common-questions/ |title=Common questions about coronavirus (COVID-19) |date=24 February 2020 |website=nhs.uk|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301190454/https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/common-questions/|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 12/13 March 2020, 29,764 tests had been conducted in the UK, corresponding to 450.8 tests per million people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing|author=Esteban Ortiz-Ospina|title=How many tests for COVID-19 are being performed around the world?|url-status=dead<!--Not actually dead, article gone!-->|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314010612/https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing|archive-date=14 March 2020|date=13 March 2020|website=ourworldindata.org|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March, Matt Hancock said the government had bought 3.5m kits that would test if a person has already had COVID-19; no date was given for their arrival. These tests would allow people to know if they were immune and therefore able to \"go back to work\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Sarah |title=Matt Hancock: 3.5m coronavirus test kits on way to NHS |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/24/matt-hancock-35m-coronavirus-test-kits-are-on-the-way-to-the-nhs |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401095649/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/24/matt-hancock-35m-coronavirus-test-kits-are-on-the-way-to-the-nhs|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Hancock announced on 28 March that 10,000 tests a day were now being processed; the actual figure was 5,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merrick |first1=Rob |title=Coronavirus: UK's failure to carry out mass testing condemned by former WHO director |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-testing-cases-deaths-who-germany-update-a9437126.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401134722/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-testing-cases-deaths-who-germany-update-a9437126.html |archivedate=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Woodcock |first1=Andrew |title=Coronavirus testing still below daily target despite government claim milestone passed |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-testing-uk-daily-target-nhs-cases-latest-a9434496.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401142538/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-testing-uk-daily-target-nhs-cases-latest-a9434496.html |archivedate=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 31 March, 143,186 people had been tested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|title=Number of coronavirus (COVID-19) cases and risk in the UK|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\nThe government and Public Health England were criticised for what some saw as a failure to organise mass testing. On 28 March the editor-in-chief of ''[[The Lancet]]'' published a condemnation of what he saw as government inaction and ignoring of WHO advice.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Horton |first1=Richard |authorlink1=Richard Horton (editor) |title=Offline: COVID-19 and the NHS\u2014\"a national scandal\" |journal=[[The Lancet]] |date=March 2020 |volume=395 |issue=10229 |page=1022 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30727-3 |pmid=32222186 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30727-3/fulltext |accessdate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330213137/https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30727-3/fulltext|archive-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live|doi-access=free }}</ref> On 31 March former WHO director [[Anthony Costello]], following WHO advice that countries should \"test, test, test\", said the key to the UK transitioning out of lockdown was mass testing, and that the UK had the capacity to reach the level of testing being carried out by Germany (70,000 tests a day, compared to the UK's 5,000), but that the government and [[Public Health England]] (PHE) had been too slow and controlling to organise.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Oli |title=Coronavirus testing crisis: Ex-WHO chief exposes UK failure as 44 testing labs sit unused |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1262707/Coronavirus-UK-testing-news-WHO-lockdown-labs-Boris-Johnson-PHE-NHS |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=31 March 2020 |archivedate=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401122745/https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1262707/Coronavirus-UK-testing-news-WHO-lockdown-labs-Boris-Johnson-PHE-NHS|url-status=live}}</ref> The day after, Conservative MP [[Jeremy Hunt]], chair of the [[Health and Social Care Select Committee]] and former Health Secretary, said it was \"very worrying\" that the government had not introduced mass testing because doing so had been \"internationally proven as the most effective way of breaking the chain of transmission\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Hospitals urged to use lab space to test NHS staff |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52114719 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401144932/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52114719 |archivedate=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 April, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reported one of the Government's top science advisers, [[Graham Medley]], claiming that \"mass public testing has never been our strategy for any pandemic.\" Medley also stated that the Government \"didn't want to invest millions of pounds into something that is about preparedness.\"<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/02/exclusive-systematic-failures-governments-pandemic-strategy/ 'Exclusive: The systematic failures in the Government's pandemic strategy laid bare'], ''The Telegraph'', 2/4/20.</ref>\n\n==Forecasting==\n[[File:Social distancing at the pharmacy Cockfosters London 23_March_2020.jpg|thumb|[[Social distancing]] at a London pharmacy, 23 March 2020]]\nReports from the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council's]] Centre for Global Infectious Disease Analysis at [[Imperial College]], London have been providing mathematically calculated estimates of cases and case fatality rates.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020>{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=10 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus: NHS staff get power to keep patients in isolation as UK declares \"serious threat\" |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550 |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=368 |pages=m550 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m550 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32041792|url-access=subscription|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191051/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Imperial2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/mrc-global-infectious-disease-analysis/news--wuhan-coronavirus/ |title=COVID-19 reports {{!}} Faculty of Medicine {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=www.imperial.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125095230/http://www.imperial.ac.uk/mrc-global-infectious-disease-analysis/news--wuhan-coronavirus/|archive-date=25 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> In February, the team at Imperial, led by epidemiologist [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]], estimated about two-thirds of cases in travellers from China were not detected and that some of these may have begun \"chains of transmission within the countries they entered.\"<ref name=Imperial24Feb20>{{cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/195564/two-thirds-covid-19-cases-exported-from-mainland/ |title=Two thirds of COVID-19 cases exported from mainland China may be undetected {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306033332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/195564/two-thirds-covid-19-cases-exported-from-mainland/|archive-date=6 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=NewSci>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2234967-covid-19-our-chance-to-contain-the-coronavirus-may-already-be-over/  |title=Covid-19: Our chance to contain the coronavirus may already be over |last=MacKenzie |first=Debora |date= |website=New Scientist |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200226201356/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2234967-covid-19-our-chance-to-contain-the-coronavirus-may-already-be-over/ |archive-date=26 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=JapanTimes26Feb20>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/26/world/science-health-world/covid-19-global-monitoring/ |title=COVID-19 strains global monitoring systems to the extreme |date=26 February 2020 |work=The Japan Times|access-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live |issn=0447-5763}}</ref> They forecast that the new coronavirus could infect up to 60% of the UK's population, in the worst-case scenario.<ref name=\"Petter2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-valentines-day-hugging-kissing-symptoms-outbreak-a9332976.html |title=Prevent spread of coronavirus on with 'less hugging and kissing', says virologist |last=Petter |first=Olivia |date=13 February 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200214165034/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-valentines-day-hugging-kissing-symptoms-outbreak-a9332976.html |archive-date=14 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a paper, the Imperial team provided detailed forecasts of the potential impacts of the epidemic in the UK and US.<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\" /><ref name=\"Independent200317\">{{cite news |last1=Lintern |first1=Shaun |title=World holds its breath and looks to China for clues on what coronavirus pandemic does next |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-china-imperial-college-scientists-modelling-a9405771.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140137/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-china-imperial-college-scientists-modelling-a9405771.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> It details the potential outcomes of an array of 'non-pharmaceutical interventions'. Two potential overall strategies outlined were: mitigation, in which the aim is to reduce the health impact of the epidemic but not to stop transmission completely; and suppression, where the aim is to reduce transmission rates to a point where case numbers fall. Until this point government actions had been based on a strategy of mitigation, but the modelling predicted that while this would reduce deaths by approximately 2/3, it would still lead to approximately 250,000 deaths from the disease and the health systems becoming overwhelmed.<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\" /> On the same day as the report was released, the Prime Minister announced in a press conference significant changes to the government advice, extending self isolation to whole households, advising social distancing particularly for vulnerable groups, and indicating that further measures were likely to be required in the future.<ref name=avoid/><ref name=\"Independent200317\" /> A paper on 30 March by Imperial estimated that the lockdown would reduce the number of dead from 510,000 to less than 20,000.<ref>[https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-Europe-estimates-and-NPI-impact-30-03-2020.pdf COVID19 Europe estimates and NPI impact] Neil Ferguson, Imperial College London</ref>\n\nIn April, biostatistician Professor [[Sheila Bird]] said that delays in the reporting of deaths from the virus mean that there is a risk of underestimating the steepness of the rising epidemic trend.<ref name=guardian0404>{{cite web|author=Caelainn Barr, Pamela Duncan and Niamh McIntyre |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/04/why-what-we-think-we-know-about-the-uks-coronavirus-death-toll-is-wrong |title=Why what we think we know about the UK's coronavirus death toll is wrong &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nConcerns have been raised that [[right-wing]] voices in the United Kingdom could fuel [[Islamophobia]], after [[Andrew Pierce]], a journalist for the Daily Mail tabloid, tweeted on Sunday: \"If families gather for holy month of [[Ramadan]] there will be a huge spike in Covid cases. Doctors are very worried.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Aina Khan|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2020/04/anger-wing-uk-voices-predict-ramadan-virus-spread-200413170844190.html |title=Anger as right-wing UK voices 'predict' Ramadan virus spread |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date= |access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Response by sector==\n===Arts and entertainment===\n====Music====\n[[File:Wee Annie, Cleats & Clyde, face mask.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Wee Annie\" statue in [[Gourock]] with a face mask, on 22 March.]]\nOn 13 March, [[BBC Radio 1]] cancelled its [[BBC Radio 1's Big Weekend|Big Weekend]] music festival, scheduled to take place at the end of May.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/51672257 |title=Coronavirus: Coachella, Radio 1's Big Weekend, BTS and other music events affected |work=CBBC Newsround |date=13 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301213740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/51672257|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other music events to be cancelled included the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival,<ref name=MetroGigs/> the 2020 [[Glastonbury Festival]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51942898 |title=Glastonbury festival cancelled due to coronavirus |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |last1=Savage |first1=Mark| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318114624/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51942898| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Isle of Wight Festival|Isle of Wight]] and [[Download Festival|Download]] music festivals<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/26/download-and-isle-of-wight-festivals-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus |title=Download and Isle of Wight festivals cancelled due to coronavirus |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |date=26 March 2020 |via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> and the [[Cambridge Folk Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/cambridge-folk-festival-been-cancelled-17997939 |title=Another summer festival has been cancelled this year in Cambridge |first=Alistair |last=Ryder |date=27 March 2020 |website=cambridgenews}}</ref>\n\nAmong the artists and bands to postpone or cancel UK gigs or tours were [[Avril Lavigne]] and [[The Who]].<ref name=MetroGigs>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/artists-cancelled-gigs-due-coronavirus-12401000/ |title=Coronavirus: Gigs and events cancelled so far |date=15 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200316162942/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/artists-cancelled-gigs-due-coronavirus-12401000/|archive-date = 16 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/coronavirus-tours-gigs-festivals-cancelled-list-who-bts-billie-eilish-stormzy-a9399646.html |title=Billie Eilish, the Who and BTS among tours and festivals cancelled over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200317214345/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/coronavirus-tours-gigs-festivals-cancelled-list-who-bts-billie-eilish-stormzy-a9399646.html|archive-date = 17 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Other, including [[Chris Martin]] of [[Coldplay]], [[Yungblud]], [[Keith Urban]], and [[Christine And The Queens]] responded to the situation by live-streaming gigs through social media.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51924765 |title=Pop stars live-stream concerts to combat isolation |work=BBC News |date=17 March 2020 |last1=Savage |first1=Mark| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014752/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51924765| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Former [[Beautiful South]] members [[Paul Heaton]] and [[Jacqui Abbott]] announced they would play a free show for NHS staff working on the frontline of the pandemic in October, giving away 9,000 tickets for the event.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52032618 |title=Paul Heaton and Jacqui Abbott to play free NHS gig |first=Mark |last=Savage |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Rick Astley]] announced that he would play a free gig for NHS staff at the [[Manchester Arena]] on 28 October,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/rick-astley-announces-free-concert-for-nhs-primary-care-and-emergency-service-workers-2638332|title=Rick Astley announces free concert for NHS, Primary Care and emergency service workers|date=31 March 2020}}</ref> while [[Liam Gallagher]] announced that he would play a free gig for NHS staff at [[The O2 Arena]] on 29 October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/liamgallagher/status/1248596479561826306|title=It's an honour to announce that I will be doing a gig for the NHS and careworkers at London's TheO2 on October 29th. They do an incredible job, we are very lucky to have them. LG xpic.twitter.com/iRfb2RNNNy|first=Liam|last=Gallagher|date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Theatre and cinema====\nOn 15 March, London's [[The Old Vic|Old Vic]] became the first [[West End theatre|West End]] theatre to cancel a performance when it ended its run of [[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Endgame (play)|Endgame]]'' two weeks early.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/old-vic-endgame-coronavirus-daniel-radcliffe-a4387811.html |title=Endgame as Old Vic becomes first London theatre to cancel performances |date=15 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154238/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/old-vic-endgame-coronavirus-daniel-radcliffe-a4387811.html|archive-date = 16 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> On 16 March, other theatres in London, as well as elsewhere around the UK, closed following Boris Johnson's advice that people should avoid such venues.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51906370 |title=West End shuts down after PM's coronavirus advice |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020| access-date=16 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316220403/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51906370| archive-date=16 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 March, cinema chains [[Odeon Cinemas|Odeon]], [[Cineworld]], [[Vue Cinemas|Vue]] and [[Picturehouse Cinemas|Picturehouse]] announced they would be closing all of their UK outlets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |title=Most UK cinemas shut after virus advice |work=BBC News |date=17 March 2020| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014723/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51925490| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On 1 April, the 2020 [[List of Edinburgh festivals|Edinburgh festivals]], planned for August, were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-52121586|title=Edinburgh festivals cancelled due to coronavirus|date=1 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] launched National Theatre at Home, a two-month programme whereby a different production from its archives was streamed for free each week. The project began with [[Richard Bean]]'s comedy ''[[One Man, Two Guvnors]]'' featuring [[James Corden]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2020/mar/26/national-theatre-to-broadcast-shows-online-on-thursdays|title=National Theatre to broadcast shows online on Thursdays|first=Mark Brown Arts|last=correspondent|date=26 March 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n====Television and radio====\nTelevision programmes to be affected included forthcoming series of ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'' and ''[[Line of Duty]]'', which had their filming schedules delayed.<ref name=soaps/> On 13 March, [[ITV plc|ITV]] announced that the 2020 series finale of ''[[Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway]]'', scheduled to be broadcast from [[Walt Disney World]] in [[Florida]] would no longer go ahead after the resort announced its intention to close as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/13/ant-decs-saturday-night-takeaway-finale-walt-disney-world-florida-cancelled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-12396126/ |title=Saturday Night Takeaway Walt Disney World finale in Florida cancelled |newspaper=Metro |publisher= |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314201437/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/13/ant-decs-saturday-night-takeaway-finale-walt-disney-world-florida-cancelled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-12396126/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, ITV announced that the filming schedule for its two soaps, ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and ''[[Emmerdale]]'' had not been affected by the pandemic,<ref name=soaps>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51912510 |title=Coronavirus: Coronation Street and Emmerdale 'to remind about hand-washing' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317024423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51912510 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> but filming ceased on 23 March.<ref name=Lorraine>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-22/coronavirus-coronation-street-emmerdale-suspend-production-coronavirus-fears/ |title=Lorraine and Loose Women to stop live broadcasting as Coronation Street and Emmerdale suspend filming |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March ITV announced the semi-final of the [[The Voice UK (series 9)|ninth series]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', scheduled for 28 March, would be postponed until later in the year.<ref name=Revamp>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51931050 |title=Coronavirus: BBC and ITV revamp broadcast plans amid outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318012425/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51931050 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the [[BBC]] delayed the implementation of its planned changes to [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|TV licences]] for those aged over 75 from June to August.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316132508/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March the BBC also announced that it would delay its plans to cut 450 news jobs due to the pressure of covering the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52035875 |title=BBC News suspends 450 job cuts to ensure Covid-19 coverage |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the BBC announced major changes to the schedule across the network. While some programmes were suspended, others such as ''[[Newsnight]]'' and ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'' continued with a smaller number of production staff. Some podcasts were also suspended.<ref name=BBC-changes/> On 18 March it was announced that filming of soap operas and regular dramas would be suspended.<ref name=EastEnders>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51943592 |title=Coronavirus: EastEnders, Casualty, Doctors and Holby City suspend filming |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318102224/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51943592 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The BBC also said that it would show more educational programmes to cater for children not attending school,<ref>{{cite news |first=Dave |last=Speck |url=https://www.tes.com/news/coronavirus-bbc-works-schools-offer-tv-lessons |title=Coronavirus: BBC works with schools to offer TV lessons |newspaper=Times Educational Supplement |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192711/https://www.tes.com/news/coronavirus-bbc-works-schools-offer-tv-lessons |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and more programmes focused on health, fitness, education, religion and food recipes.<ref name=Revamp/> On 23 March, ITV ceased the live broadcasting of two programmes.<ref name=Lorraine/>\n\nOn radio, some [[BBC World Service]] programmes were suspended. Radio news summaries on [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3]], [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live|Radio 5 Live]] were merged into a single output, with [[BBC 6 Music]] using the same script. The [[BBC Asian Network]] and ''[[Newsbeat]]'' worked together to maintain production of stories.<ref name=BBC-changes>{{Cite press release |title=BBC News sets out plans to keep audiences receiving trusted and accurate information |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/news-coronavirus |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318145141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/news-coronavirus |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 March, the BBC announced that its local radio stations in England would broadcast a virtual church service, led initially by the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], but with plans to expand religious services to cover other faiths.<ref name=Revamp/> On the same day [[Radio News Hub]], a radio news bulletin provider based in [[Leeds]], announced that it would produce a daily ten-minute programme giving a round-up of information about the pandemic and that would be made available free of charge to radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/free-daily-coronavirus-news-round-up-available/ |title=Free daily coronavirus news round-up available |work=Radio Today |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182740/https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/free-daily-coronavirus-news-round-up-available/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 March, [[BBC Local Radio]] announced that it had teamed up with manufacturers, retailers and the social isolation charity [[WaveLength]] to give away free [[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]] radios to vulnerable people over the age of 70.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/bbc-to-give-away-dab-radios-for-some-over-70s/ |title=BBC to give away DAB radios to some over 70s |publisher=Radio Today |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nMany construction sites initially remained operational following the introduction of social distancing rules. Following criticism, housebuilders including [[Barratt Developments|Barratt]] and [[Taylor Wimpey]], and contractors including [[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] paused work on 24 March,<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/buildings/barratt-and-taylor-wimpey-shut-all-sites-24-03-2020/ Barratt and Taylor Wimpey shut all sites] 24 March 2020 ''www.constructionnews.co.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref> though Mace later reopened some sites.<ref name=\"TCI-07Apr2020\">{{cite news |title=Mace starts reopening sites |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/mace-starts-reopening-sites |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Construction Index |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, confusion about what constituted essential work, along with contractors' enforcement of subcontractors' contractual obligations, meant some projects remained operational, and many site workers experienced highly variable application of social distancing precautions.<ref name=\"Zak-02Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Garner-Purkis |first1=Zak |title=Construction: coronavirus villain or saviour of the economy |url=https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/agenda/investigations/construction-coronavirus-villain-or-saviour-of-the-economy-02-04-2020/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Construction News |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> In Scotland, work was ordered to be suspended on all non-essential construction projects from 6 April.<ref name=\"Prior-06Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Prior |first1=Grant |title=Scottish sites ordered to close unless on essential list |url=https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2020/04/06/scottish-sites-ordered-to-close-unless-on-essential-list/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Construction Enquirer |date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Major contractors including Mace, [[Sir Robert McAlpine|McAlpine]], [[Laing O'Rourke]], [[Wates Group|Wates]] and [[Morgan Sindall Group|Morgan Sindall]] each put 100s of workers on furlough.<ref name=\"Rogers-03Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Rogers |first1=Dave |title=Mace furloughs more than 800 staff |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/mace-furloughs-more-than-800-staff/5105393.article |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Building |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> By 8 April, work at 80% of UK housebuilding sites had stopped.<ref name=\"Gardiner-08Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Gardiner |first1=Joey |title=Work stops at 80% of UK housebuilding sites |url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/work-stops-at-80-of-uk-housebuilding-sites/5105470.article |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Building |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Consumers===\n[[File:Pasta shortage tourism at Tesco, Finchley, London.jpg|thumb|The almost empty pasta section in a London [[Tesco]], 7 March 2020]]\nIt was reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that British supermarkets and their suppliers had developed a plan to ensure a consistent supply of a range of basic goods if there was panic-buying by consumers. Tesco, the country's largest supermarket chain, was said to have carried out simulation exercises to plan for events such as a pandemic flu outbreak which could be used to deal with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=guardi>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/02/uk-supermarkets-braced-for-stockpiling-if-coronavirus-escalates-panic-buying |title=UK supermarkets draw up plan to 'feed the nation' as coronavirus spreads |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first1=Jasper |last1=Jolly |first2=Rebecca |last2=Smith |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303013359/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/02/uk-supermarkets-braced-for-stockpiling-if-coronavirus-escalates-panic-buying|archive-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> There were reports of hand sanitiser and anti-bacterial products selling out at some supermarkets.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegrocer.co.uk/service-and-availability/supermarkets-sell-out-of-hand-sanitiser-amid-coronavirus-panic-buying/602551.article |title=Supermarkets sell out of hand sanitiser amid coronavirus panic-buying |website=The Grocer |publisher=William Reed Business Media |first1=Carina |last1=Perkins |first2=Ellis |last2=Hawthorne |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> Online retailers reported consumers placing unusually large orders while the managing director of the frozen food chain [[Iceland (retailer)|Iceland]] reported increased sales of \"multibuy deals and larger packs\".<ref name=guardi/>\n[[File:DSC05532 (49675496857).jpg|thumb|People in London were buying more canned foods and toilet paper, 18 March 2020|alt=]]\nSome supermarkets and other shops responded by limiting the quantity of popular items that each customer could buy, while others had a limit across their entire range.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/21/uk-supermarket-restrictions-grocery-shops-panic/ |title=UK supermarket restrictions: how local grocery shops are introducing rationing to fight food shortages |first=Lizzie |last=Roberts |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321193542/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/21/uk-supermarket-restrictions-grocery-shops-panic/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/national/18312957.supermarkets-place-buying-limits-items-bring-oap-only-shopping-hours/ |title=Supermarkets place buying limits on items and bring in OAP-only shopping hours |website=Sutton & Croydon Guardian |agency=Press Association|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321193541/https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/national/18312957.supermarkets-place-buying-limits-items-bring-oap-only-shopping-hours/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sainsbury's]] announced on 18 March that they would introduce a dedicated shopping hour for elderly and disabled customers, as well as giving them priority for online deliveries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/elderly-only-shopping-sainsburys-brings-17941743 |title=Elderly-only shopping as Sainsbury's brings in tough new rules |website=Wales Online |first=Neil |last=Shaw |date=18 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321194235/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/elderly-only-shopping-sainsburys-brings-17941743|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other supermarkets, such as Iceland and Morrisons, also introduced measures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/tesco-asda-sainsburys-aldi-iceland-17952371 |title=Supermarket opening time changes and new rules on what you can buy |website=Chronicle Live |first1=Michael |last1=Muncaster |first2=Elle May |last2=Rice |date=20 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213358/https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/tesco-asda-sainsburys-aldi-iceland-17952371|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sainsbury's further announced on 21 March that they would give healthcare workers allocated shopping hours on three mornings a week.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/sainsburys-offers-nhs-and-elderly-three-weekday-shopping-slots-224199/ |title=Coronavirus Kent: Sainsbury's offers NHS staff allocated shopping hours and extends dedicated slots for elderly |website=Kent Online |first=Joe |last=Walker |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321201312/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/sainsburys-offers-nhs-and-elderly-three-weekday-shopping-slots-224199/|archive-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] stopped sellers from sending non-essential products to their warehouses.<ref name=\"Amazon\" /> [[Selfridges]] closed all its stores and sold only online.<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51941987 |title=Sainsbury's limits sales of all food items amid stockpiling |website=BBC News |date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074305/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51941987|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the panic buying of food, Professor [[Stephen Powis]], medical director at NHS England, said on 21 March that NHS staff were being deprived of food supplies because of the activities of some consumers, and urged people to shop responsibly. [[Helen Dickinson]], head of the [[British Retail Consortium]] said that there was enough food in the supply chain, but that the issue was getting it to retailers quick enough, suggesting the food industry was experiencing \"a peak in demand\" like at Christmas, but \"without the four-month build-up period.\" She added that that an extra \u00a31bn had been spent on food in the preceding three weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51989721 |title=Buy responsibly and think of others, shoppers told |work=BBC News |date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213812/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51989721|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] also urged shoppers to stop panic buying.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |website=BBC News |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321142202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day it was reported that Tesco, [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] had begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |website=BBC News |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321000450/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the government announced that the [[Phase-out of lightweight plastic bags#United Kingdom|5p charge for carrier bags]] would be waived for online food deliveries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/21/plastic-bag-charge-waived-speed-supermarket-service-coronavirus-crisis-12435418/ |title=Coronavirus: Plastic bag charge waived for online deliveries to speed up service |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |first=James |last=Hockaday |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSainsbury's announced that it would remove purchasing limits on most items from 5 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/british-supermarket-sainsbury-s-to-remove-most-customer-purchasing-limits-12606332|title=British supermarket Sainsbury's to remove most customer purchasing limits|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> On 8 April Tesco said that it could not meet the increased demand for online shopping despite expanding its home delivery service, and 85 to 90 percent of food would need to be bought in store.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52211912 Coronavirus: Tesco tells people to visit stores to get food] 8 April 2020, ''www.bbc.co.uk'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref>\n\n=== Defence ===\n{{main|Operation Rescript|Operation Broadshare}}\nIn March 2020, following a request for [[military aid to the civil authorities]], the Ministry of Defence announced the formation of the COVID Support Force, a 20,000-strong military force under [[Home Command (British Army)#Standing Joint Commander (UK)|Standing Joint Command]] at [[Aldershot Garrison|Aldershot]], to support public services and civil authorities in tackling the pandemic.<ref name=\"Rescript1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/standing-joint-command-sjc-resilience-of-the-uk-30e1b47c3643|title=Standing Joint Command (SJC): Resilience of the UK|last=Ministry of Defence|date=2020-04-08|website=Medium|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Two military operations; [[Operation Rescript]], based in the UK, and [[Operation Broadshare]], focused on overseas defence activities, were launched.<ref name=\"Rescript2\" /> [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] [[Nick Carter (British Army officer)|Nick Carter]] ordered the military to prepare for a \"six month\" operation and to be on an \"operational footing\" by mid-April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Defence Chief tells military to prepare for six-month operation whilst warning of threats from 'those who wish to undermine our way of life' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/defence-chief-tells-military-prepare-six-month-operation-whilst/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Telegraph |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321114808/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/defence-chief-tells-military-prepare-six-month-operation-whilst/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The COVID Support Force was initially tasked with driving oxygen tankers for the NHS, as well as delivering medical supplies, including PPE, to hospitals.<ref name=\"Rescript1\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=COVID Support Force: the MOD's contribution to the coronavirus response |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/covid-support-force-the-mods-contribution-to-the-coronavirus-response |accessdate=24 March 2020 |agency=GOV.UK |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Prior to the announcement of the COVID Support Force, the armed forces had assisted the British government in repatriating British citizens from affected areas, including China and Japan.<ref name=\"MACA\">{{cite web |title=Military Aid to Civil Authorities: The COVID Support Force |url=https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/military-aid-to-civil-authorities-the-covid-support-force-acd80ec70099 |website=medium.com |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321135440/https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/military-aid-to-civil-authorities-the-covid-support-force-acd80ec70099 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Royal Air Force also repatriated British and EU citizens from Cuba.<ref>{{cite news |title=RAF assist repatriation flight of British and EU citizens from Cuba |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/raf-assist-repatriation-flight-of-british-and-eu-citizens-from-cuba/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=UK Defence Jorunal |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe coronavirus pandemic affected British military deployments at home and abroad. Training exercises, including those in Canada and Kenya, had to be cancelled to free up personnel for the COVID Support Force.<ref>{{cite news |title=10,000 extra troops to join British army's Covid support force |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132719/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The British training mission in Iraq, part of [[Operation Shader]], had to be down-scaled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Britain could see biggest mobilisation of military since Iraq war |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-britain-could-see-biggest-mobilisation-of-army-since-iraq-war-11963256 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> An air base supporting this military operation also confirmed two cases of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two British Service Members Test Positive For Coronavirus In Cyprus |url=https://www.forces.net/news/two-british-service-members-test-positive-coronavirus-cyprus |agency=forces.net |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nElsewhere in defence, air shows, including the [[Royal International Air Tattoo]] at [[RAF Fairford]], were cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Farnborough and RAF Fairford air shows cancelled |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-51978103 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Civilian airports, including [[Birmingham Airport]], were used to practice transferring Coronavirus patients to local hospitals via helicopter.<ref name=\"Irwin\">{{cite news |last1=Irwin |first1=David |title=Military helicopters training over airport amid Covid-19 crisis |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321180535/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Military on more manoeuvres around Birmingham Airport to transport coronavirus patients |url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Solihull Observer |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132723/https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several defence and aerospace companies contributed to the national effort to produce more ventilators.<ref>{{cite news |title=Covid-19: Aerospace companies to lead national ventilator effort |url=https://www.janes.com/article/94999/covid-19-aerospace-companies-to-lead-national-ventilator-effort |agency=Janes |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> [[BAE Systems]], the country's largest defence company, also loaned its [[Warton Aerodrome]] site to be used as a temporary morgue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Every known detail on morgue to be set up at BAE Systems in Warton |url=https://www.lancs.live/news/lancashire-news/every-known-detail-morgue-set-18066310 |agency=lancs.live |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe armed forces assisted in the transportation of coronavirus patients in some of the country's remotest regions, such as [[Shetland]] and the [[Isles of Scilly]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Military called in to fly Covid-19 patient to intensive care |url=https://www.shetnews.co.uk/2020/03/22/military-called-in-to-fly-covid-19-patient-to-intensive-care/ |agency=shetnews.co.uk |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Headquarters Standing Joint Command (HQ SJC): Coordinating the military contribution to the UK's resilience operations |url=https://medium.com/@DefenceHQ/headquarters-standing-joint-command-hq-sjc-coordinating-the-military-contribution-to-the-uks-99b447414235 |agency=medium.com |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March 2020, [[Joint Helicopter Command]] began assisting the coronavirus relief effort by transporting people and supplies. Helicopters were based at [[RAF Leeming]] to cover Northern England and Scotland, whilst helicopters based at [[RAF Benson]], [[RAF Odiham]] and  [[RNAS_Yeovilton_(HMS_Heron)|RNAS Yeovilton]] supported the Midlands and Southern England.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Measures To Support Battle Against Coronavirus In Scotland |url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/coronavirus/new-measures-to-support-battle-against-coronavirus-in-scotland/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=raf.mod.uk |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, the armed forces helped plan and construct a field hospital at the [[ExCeL London]] conference centre, named [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]]. Further [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|critical care field hospitals]] were later built with military assistance in Birmingham, Manchester, Harrogate, Bristol, Exeter, Washington and Glasgow. These hospitals were staffed by military medics, alongside the NHS.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Army Supports Glasgow SEC Centre's Conversion Into Temporary Hospital |url=https://www.forces.net/news/coronavirus-army-support-glasgow-secs-conversion-temporary-hospital |agency=forces.net |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April, armed forces personnel began supporting ambulance services across the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Military deploys 80 troops to help ambulance service cope with pressure of coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/military-help-south-central-ambulance-service-a4403971.html |agency=Evening Standard |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Welsh Secretary praises UK's Armed Forces' support in Wales' fight against coronavirus |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/welsh-secretary-praises-uks-armed-forces-support-in-wales-fight-against-coronavirus |agency=UK.GOV |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Military personnel join medics to boost Essex ambulance service during crisis |url=https://www.bishopsstortfordindependent.co.uk/news/coronavirus-soldiers-on-the-frontline-with-essex-ambulance-crews-9105888/ |agency=Bishop's Stortford Independent |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Elsewhere, the armed forces helped transform locations to accommodate additional patient beds, including across Cumbria and the Isle of White.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leisure centres in Cumbria transformed into additional NHS bed capacity |url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/18349635.leisures-centres-cumbria-transformed-additional-nhs-bed-capacity/?fbclid=IwAR1WmVvnMFR81MQQpTzj5mGyZUI2o3Oyysw9IyiWraGFPH8cxNC3PLAsuN8 |agency=News & Star |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Army Begin Work at St. Mary's Hospital |url=https://www.islandecho.co.uk/army-begin-work-at-st-marys-hospital/ |agency=islandecho.co.uk |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Testing centres, including in Glasgow, were also assembled with military assistance.<ref>{{cite news |title=LOCAL RESERVISTS TO SUPPORT SCOTS GUARDS WITH CORONAVIRUS MISSION |url=https://www.islandecho.co.uk/local-reservists-to-support-scots-guards-with-coronavirus-mission/ |agency=Island Echo |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTraining locations, such as [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] and [[HMS Raleigh (shore establishment)|HMS Raleigh]], had to adapt their passing out parades. Cadets involved were made to stand {{convert|2|m}} apart in combat dress and there were no spectators in the grandstands.<ref>{{cite news |title=New-Look Parade As Officer Cadets Pass Through Sandhurst During Pandemic |url=https://www.forces.net/news/new-look-parade-officer-cadets-pass-through-sandhurst-during-pandemic |agency=forces.net |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=RECRUITS FINISH TRAINING AMID CORONAVIRUS RESPONSE |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2020/march/27/20200327-hms-raleigh-finish-training |agency=Royal Navy |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, following Prime Minister Boris Jonhson's hospitalisation due to coronavirus, concerns were raised with regards to national security, in particular control of the country's [[United Kingdom and weapons of mass destruction|nuclear weapons]]. When asked by the BBC, Cabinet Office Minister [[Michael Gove]] stated \"There are well developed protocols which are in place. I just really cannot talk about national security issues\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Who has the UK nuclear button while Johnson is ill? No comment |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-britain-nuclear/who-has-the-uk-nuclear-button-while-johnson-is-ill-no-comment-idUSL8N2BV1Z5 |agency=Reuters |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 12 April 2020, the COVID Support Force had responded to 76 requests for assistance from government ministries with 2,680 personnel deployed from a total of 23,000 on standby. 2,300 vehicles were also in use as temporary ambulances and to transport personnel and supplies in 34 locations across the country.<ref name=\"12AprilStats\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Armed forces rapidly expand their response to COVID-19 |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-armed-forces-rapidly-expand-their-response-to-covid-19-11970136 |agency=Sky News |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economics===\nThe governor of the [[Bank of England]] called on the British government to provide support to businesses affected by the virus<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/04/next-bank-of-england-governor-calls-for-funds-for-coronavirus-hit-firms |title=Next Bank of England governor calls for funds for coronavirus-hit firms |work=Guardian |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100455/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/04/next-bank-of-england-governor-calls-for-funds-for-coronavirus-hit-firms|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and was reported to be working with the Treasury to provide a stimulus package to prevent the British economy falling into recession.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/05/coronavirus-could-push-uk-to-brink-of-recession-says-goldman-sachs |title=Bank of England drafts action plan to head off coronavirus recession |first1=Jasper |last1=Jolly |first2=Julia |last2=Kollewe |work=Guardian |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100403/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/05/coronavirus-could-push-uk-to-brink-of-recession-says-goldman-sachs|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Companies listed on the London stock markets have fallen in value with commentators citing worries about the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51681620 |title=Coronavirus fears wipe \u00a3200bn off UK firms' value |work=BBC News |date=28 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302144058/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51681620|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To stimulate the economy, the Bank of England cut interest rates from 0.75 to 0.25 percent.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Inman |first1=Phillip |last2=Partington |first2=Richard |last3=Sweney |first3=Mark |title=Coronavirus: Bank of England makes emergency interest rate cut |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/11/coronavirus-bank-of-england-makes-emergency-interest-rate-cut |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the interest rate was again cut this time to 0.10% \u2013 the lowest rate in the bank's 325-year existence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed again in emergency move |date=19 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319152457/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 March, Fitch downgraded the UK's [[credit rating|government debt rating]] from AA to AA-, because of coronavirus borrowing, economic decline, and lingering uncertainty over Brexit. The ratings agency believes that the UK's government deficit for 2020 might equal 9% of GDP, compared to 2% the previous year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Henderson |first1=Richard |title=Fitch downgrades UK debt citing coronavirus impact |url=https://www.ft.com/content/28fbd0d1-c5be-4a8b-8c63-b14c746ee8bc |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Financial Times |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 9, Chancellor Sunak has solved the financing problem by overdraft and promised to pay it off by the end of the year,.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Elliott |first=Larry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/apr/09/bank-of-england-to-finance-uk-government-covid-19-crisis-spending |title=Bank of England to finance UK government Covid-19 crisis spending |date=2020-04-09 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-12 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\n{{main|2020 UK education shutdown}}\nFollowing cases in Italy, the [[Cransley School]] in [[Northwich]], [[Cheshire]], and [[Trinity Catholic College, Middlesbrough|Trinity Catholic College]] in [[Middlesbrough]] closed, as some of their pupils had returned with symptoms from Italy. Fourteen schools in England had closed by 28 February.<ref name=Bedingfield>{{Cite news |last=Bedingfield |first=Will |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-schools-closed |title=Will shutting down UK schools stop coronavirus? It's complicated |date=28 February 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=3 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302194619/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-schools-closed|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Loughborough University]] reported a student confirmed to have the virus after recent travel to Italy, and indicated that several staff members and students began self-isolation.<ref name=LboroUni>{{Cite news |last=Fagan |first=Ciaran |URL=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/news/local-news/leicestershires-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-3925980 |title=Leicestershire's first Coronavirus case is confirmed as a university student |work=Leicester Mercury|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308024036/https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/news/local-news/leicestershires-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-3925980|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] was heavily criticised for their incoherent response to the pandemic which forced international students and staff to scramble to make arrangements to return home with only two days' notice. On 13 March, students and staff were advised that international travel was discouraged and university facilities would stay open at reduced capacity. On 18 March, Vice Chancellor [[Stephen Toope]] announced a sudden U-turn and all university buildings would be indefinitely shut from all staff and students from the afternoon of Friday 20 March onwards, and all students are strongly encouraged to leave Cambridge.<ref name=\":0.1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-colleges-criticised-for-asking-students-to-leave-over-coronavirus |title=Cambridge colleges criticised for asking students to leave over coronavirus |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319153851/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-colleges-criticised-for-asking-students-to-leave-over-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The president of Cambridge [[University and College Union|UCU]] criticised that this sudden shutdown will exacerbate the pandemic as students from countries with weaker healthcare provisions are forced to return home.<ref name=\":0.1\" /> Over a thousand Cambridge students signed an open letter requesting to have multiple assessment options in lieu of the cancelled examinations in Cambridge, including the option to retake part or all of the academic year in 2020\u201321.<ref>{{cite news |last=Batty |first=David |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-students-urge-university-to-cancel-final-exams-over-coronavirus |title=Cambridge students urge university to let them retake the final year |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=20 March 2020 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154023/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-students-urge-university-to-cancel-final-exams-over-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Coventry University]] first suspended all graduation ceremonies due to be held in March and April,<ref name=\"Layton\">{{cite news |last1=Layton |first1=Josh |url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-university-cancels-graduation-ceremonies-17905226 |title=Coventry University suspends graduation ceremonies to guard against coronavirus |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[Coventry Telegraph]] |accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312175516/https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-university-cancels-graduation-ceremonies-17905226|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and from 20 March, suspended all face-to-face teaching, in favour of on-line delivery.<ref name=\"CU\">{{cite web |title=Our response to COVID-19. |url=https://www.coventry.ac.uk/the-university/key-information/health-and-safety-information/our-response-to-covid-19/ |publisher=Coventry University |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> Many other higher education institutions took similar steps at around the same time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-51880355 |title=More universities halt teaching and exams |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-19 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318214433/https://www.bbc.com/news/education-51880355|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Welsh government announced that all schools in Wales would be closing by 20 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=All schools in Wales to close by Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318132314/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] announced that Scottish schools would also be closing from 20 March, and may not reopen before the summer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Schools 'may be shut until summer' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51947670 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140554/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51947670 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later that day, it was announced that schools in Northern Ireland would close to pupils immediately and to staff on 20 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schools in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to close by the end of the week |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-18/coronavirus-outbreak-wales-school-closing-by-friday-highly-possible-scottish-schools-will-shut/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=18 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318184451/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-18/coronavirus-outbreak-wales-school-closing-by-friday-highly-possible-scottish-schools-will-shut/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, the [[Secretary of State for Education]], [[Gavin Williamson]] announced that schools in England would close from 20 March for an unspecified length of time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Schools in England follow Scotland and Wales in closing |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318174202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Boris Johnson said that schools will still look after the children of [[key workers]], and vulnerable children.<ref name=GuardianSchoolsClosed/> The UK government also announced that [[GCSE]] and [[A Level]] exams were to be cancelled, an unprecedented action in UK educational history, and that grades were to be given out based on predicted grades and teacher assessment.<ref name=GuardianSchoolsClosed>{{cite newspaper |title=UK schools to be closed indefinitely and exams cancelled |newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Adams |first1=Richard |last2=Stewart |first2=Heather |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-be-closed-indefinitely-and-exams-cancelled |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320215503/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-be-closed-indefinitely-and-exams-cancelled |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Coronavirus: GCSE and A-Level results to be based on teachers predicted grades |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-20/coronavirus-gcse-and-a-level-results-to-be-based-on-teachers-predicted-graces/ |newspaper=[[ITV News]] |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201045/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-20/coronavirus-gcse-and-a-level-results-to-be-based-on-teachers-predicted-graces/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Fears that cancelling exams will hit BAME and poor pupils worst |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/fears-that-cancelling-exams-will-hit-black-and-poor-pupils-worst |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |last1=Weale |first1=Sally |last2=Batty |first2=David |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132257/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/fears-that-cancelling-exams-will-hit-black-and-poor-pupils-worst |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Engineering===\nThe seven [[Formula One]] teams based in the UK - [[McLaren]], [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]], [[Racing Point]], [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]], [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] and [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] - and [[Haas F1 Team|Haas]] with its European headquarters there, are collaborating, in an initiative called \"Project Pitlane\", to develop and manufacture ventilators for hospitals to use for Covid-19 patients.<ref name=\"cam_20200322\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cityam.com/f1-teams-to-help-produce-20000-ventilators-for-nhs-in-fight-against-coronavirus/ |title=F1 teams to help produce 20,000 ventilators for NHS in fight against coronavirus |last=Searles |first=Michael |date=22 March 2020 |work=City A.M.}}</ref><ref name=\"tt_20200330\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/formula-one-rivals-join-forces-in-race-to-build-enough-ventilators-wv6ld8znz |title=Formula One rivals join forces in race to build enough ventilators |last=Slot |first=Owen |date=30 March 2020 |work=The Times}}</ref>\n\nHeavy equipment manufacturer [[JCB (company)|JCB]] have created prototypes of housings for ventilators to be produced by technology company [[Dyson (company)|Dyson]], and is planning to start producing them to help Dyson fulfil a government order placed with them for 10,000 machines.<ref name=\"bbc_52097747\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-52097747 |title=JCB set to help with ventilator production |date=30 March 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that [[Ineos]], the UK chemical company, had set up a factory capable of producing 1 million bottles of hand sanitiser per month. The factory in [[Newton Aycliffe]], which usually produces PVC products for windows, is operating on three shifts per day and is distributing free bottles of sanitiser to the UK's national health services.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/ineos-hand-sanitiser-factory-up-and-running/ |title=INEOS hand sanitiser factory up and running |date=2 April 2020|work=The Engineer}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, [[Jaguar Land Rover]] (JLR) put a re-usable protective visor into production in Warwickshire. Their target is to produce 5,000 units per week in [[Warwickshire]] and distribute them to NHS Trusts around the country. The manufacturing data for the visor, designed by JLR's engineers in Gaydon, is to be made open-source, so that other manufacturers can also produce the visors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/jlr-rapid-manufacture-face-visor/ |title=JLR produces protective face visors for frontline NHS staff |date=3 April 2020|work=The Engineer}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\n====LGBT pride====\nOn 23 March, [[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, was postponed. It was one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323092251/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 3 April, [[Brighton Pride]], scheduled for Saturday 1 August, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-52147938 |title=Coronavirus: Brighton Pride 2020 cancelled - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n====Northern Ireland parades====\nOn 6 April the [[Orange Order|Orange Lodge of Ireland]] announced that the traditional [[Twelfth of July]] parades in Northern Ireland had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52184743 |title=Coronavirus: Twelfth of July parades cancelled due to outbreak|date= 6 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Food and hospitality===\nFast food and drink outlets [[Pret a Manger]] and [[McDonald's]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/food-and-drink/mcdonalds-closing-seating-areas-coronavirus-takeway-drive-thru-monopoly-2482763 |title=McDonald's closing all seating areas due to coronavirus to become takeaway only \u2013 and Monopoly promotion is scrapped |publisher=inews |date= |accessdate=2020-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154309/https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/food-and-drink/mcdonalds-closing-seating-areas-coronavirus-takeway-drive-thru-monopoly-2482763 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> (among others) at first announced that they would not permit customers to sit and eat in stores, but customers could still order products to take away and consume off the premises. On 22 March McDonald's announced it would close all outlets in the UK and Ireland by 7pm on 23 March.<ref name=guardian-mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday |title=McDonald's to close restaurants in UK and Ireland on Monday |newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224815/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nando's]] announced later the same day they would also close their outlets.<ref name=guardian-mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday/>\n\nInitially, the pub chain [[J D Wetherspoon]] remained open, despite government advice for the public to avoid places of social activity, including pubs. The chain announced that it would keep all pubs open \"unless the government states otherwise\". Wetherspoons put rules into place for the duration of the crisis to promote social distancing (as recommended by the government), including spacing out tables more and encouraging customers to use the Wetherspoons [[mobile app]] to order food and drink.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/news/2020/03/covid-19 |title=Wetherspoon is to continue operating its pubs across the UK \u2013 J D Wetherspoon | access-date=19 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319170624/https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/news/2020/03/covid-19 | archive-date=19 March 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 March, all Wetherspoon pubs were closed in line with instructions from the government.<ref>[https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/contact/faqs/uk-coronavirus-covid-19-infection Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the UK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154903/https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/contact/faqs/uk-coronavirus-covid-19-infection |date=19 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.jdwetherspoon.com'' accessed 21 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, [[Alcohol_licensing_laws_of_the_United_Kingdom#Off-licence|off-licences]] were added to the list of essential businesses allowed to stay open, also enabling pubs and brewery taprooms with licences to sell beer for home consumption to offer takeaway sales and home deliveries.<ref name=\"Davies-25Mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |last2=Sweney |first2=Mark |title=UK pubs and breweries push to be allowed takeaway sales |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/25/off-licences-added-to-essential-businesses-list-by-uk-government-covid-19 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Guardian |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Government ===\n[[File:British Government NHS coronavirus public info poster.pdf|thumb|upright|English NHS coronavirus poster, February 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/london/2020/02/03/coronavirus-public-information-campaign-launched-across-the-uk/ |title=Coronavirus public information campaign launched across the UK |work=NHS England |date=3 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>]]\nGuidance has altered in line with the number of cases detected and changes in where affected people have contracted the virus, as well as with what has been happening in other countries.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\"/> In February, [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Adviser]] to the UK Government, [[Chris Whitty]] explained \"we basically have a strategy which depends upon four tactical aims: the first one is to contain; the second of these is to delay; the third of these is to do the science and the research; and the fourth is to mitigate so we can brace the NHS.\"<ref name=Kobie>{{Cite news |last=Kobie |first=Nicole |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-response |title=This is how the UK is strengthening its coronavirus defences |date=15 February 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302194615/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-response|archive-date=2 March 2020}}</ref> These aims equate to four phases; specific actions involved in each of these phases are:\n*Contain: detect early cases, follow up close contacts, and prevent the disease taking hold in this country for as long as is reasonably possible\n*Delay: slow the spread within the UK, and (if it does take hold) lower the peak impact and push it away from the winter season\n*Research: better understand the virus and the actions that will lessen its effect on the UK population; innovate responses including diagnostics, drugs and vaccines; use the evidence to inform the development of the most effective models of care\n*Mitigate: provide the best care possible for people who become ill, support hospitals to maintain essential services and ensure ongoing support for people ill in the community, to minimise the overall impact of the disease on society, public services and on the economy.<ref name=Plan2020>Department of Health and Social Care, Emergency and Health Protection Directorate, [https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/869827/Coronavirus_action_plan_-_a_guide_to_what_you_can_expect_across_the_UK.pdf Coronavirus: action plan: A guide to what you can expect across the UK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304131952/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/869827/Coronavirus_action_plan_-_a_guide_to_what_you_can_expect_across_the_UK.pdf |date=4 March 2020 }}, published 3 March, accessed 7 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe four UK CMOs raised the UK risk level from low to moderate on 30 January 2020, upon the WHO's announcement of the disease as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> As soon as cases appeared in the UK on 31 January 2020, a public health information campaign, similar to the previous \"[[Catch it, Bin it, Kill it]]\" campaign, was launched in the UK, to advise people how to lessen the risk of spreading the virus.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Travellers from Hubei province in China, including the capital Wuhan were advised to self-isolate, \"stay at home, not go to work, school or public places, not use public transport or taxis, ask friends, family members or delivery services to do errands\",<ref name=NHS.ukCOVID>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) |last= |first= |date=24 January 2020 |website=nhs.uk |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302222456/https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=2 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> and call [[NHS 111]] if they had arrived in the UK in previous 14 days, regardless of whether they were unwell or not.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Further cases in early February prompted the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, Matt Hancock, to announce the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Daily updates have been published by the DHSC.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> [[NHS Digital]] in the meanwhile, have been collecting data.<ref name=RapsonHSJ>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/patient-safety/nhs-collecting-coronavirus-data-from-111-calls/7026999.article |title=NHS collecting coronavirus data from 111 calls |last=Rapson |first=Jasmine |date= |website=Health Service Journal |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Catch it, Bin it, Kill it poster.jpg|thumb|upright|Poster for the \"Catch it, Bin it, Kill it\" slogan which has been revived in the fight against coronavirus]]\nOn 25 February 2020, the UK's CMOs advice for all travellers (unwell or not) who had returned to the UK from Hubei province in the previous 14 days, Iran, specific areas designated by the Italian government as quarantine areas in northern Italy and special care zones in South Korea since 19 February, to self-isolate and call NHS 111.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\"/> This advice was also advocated for any person who has flu-like symptoms with a history of travelling from Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar and areas in Italy north of Pisa, Florence and Rimini, returning to the UK since 19 February. Later, self-isolation was recommended for anyone returning from any part of Italy from 9 March.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\"/>\n\nInitially, Boris Johnson largely kept Britain open, resisting the kind of lockdowns seen elsewhere in Europe. In a speech on 3 February, Johnson's main concern was that the \"coronavirus will trigger a panic and a desire for market segregation that go beyond what is medically rational to the point of doing real and unnecessary economic damage.\"<ref>[https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-britain-must-become-the-superman-of-global-free-trade \"Britain must become the superman of global free trade\"], ''The Spectator'', 3/2/20.</ref> On 13 March, UK chief scientific adviser Sir Patrick Vallance told [[BBC Radio 4]] that one of \"the key things we need to do\" is to \"build up some kind of [[herd immunity]] so more people are immune to this disease and we reduce the transmission\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Booth |first1=William |title=U.K. resists coronavirus lockdowns, goes its own way on response |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-herd-immunity/2020/03/16/1c9d640e-66c7-11ea-b199-3a9799c54512_story.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Washington Post |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> This involves enough people getting infected, upon which they develop immunity to the disease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-uk-cases-herd-immunity-covid-19/ |title=The U.K. is aiming for deliberate 'herd immunity' |website=Fortune|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314082329/https://fortune.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-uk-cases-herd-immunity-covid-19/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-herd-immunity-uk-nhs-outbreak-pandemic-government-a9399101.html |title=60% of UK population need to get coronavirus so country can build 'herd immunity', chief scientist says |date=13 March 2020 |website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313191522/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-herd-immunity-uk-nhs-outbreak-pandemic-government-a9399101.html|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Vallance said that 60% of the UK's population will need to become infected for herd immunity to be achieved.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mueller |first=Benjamin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/world/europe/coronavirus-britain-boris-johnson.html |title=As Europe Shuts Down, Britain Takes a Different, and Contentious, Approach |date=13 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2020 |issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313232126/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/world/europe/coronavirus-britain-boris-johnson.html|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> This stance was criticised by experts who said that it would lead to hundreds of thousands deaths and overwhelm the NHS. Over 200 scientists urged the government to rethink the approach in an open letter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyle |first1=Christina |title=On coronavirus containment, Britain's Johnson is less restrictive than other European leaders |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-19/british-prime-minister-boris-johnsons-coronavirus-european-leaders |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Health Secretary Matt Hancock denied that herd immunity was a plan for the UK, although the [[Department of Health and Social Care]] said that \"herd immunity is a natural byproduct of an [[epidemic]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=What is herd immunity and is it an option for dealing with the UK coronavirus pandemic? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-herd-immunity-meaning-definition-what-vaccine-immune-covid-19-a9397871.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 4 April, ''[[The Times]]'' reported that the government's science adviser, Graham Medley, is still advocating a \"herd immunity\" strategy.<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnsons-coronavirus-adviser-calls-for-a-way-out-of-lockdown-rd58g6tc9 'Boris Johnson's coronavirus adviser calls for a way out of lockdown - Britain may still need to adopt herd immunity'], ''The Times'', 4/4/20.</ref> There was also criticism over a lack of transparency around the scientific evidence being used to inform the government response, with a letter published in [[the Lancet]] on 17 March calling on the government to openly share its data and models as a matter of urgency.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alwan|first=Nisreen A|last2=Bhopal|first2=Raj|last3=Burgess|first3=Rochelle A|last4=Colburn|first4=Tim|last5=Cuevas|first5=Luis E|last6=Smith|first6=George Davey|last7=Egger|first7=Matthias|last8=Eldridge|first8=Sandra|last9=Gallo|first9=Valentina|last10=Gilthorpe|first10=Mark S|last11=Greenhalgh|first11=Trish|date=17 March 2020|title=Evidence informing the UK's COVID-19 public health response must be transparent|journal=The Lancet|volume=395|issue=10229|pages=1036\u20131037|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(20)30667-x|pmid=32197104|issn=0140-6736|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, Boris Johnson said in an interview with [[BBC News]]: \"The most important thing now is that we prepare against a possible very significant expansion of coronavirus in the UK population\". This came after the 39th case in the UK was confirmed and over a month after the first confirmed case in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550 |title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302195801/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, a [[BBC One]] programme ''Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know'' addressed questions from the public on the outbreak.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |title=BBC News Special \u2013 Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know |date=2 March 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303115141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, the Coronavirus Action Plan was unveiled.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The next day, as the total number of cases in the UK stood at 51, the government declared the coronavirus pandemic as a \"level 4 incident\",<ref name=Discombe3March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/quality-and-performance/national-incident-over-coronavirus-allows-nhse-to-command-local-resources/7027045.article |title=National incident over coronavirus allows NHSE to command local resources |last=Discombe |first=Matt |date=3 March 2020 |website=[[Health Service Journal]] |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> permitting NHS England to take command of all NHS resources.<ref name=Discombe3March2020/><ref name=Sr2020>{{Cite book |last=Warnick |first=Mark S. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gaTDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA90&dq=nhs+Level+4+incident#v=onepage |title=Emergency Incident Management Systems: Fundamentals and Applications |last2=Sr |first2=Louis N. Molino |date=2020 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=978-1-119-26711-9 |edition=Second |location= |pages=89\u201390}}</ref> Planning has been made for [[behaviour change (public health)|behaviour changing]] publicity including good hygiene and respiratory hygiene (\"catch it, bin it, kill it\"),<ref name=Campbell3Mar2020>{{Cite news |last=Campbell |first=Denis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/explained-uk-coronavirus-action-plan |title=Explained: UK's coronavirus action plan |date=3 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live |last2=Siddique |first2=Haroon |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Weaver |first3=Matthew|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304035015/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/explained-uk-coronavirus-action-plan|archive-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> a simple measure which helps in delaying the peak of the infection and buys time for the testing of drugs and initial development of vaccines.<ref name=Plan2020 /> Primary care has been issued guidance.<ref name=Razai6March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Razai |first=Mohammad S. |last2=Doerholt |first2=Katja |last3=Ladhani |first3=Shamez |last4=Oakeshott |first4=Pippa |date=6 March 2020 |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (covid-19): a guide for UK GPs |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m800 |journal=BMJ |volume=368 |pages=m800 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m800 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32144127|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309150416/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m800|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nControversy over apparent errors that the Government had made continued. For example, Dr. [[Richard Horton (editor)|Richard Horton]], editor of ''The Lancet'' told BBC's ''Question Time'' that \"We knew in the last week of January that this was coming. The message from China was absolutely clear that a new virus with pandemic potential was hitting cities. ... We knew that 11 weeks ago and then we wasted February when we could have acted.\"<ref>[https://inews.co.uk/news/health/question-time-richard-horton-uk-coronavirus-nhs-prepared-response-2520479 'Question Time: Medical expert Richard Horton says UK \"wasted February\" when it should have been preparing NHS for coronavirus cases'], ''INews'', 27/3/20. See also:  [https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)30727-3/fulltext 'COVID-19 and the NHS \"a national scandal\"'], ''The Lancet'', Editorial, 28/3/20.</ref>\n\nPublic Health England has also been involved with efforts to support the [[British Overseas Territories]] against the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/06/public-health-england-joins-cayman-in-coronavirus-response-efforts/ |title=Public Health England joins Cayman in coronavirus response efforts |first=Reshma |last=Ragoonath |date=7 March 2020 |website=Cayman Compass|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307160127/https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/06/public-health-england-joins-cayman-in-coronavirus-response-efforts/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gibraltar.gov.gi/press-releases/government-statement-on-covid-19-1412020-5647 |title=Government Statement on COVID-19 \u2013 141/2020 |website=Government of Gibraltar|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309191352/https://www.gibraltar.gov.gi/press-releases/government-statement-on-covid-19-1412020-5647|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson said that he had contracted coronavirus and was self-isolating and that he would continue to lead the Government's response to coronavirus through [[Videotelephony|video conference]].<ref name=Boris />  On the evening of 5 April the Prime Minister was admitted to hospital for tests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52177125|title=Boris Johnson in hospital over virus symptoms|work=BBC News|date=6 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The next day he was moved to the [[intensive care unit]] at [[St Thomas' Hospital]], and Dominic Raab was asked to deputise for him.<ref name=BorisJohnsonICU/>\n\n==== Regulations and legislation ====\n[[File:Restaurant in London offering home deliveries during the Coronavirus pandemic March 2020.jpg|thumb|Restaurant in London offering home deliveries after dining in was banned. March 2020.]]\nThe government published the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]]<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303041542/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made |date=3 March 2020 }} Legislation.gov.uk</ref> on 10 February 2020, a [[statutory instrument (UK)|statutory instrument]] covering the legal framework behind the government's initial containment and isolation strategies and its organisation of the national reaction to the virus. Other published regulations include changes to [[Statutory sick pay|Statutory Sick Pay]] (into force on 13 March),<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/287/contents/made The Statutory Sick Pay (General) (Coronavirus Amendment) Regulations 2020] Leglisation.gov.uk</ref> and changes to [[Employment and Support Allowance]] and [[Universal Credit]] (also 13 March).<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/289/contents/made The Employment and Support Allowance and Universal Credit (Coronavirus Disease) Regulations 2020] Leglisation.gov.uk</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the government introduced the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]], which grants the government discretionary [[emergency powers]] in the areas of the NHS, social care, schools, police, the Border Force, local councils, funerals and courts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342 |last=Heffer |first=Greg |title=Coronavirus Bill: Emergency laws to contain spread of COVID-19 published |website=[[Sky News]] |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318201123/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The act received [[royal assent]] on 25 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18318799.jacob-rees-mogg-says-parliament-will-return-easter-recess/ |last=Carmichael |first=Hannah |title=Jacob Rees-Mogg says Parliament will return after Easter recess |newspaper=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319155145/https://www.thenational.scot/news/18318799.jacob-rees-mogg-says-parliament-will-return-easter-recess/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClosures to pubs, restaurants and indoor sports and leisure facilities were imposed via the Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020.<ref>[https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020 UK Statutory Instruments 2020 No. 327 Table of contents] ''www.legislation.gov.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe restrictions on movements, except for allowed purposes are:\n*[[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]]<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/350/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020 UK Statutory Instruments 2020 No. 350 Table of contents] ''www.legislation.gov.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref>\n*''Health Protection (Coronavirus) (Restrictions) (Scotland) Regulations 2020''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ssi/2020/103/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus) (Restrictions) (Scotland) Regulations 2020|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref>\n* ''Health Protection (Coronavirus Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/wsi/2020/353/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref>\n*''The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (Northern Ireland) Regulations 2020''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health-ni.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/health/Coronavirus-Restrictiions-Regs-2020.pdf |title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2020 |website=Department of Health (Northern Ireland)}}</ref>\n\n====Communications====\n[[File:GOV.UK COVID-19 text.png|thumb|alt=GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives. |UK Government advisory SMS message, 24 March 2020]]\n\nThe government has held daily evening press conferences since the 17 March. These were mostly hosted by Boris Johnson with cabinet ministers (often Matt Hancock) and senior scientific advisors.<ref>Manchester Evening News [https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/uk-news/live-matt-hancock-coronavirus-press-17972794 RECAP: Matt Hancock holds daily press conference on UK's coronavirus response] ''www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk'', accessed 25 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, all major mobile telephony providers, acting upon a government request, sent out an [[SMS message]] to each of their customers, with advice on staying isolated.<ref name=\"BBC-52017451\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451 |first1=Rory |last1=Cellan-Jones |website=BBC News |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref> This was the first ever use of the facility.<ref name=\"BBC-52017451\" /> Although the government in 2013 endorsed the use of [[Cell Broadcast]] to send official [[Emergency population warning|emergency messages]] to all mobile phones, and has tested such a system, it has never actually been implemented. Backer [[Toby Harris]] said that the government had not yet agreed upon who would fund and govern such a system.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jim |last=Waterson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/government-ignored-advice-set-up-uk-emergency-alert-system |title=Government ignored advice to set up UK emergency alert system |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Sweney |first=Mark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/24/uk-mobile-firms-asked-to-alert-britons-to-heed-coronavirus-lockdown |title=UK mobile firms asked to alert Britons to heed coronavirus lockdown |date=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Law and order===\nOn 17 March, trials lasting longer than three days were postponed until May in England and Wales, while Scottish courts were not starting any new trial indefinitely. In England and Wales those cases already running would continue in the hope of reaching a conclusion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bowcott |first=Owen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/mar/18/longer-criminal-trials-in-england-and-wales-to-be-delayed-due-to-covid-19 |title=Longer criminal trials in England and Wales to be delayed due to Covid-19 |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318222623/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/mar/18/longer-criminal-trials-in-england-and-wales-to-be-delayed-due-to-covid-19 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stubley |first=Peter |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-trials-court-jail-delays-lord-chief-justice-a9407936.html |title=Coronavirus: Criminal trials longer than three days to be put on hold |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318152500/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-trials-court-jail-delays-lord-chief-justice-a9407936.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> A poll published on 20 March claimed that only 23% of British adults were strictly following the government's coronavirus advice.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only a quarter of UK adults are strictly following government's coronavirus advice, poll finds |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/quarter-uk-adults-strictly-following-governments-coronavirus/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Personal attacks====\n{{Further|List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United Kingdom}}\nThere have been [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United Kingdom|reports of hate incidents]] against Italian and Chinese persons<ref name=\"Guardian Racism\">{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Lucy |title=Chinese in UK report 'shocking' levels of racism after coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/09/chinese-in-uk-report-shocking-levels-of-racism-after-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=9 February 2020}}</ref> and a Singaporean student was assaulted in London in an attack that police linked to coronavirus fears.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51736755 |title=Coronavirus: Men wanted over racist Oxford Street attack on student |work=BBC News |accessdate=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304122002/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51736755|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Prisons====\nThe government released specific guidance to prisons in the event of coronavirus symptoms or cases, specifically the rule that \"any prisoner or detainee with a new, continuous cough or a high temperature should be placed in [[protective isolation]] for 7 days\".<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: prisons and other prescribed places of detention guidance |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320013825/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> There are around 83,000 prisoners in England and Wales.<ref name=Grierson26Mar2020/>\n\nOn 14 March, a prison officer in [[HMP High Down]] in Surrey tested positive for the virus and was sent home to self-isolate. Four officers who had contact with him were placed in isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prison officer tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-51917123 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, the first coronavirus case was reported within the UK prison population. The prisoner, who had been serving time in [[HMP Manchester]] (commonly referred to as Strangeways), was moved to a hospital. While no other prisoners or staff tested positive for the virus, thirteen prisoners and four members of staff were put into isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bulman |first1=May |title=First UK prisoner infected with coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=18 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161647/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Prison visits remained open, but the situation is being monitored.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slater |first1=Chris |title=Strangeways prisoner tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210353/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in Wales were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320154011/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Another prison officer tested positive on 20 March at [[HMP Whitemoor]] near [[March, Cambridgeshire|March]], [[Cambridgeshire]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elworthy |first1=John |title=Ministry of Justice confirm an officer at top security Whitemoor Prison, March, tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/whitemoor-prison-officer-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-1-6572331 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Cambs Times |date=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321195409/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/whitemoor-prison-officer-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-1-6572331 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the case in HMP Manchester, public services think tank [[Reform (think tank)|Reform]] called for the release of 2,305 \"low-risk\" offenders on short sentences to reduce the risk of coronavirus on the prison population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Ministers urged to release hundreds of prisoners on short sentences to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=20 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320165607/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Their report argues that prison are \"overcrowded [with] insanitary conditions and poor-quality healthcare\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Reducing the prison population: Extending Home Detention Curfew and scrapping short sentences {{!}} Reform |url=https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |website=reform.uk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320165609/https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Similar actions have been taken in Iran and the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319212202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Former justice secretary [[David Gauke]] echoed similar sentiments, citing the \"churn\" of prisoners going in and out of prison as a risk.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Townsend |first1=Mark |last2=Savage |first2=Mark |last3=Doward |first3=Jamie |title=Prisons 'could see 800 deaths' from coronavirus without protective measures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Observer |date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321221813/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, a prisoner tested positive for the virus at [[HMP Birmingham]] and was placed into isolation. The prison was not placed into full lockdown, but made the decision to restrict access.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Carl |title=Prisoner at HMP Birmingham tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/prisoner-hmp-birmingham-tests-positive-17967296 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, a prisoner at [[HMP Oakwood]] near [[Wolverhampton]] tested positive for the virus and was placed into isolation. Visits to the prison were not stopped, but it is believed they were reduced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guttridge |first1=Richard |title=Prisons 'ready to act' but visits allowed as HMP Oakwood coronavirus case confirmed |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/health/coronavirus-covid19/2020/03/23/prisons-ready-to-act-on-coronavirus-but-visits-still-allowed/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=www.expressandstar.com |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the Ministry of Justice announced that prison visits would be suspended and that inmates would be confined to their cells.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pegg |first1=David |last2=Allison |first2=Eric |title=Release inmates or face jail pandemic, say prison governors |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/25/release-prisoners-or-face-jail-pandemic-says-chief |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> In order to maintain communication between prisoners and their families, the government promised 900 secure phones to 55 prisons, with calls being monitored and time-limited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Prison visits cancelled |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prison-visits-cancelled |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=25 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324181945/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prison-visits-cancelled |archivedate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In a committee meeting on the same day, Justice Secretary [[Robert Buckland]] suggested that 50 pregnant inmates might be given early release, and another 9,000 inmates awaiting trial could be transferred to bail hostels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inmates could be freed to ease virus jail pressures |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52029581 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, it was reported that 84-year-old convicted paedophile Edwin Hillier<ref>{{cite news |title=School caretaker jailed for child abuse |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-35633835 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=22 February 2016}}</ref> had died from COVID-19 on 22 March at [[HMP Littlehey]] in Cambridgeshire, becoming the first inmate in the UK to die from the virus.<ref name=Grierson26Mar2020>{{cite news |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |title=Man, 84, becomes first UK prisoner to die with coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/first-prisoner-in-uk-dies-from-coronavirus |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Another 66-year-old male inmate died from COVID-19 on 26 March at HMP Manchester.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man, 84, is first UK prison coronavirus death |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-52047003 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> As of 5pm on 5 April 2020, 107 cases had been confirmed in 38 UK jails, and nine prisoners with coronavirus had died.<ref name=\"JBN-07Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Jamie |first1=Bennett-Ness |title=First coronavirus death confirmed inside Belmarsh prison |url=https://www.newsshopper.co.uk/news/18363807.first-coronavirus-death-confirmed-inside-belmarsh-prison/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=News Shopper |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, the Ministry of Justice ordered 500 modular buildings, reportedly adapted from shipping containers, to provide additional single prison cell accommodation at six jails: HMPs [[HMP North Sea Camp|North Sea Camp]], Littlehey, [[HM Prison Hollesley Bay|Hollesley Bay]], [[HMP Highpoint|Highpoint]], [[HMP Moorland|Moorland]], [[HMP Lindholme|Lindholme]] and [[HM Prison Humber|Humber]].<ref name=\"TCI-14Apr2020\">{{cite news |title=Quick fix for prison expansion |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/quick-fix-for-prison-expansion |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The Construction Index |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration centres====\nDuring mid-March, 300 people were released from [[Immigration detention in the United Kingdom|immigration detention]] centres because of the pandemic following a campaign by charities concerned with an outbreak of COVID-19 in the centres.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Diane |title=Home Office releases 300 from detention centres amid Covid-19 pandemic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/home-office-releases-300-from-detention-centres-amid-covid-19-pandemic |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March, it was reported that three [[Immigration detention in the United Kingdom|immigration detention centres]] had reported cases of people with coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Titheradge |first=Dr Faye Kirkland and Noel |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52017311 |title=Coronavirus 'symptoms' at three detention centres |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 2 April, a letter leaked from [[G4S]], a company running immigration detention centres for the [[Home Office]], revealed that detainees who were at high risk from COVID-19 were being put in [[Solitary confinement|solitary confinement]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Diane |title=Revealed: at-risk immigration detainees 'to be put in solitary confinement' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/revealed-at-risk-immigration-detainees-to-be-put-in-solitary-confinement |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403112706/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/02/revealed-at-risk-immigration-detainees-to-be-put-in-solitary-confinement |archivedate=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Policing====\nOn 26 March, in an attempt to emphasise the importance of following the social distancing instructions given by the government, the police were given powers to impose fines on individuals gathered in groups or who refuse to return home when asked to.<ref name=\"bbc_52101040\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52101040 |title=Coronavirus: Police told to be 'consistent' with lockdown approach |date=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref> By 31 March, some police forces, and individual officers, were being criticised by a variety of people - citizens,<ref name=overthetop/> former [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] judge [[Jonathan Sumption, Lord Sumption|Lord Sumption]],<ref name=\"bbc_52101040\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Lord Sumption brands Derbyshire Police 'disgraceful' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-52095857 |work=BBC News |accessdate=4 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331190857/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-52095857 |archivedate=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> former [[Secretary of State for Justice|justice secretary]] [[David Gauke]],<ref name=overthetop>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Peak District drone police criticised for 'lockdown shaming' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-52055201 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=27 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330225339/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-52055201 |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> former [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|chancellor]] [[George Osborne]],<ref name=GOPO>{{cite news |last1=Slatter |first1=Nigel |title=Derbyshire police issue defiant response after heavy criticism from ex-chancellor |url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/derbyshire-police-criticism-george-osborne-4002920 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=[[Derby Telegraph]] |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402052359/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/derbyshire-police-criticism-george-osborne-4002920 |archivedate=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> privacy and civil liberties group [[Big Brother Watch]]<ref name=overthetop/> - for over-zealous and incorrect application of the new powers. Police had put black dye into [[Harpur Hill Quarry]], and, using a [[Miniature UAV|drone]], filmed people before posting the images on social media.<ref name=GOPO/> New guidance was released by the [[National Police Chiefs Council]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Vikram Dodd Police and crime correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/uk-police-reissued-with-guidance-on-enforcing-coronavirus-lockdown |title=UK coronavirus lockdown: police reissued with guidance on enforcement &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===National health services ===\n====Appointments and self-isolation====\n[[File:Coronavirus Pod at Hull Royal Infirmary (geograph 6406192).jpg|thumb|A Coronavirus 'pod' at [[Hull Royal Infirmary]].]]\nIn March, hospitals in England begin to prepare for the cancellation of all non-urgent elective procedures.<ref name=\"Ilman12March2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/free-for-non-subscribers/exclusive-nhs-prepares-to-cancel-elective-ops-in-readiness-for-covid-19-surge/7027110.article |title=Exclusive: NHS prepares to cancel elective ops in readiness for covid-19 surge |last=Illman |first=James |date=12 March 2020 |website=Health Service Journal |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 22 March, the government announced that it would be asking about 1.5 million people (everyone in England with certain health conditions that carry serious risk if infected) to self-isolate for 12 weeks. They were to be notified by mail or text messaged by their NHS general practitioners, and provided deliveries of medication, food, and household essentials, delivered by pharmacists and local governments, and at least initially paid for by the UK government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/who-million-vulnerable-self-isolate-weeks-a4394311.html |title=Who are the 1.5m vulnerable people self-isolating for 12 weeks? |date=23 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard}}</ref> Members of the public were told to stay at home, should they suspect they have symptoms of covid-19, and not visit a GP, pharmacy, or hospital.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Michelle |title=Coronavirus: What is shielding? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-51997151 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326115215/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-51997151 |archivedate=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> For advice, the public were told to use a dedicated online self-assessment form before calling [[NHS 111]], the non-emergency medical helpline.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Michelle |title=Coronavirus: NHS 111 has 1.7 million queries in 15 days |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52120804 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401153344/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52120804 |archivedate=1 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Equipment====\n[[File:Face masks 2020.jpg|thumb|Face masks given to NHS staff March 2020]]\nOn 16 March, Boris Johnson met with business leaders via conference call and set them the target of delivering 30,000 [[ventilator]]s in a fortnight; the government also declined to join an emergency [[European Union]] scheme to procure ventilators and other emergency equipment like [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for hospital staff, stating that the UK was no longer part of the EU and that this was area in which it was making its own efforts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Francis |last2=O'Neill |first2=Sean |last3=Waterfield |first3=Bruno |last4=Courea |first4=Eleni |title=Ventilator crunch looms after snubbing EU action |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ventilator-crunch-looms-after-snubbing-eu-action-6s7tg3vnw |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=27 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327042903/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ventilator-crunch-looms-after-snubbing-eu-action-6s7tg3vnw |archivedate=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, it was announced that NHS England had negotiated a deal to use, at cost price, almost the entire private health system, bringing 8,000 beds and 1,100 ventilators into the project.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989183 |title=NHS deal will provide thousands of extra beds |work=BBC News |date=21 March 2020|access-date = 23 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323072035/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989183|archive-date = 23 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Existing ventilator stocks stood at 5,900 at the beginning of the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=UK government sends ventilator blueprints to major manufacturers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/16/vauxhall-owner-psa-car-shuts-european-plants-amid-coronavirus-fears |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325105715/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/16/vauxhall-owner-psa-car-shuts-european-plants-amid-coronavirus-fears |archivedate=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, [[primary care]] magazine ''[[Pulse (magazine)|Pulse]]'' reported doctors were receiving out of date PPE that had had its 2016 [[Shelf life|use-by]] date covered with a sticker saying \"2021\".<ref name=\"outofdateppe\">{{cite news |last1=Legraien |first1=Lea |title=GPs being sent 'out-of-date' face masks with 'concealed' best before dates |url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/clinical/clinical-specialties/respiratory-/gps-being-sent-out-of-date-face-masks-with-concealed-best-before-dates/20040359.article |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[Pulse (magazine)|Pulse]] |date=16 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326200326/http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/clinical/clinical-specialties/respiratory-/gps-being-sent-out-of-date-face-masks-with-concealed-best-before-dates/20040359.article |archivedate=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, the government offered reassurance that this was safe.<ref name=Legrain17March2020>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/clinical/clinical-specialties/respiratory-/out-of-date-face-masks-distributed-to-gps-safe-to-use-says-government/20040349.article|title=Out-of-date face masks distributed to GPs 'safe' to use, says Government|last=Legraien|first=Lea|date=17 March 2020|website=Pulse Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Earlier in the month, in response to a survey of Pulse's readership, two of five GPs reported they still did not have PPE to protect them from coronavirus.<ref name=\"outofdateppe\"/> Some of these concerns were raised with Johnson during [[Prime Minister's Questions]], to which the Prime Minister replied the UK had \"stockpiles\" of PPE.<ref>{{cite news |title=PM issues assurances over protective gear for NHS staff |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[Evening Express (Scotland)|Evening Express]] |agency=[[Press Association]]|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/pm-issues-assurances-over-protective-gear-for-nhs-staff-amid-concern/ |date=18 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401211858/https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/pm-issues-assurances-over-protective-gear-for-nhs-staff-amid-concern/ |archivedate=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, the [[The Doctors\u2019 Association UK|Doctors' Association]] reported NHS staff felt they were being put at risk due to lack of PPE.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: NHS staff 'at risk' over lack of protective gear |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51950276 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321070815/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51950276 |archivedate=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 March, in a letter with 3,963 signatures published in ''[[The Times]]'', NHS staff asked Johnson to \"protect the lives of the life-savers\" and resolve the what they saw as the \"unacceptable\" shortage of protective equipment.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus letter to the editor: Without protection, NHS staff are cannon fodder |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-letter-to-the-editor-without-protection-nhs-staff-are-cannon-fodder-tsw0nmbsx |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=The Times |date=22 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321221638/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coronavirus-letter-to-the-editor-without-protection-nhs-staff-are-cannon-fodder-tsw0nmbsx |archivedate=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Hancock admits 'challenges' in supplying medics with protective equipment |url=https://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/national/18326318.hancock-admits-challenges-supplying-medics-protective-equipment/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Thurrock Gazette |agency=[[Press Association ]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401213239/https://www.thurrockgazette.co.uk/news/national/18326318.hancock-admits-challenges-supplying-medics-protective-equipment/ |archivedate=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 March, in an effort to meet demand and due to concerns about the rising number of medics becoming ill after exposure to the virus, the NHS asked [[Hardware store|DIY]] stores to donate PPE for use by NHS staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Laura |last2=Gardner |first2=Bill |title=NHS asks DIY stores to donate protective equipment to staff on the coronavirus frontline |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/23/nhs-asks-diy-stores-donate-protective-equipment-staff-coronavirus/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331102758/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/23/nhs-asks-diy-stores-donate-protective-equipment-staff-coronavirus/ |archivedate=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hancock admitted there were \"challenges\" with supplying PPE to NHS staff and said a million masks had been bought that weekend.<ref>{{cite news |authorlink1=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329204359/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52000150 |title=Coronavirus: Hancock admits 'challenges' over NHS equipment |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52000150 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=23 March 2020 |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, the government said there was enough PPE for everyone in the NHS who needed it; this was contradicted by the [[Royal College of Nursing]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Drakeford claims enough protective kit for NHS despite concerns |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52018653 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326112144/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52018653 |archivedate=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA), which said some of the PPE doctors had received were inadequate<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Minister admits PPE 'challenges and problems' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52079429 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329232522/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52079429 |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and medics were resorting to wearing DIY PPE they had purchased themselves.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Continuing issues with protective kit for NHS, says minister |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52035545 |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327191643/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52035545 |archivedate=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The BMA warned that without enough PPE doctors would die.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gibbons |first1=Katie |last2=Bennett |first2=Rosemary |title=Doctors forced to buy safety gear from DIY stores |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/doctors-forced-to-buy-safety-gear-from-diy-stores-hjg9fbsgl |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Times |date=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330050416/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/doctors-forced-to-buy-safety-gear-from-diy-stores-hjg9fbsgl |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC05602 (49675594083).jpg|thumb|People in London wear masks on 19 March 2020|alt=]]\nOn March 31, 10,000 health workers wrote to the prime minister demanding better safeguards, including the right PPE.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gibbons |first1=Katie |last2=Lay |first2=Kat |title=NHS staff beg Boris Johnson: Give us the right protective coronavirus gear |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-staff-beg-boris-johnson-give-us-the-right-protective-coronavirus-gear-cs77576v6 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Times |date=31 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404114350/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nhs-staff-beg-boris-johnson-give-us-the-right-protective-coronavirus-gear-cs77576v6 |archivedate=4 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 April, the government said 390 million pieces of PPE had been distributed to the health service in the past fortnight. The [[Royal College of Midwives]]<ref name=\"RCM\">{{cite news |last1=Milmo |first1=Cahal |title=Coronavirus: Unions declare PPE shortage is 'crisis within a crisis' despite Downing Street insistence that vital supplies are being delivered |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-latest-unions-warn-ppe-shortage-crisis-within-crisis-deliveries-covid-19-outbreak-2525801 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] |date=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402112439/https://inews.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-latest-unions-warn-ppe-shortage-crisis-within-crisis-deliveries-covid-19-outbreak-2525801 |archivedate=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the BMA said that the supplies had yet to reach medical staff.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Councils appeal for protective equipment |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-52125800 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220330/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-52125800 |archivedate=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCM, in a joint statement with unions, including [[Unite the Union|Unite]], [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]] and the [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]], said the lack of PPE was now 'a crisis within a crisis'.<ref name=\"RCM\"/>\n\nOn 29 March the government issued specification for the \"minimally clinically acceptable\" manufacturer and use of [[Continuous Positive Airway Pressure]] (CPAP) machines.<ref>{{cite web |title=Specification for Rapidly Manufactured CPAP System to be used during the coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/specification-for-rapidly-manufactured-cpap-system-to-be-used-during-the-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220830/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/specification-for-rapidly-manufactured-cpap-system-to-be-used-during-the-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak |archivedate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Staffing====\nOn 1 March, Hancock said retired NHS staff might be asked to return to work to help with the crisis.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bosotti |first1=Aurora |title=Coronavirus outbreak: Matt Hancock confirms retired NHS staff may be called back into work |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1249352/Coronavirus-outbreak-Matt-Hancock-UK-NHS-staff-COVID-19-epidemic-latest-news |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=1 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329114438/https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1249352/Coronavirus-outbreak-Matt-Hancock-UK-NHS-staff-COVID-19-epidemic-latest-news |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The request was issued on 19 March and included final year medical students.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 'Your NHS needs you' - Thousands of retired doctors and nurses urged to return |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-your-nhs-needs-you-thousands-of-retired-doctors-and-nurses-urged-to-return-11960514 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[Sky News]] |date=19 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330062915/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-your-nhs-needs-you-thousands-of-retired-doctors-and-nurses-urged-to-return-11960514 |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 March, Boris Johnson announced that more than 20,000 former NHS staff were returning to work in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Milne |first1=Oliver |title=More than 20,000 retired NHS staff will re-join service for coronavirus fight |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-more-20000-retired-nhs-21776375 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330112554/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-more-20000-retired-nhs-21776375 |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, it was announced that the NHS had negotiated a deal to use, at cost price, almost the entire private health system, bringing 20,000 medical staff into the national effort.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn 24 March, Matt Hancock announced the start of a scheme to recruit 250,000 volunteers to support the NHS through the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 250,000 people urged to become volunteers to help NHS and fight Covid-19 |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/government-launches-campaign-recruit-250000-nhs-volunteers-matt-hancock/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329030238/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/government-launches-campaign-recruit-250000-nhs-volunteers-matt-hancock/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The volunteers would carry out jobs like collecting and deliver shopping, medication or \"other essential supplies\" for people in isolation; transporting equipment and medication between NHS services; transporting medically fit patients and providing telephone support to people at risk of loneliness because of self-isolation.<ref name=\"cauldield\">{{cite news |last1=Caulfield |first1=Chris |title=Call for NHS volunteers paused as 750,000 sign up |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/29/call-nhs-volunteers-paused-as750000-sign-12473430/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329125544/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/29/call-nhs-volunteers-paused-as750000-sign-12473430/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The target was surpassed in 24 hours and was raised to 750,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Volunteer target raised to 750,000 after more than half a million people sign up to help NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-more-than-half-a-million-people-volunteer-to-help-nhs/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329021015/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-more-than-half-a-million-people-volunteer-to-help-nhs/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The scheme was paused on 29 March after the new target was reached.<ref name=\"cauldield\"/>\n\n====Beds====\nThe National Health Service freed up 30,000 beds by discharging patients who were well enough and delaying non-emergency treatment,<ref name=\"hsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/policy-and-regulation/nhs-block-books-almost-all-private-hospital-sector-capacity-to-fight-covid-19/7027196.article|title=NHS block books almost all private hospital sector capacity to fight covid-19|first=James|last=Illman|date=21 March 2020|website=Health Service Journal}}</ref> and acquired use of 20,000 beds in private sector facilities.<ref name=\"hsj\" />  Emergency building work was undertaken to add capacity to existing hospitals, 52 beds in Wigan, for example.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/health/coronavirus/large-crane-block-wigan-lane-partially-covid-19-emergency-ward-work-escalates-2524891|title=Large crane to block Wigan Lane partially as Covid-19 emergency ward work escalates|website=www.wigantoday.net}}</ref>\n\n====NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals====\n{{main|NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals}}\nOn 24 March, it was announced that NHS England would establish a [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals|temporary critical care hospital]], [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], in the [[Excel London]] conference centre.<ref name=\"bbc_52018477\"/> The field hospital would have 4,000 beds in two wards.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Denis |last2=Dodd |first2=Vikram |title=NHS plans to turn ExCeL centre into coronavirus hospital |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/nhs-plans-to-turn-excel-centre-into-coronavirus-hospital?CMP=share_btn_tw |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Goodall |first1=Lewis |title=NEW: Matt Hancock announces a new temporary hospital - the ExCel centre in London is being converted into the \"Nightingale Hospital\" |url=https://twitter.com/lewis_goodall/status/1242492246605389825 |website=@lewis_goodall |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Also on 24 March, it was reported that NHS Wales were looking at the [[Principality Stadium]] in Cardiff for a similar purpose.<ref name=\"itv_2020-03-25\"/> On 25 March, it was confirmed that NHS Scotland had identified Glasgow's [[SEC Centre]] exhibition and conference facility as a potential site for a similar hospital in Scotland.<ref name=\"bbc_52045977\"/> On 26 March it was reported that the Northern Ireland health service was also looking for potential sites to use for temporary hospitals.<ref name=\"bt_20200327\"/> On 27 March, NHS England announced that they would be establishing more NHS Nightingale Hospitals in other major UK conference centres to help to deal with the large number of cases expected,<ref name=\"ITV-2020-03-27\"/> at the [[National Exhibition Centre]], Birmingham and at [[Manchester Central Convention Complex]].<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Lucy |title=UK coronavirus live: rate of infection doubling every three to four days, says Gove |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/27/uk-coronavirus-live-rough-sleepers-nhs-applause-covid-19-latest-news#block-5e7e33ce8f08af215f6fca9e |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The London hospital opened 3 April,<ref>{{cite news |title=First coronavirus field hospital opens in London |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598 |accessdate=4 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> and received its first patients on 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52208156 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson spends second night in intensive care |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n[[File:St Bartholomew's Episcopal Church, Gourock, COVID closure.jpg|thumb|Notice at Episcopal Church in [[Gourock]]; No public services until further notice.]]\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\nThe [[Church of England]] and other [[Anglican Communion|Anglican]] churches in the British Isles suspended in-person worship during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Church of England suspends public worship over coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-church/church-of-england-suspends-public-worship-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN2142GE |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Church and religious services off across Wales |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-51974782 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Piskies 2020\">{{cite web | last=Walker | first=Donald | title=Coronavirus \u2013 Suspension of Church Services | website=The Scottish Episcopal Church | date=17 March 2020 | url=https://www.scotland.anglican.org/coronavirus-cessation-of-church-services/ | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] led a virtual service that was broadcast on 39 local BBC stations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Archbishop of Canterbury to lead first virtual Church of England service |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-archbishop-of-canterbury-to-lead-first-virtual-church-of-england-service-11960268 |publisher=Sky News |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Catholic Church]], [[Methodist Church in Great Britain]] and the [[Society of Friends]] also put a temporary moratorium on public worship.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020\">{{cite web |last1=Sherwood |first1=Harriet |title=Church of England suspends all services over coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/church-of-england-suspends-services-coronavirus |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Catholic churches preparing to suspend Mass |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51887510 |publisher=BBC |language=English |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe chief rabbi in the United Kingdom advised the suspension of Jewish worship in synagogues and the [[Muslim Council of Britain]] has ordered the closure of mosques in the country.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020\"/>\n\n===Research and innovation===\nExisting research<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/mrc-global-infectious-disease-analysis/covid-19/\n |title=COVID-19 reports |website=Imperial College London |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> by the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)]] Centre for Global Infectious Disease Analysis informs understanding of the COVID-19 outbreak and Diamond Light Source allows scientists to design and develop compounds that may lead to clinical drugs to tackle it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.diamond.ac.uk/covid-19.html |title=Shining our expertise on Coronavirus |website=Diamond|access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[UK Research and Innovation]] announced <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukri.org/news/launch-of-new-website-explaining-the-science-behind-coronavirus/ |title=Launch of new website explaining the science behind coronavirus |website=UK Research and Innovation |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> the launch of a website to explain the scientific  evidence and the facts about the virus, the disease, the epidemic, and its control, in a bid to dispel misinformation. The editorial team come from [[University of Oxford]], [[European Bioinformatics Institute]], [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], [[Imperial College London]], [[University of Glasgow]] and [[King's College London]].\n\nUK Research and Innovation also announced<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukri.org/news/covid-19-vaccine-therapy-research-boosted-by-six-new-projects-in-rapid-response/\n |title=COVID-19 vaccine & therapy research boosted by six new projects in rapid response |website=UK Research and Innovation |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> \u00a320 million for rapid response R&D projects such as a project to develop a vaccine and another to test the viability of existing drugs to treat the virus. A COVID-19 Genomics UK Consortium has been established to deliver large-scale, rapid sequencing of the cause of the disease<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukri.org/news/uk-launches-whole-genome-sequence-alliance-to-map-spread-of-coronavirus/\n |title=UK launches whole genome sequence alliance to map spread of coronavirus |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n, and \u00a3260 million to the [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] to support its vaccine development work against COVID-19 and other emerging infectious diseases<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cepi.net/news_cepi/uk-boosts-support-for-cepi-to-spur-covid-19-vaccine-development/ |title=UK boosts support for CEPI to spur COVID-19 vaccine development |website=Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations |access-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> .\n\n[[Innovate UK]] announced \u00a320 million funding for innovative businesses<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/help-find-new-ways-to-ease-global-disruption-apply-for-funding/ |title=Help find new ways to ease global disruption: apply for funding |website=GOV.UK |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and is also working closely with [[Formula 1]] and a collective of UK-based teams, engine manufacturers and their respective technology arms as part of Project Pitlane to co-ordinate its work.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ukri.org/news/formula-1s-project-pitlane-will-deliver-ventilators-to-help-treat-covid-19-patients/\n |title=Formula 1's Project Pitlane will support the manufacture of medical devices to help treat Covid-19 patients |website=UK Research and Innovation |access-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\nOn 5 March, the England\u2013Italy fixtures in the men's and women's' [[Six Nations Championship]] tournaments, set to be played in Rome on 14 and 15 March, were postponed by tournament organisers after the Italian government introduced restrictions on attendances to sporting events.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |website=BBC Sport |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306233340/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Scotland's Women's [[Women's Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] home fixture against France on 7 March was also postponed after one Scotland player tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"bbc_women_sixnations\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308061514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTo contain the spread of the virus the [[Premier League]] announced on 6 March an end to pre-match fair play handshakes between players and officials.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51760339 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League & EFL ditch pre-match fair-play handshakes |website=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307001827/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51760339|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 March, the Premier League match between [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] was postponed in light of confirmation that [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]] had contracted the virus. Marinakis had met with several Arsenal players when the London side hosted Olympiacos in a [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League knockout phase#Round of 32|Europa League round of 32]] match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51829511 |title=Manchester City v Arsenal postponed over coronavirus fears |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311084144/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51829511|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 March the four-day [[Cheltenham Festival]] continued as planned with enhanced hygiene measures in place,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/10/cheltenham-festival-key-event-in-racing-calendar-goes-ahead-despite-coronavirus |title=Cheltenham Festival: key race meeting goes ahead despite coronavirus |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Steven |last=Morris |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095618/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/10/cheltenham-festival-key-event-in-racing-calendar-goes-ahead-despite-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as did the [[All England Open Badminton Championships]] in Birmingham the next day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/11/service-as-normal-badminton-birmingham-all-england-championships |title=Service as normal: badminton's finest cock-a-hoop to get back to business |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Sean |last=Ingle |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314212841/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/11/service-as-normal-badminton-birmingham-all-england-championships|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, it was announced that Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] had tested positive to COVID-19,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51865442 |title=Mikel Arteta: Arsenal manager tests positive for coronavirus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313005542/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51865442|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the next day [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] midfielder [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]] became the first Premier League player to test positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Chelsea's Callum Hudson-Odoi and Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta test positive |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867854 |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313071303/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867854|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional football was later suspended across the United Kingdom on 13 March, with the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[Women's Super League]], and Welsh and Northern Irish football leagues delaying matches until the beginning of April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended in England \u2013 Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland halt games |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140033/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Scottish Professional Football League]] suspending matches indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51858736 |title=Coronavirus: Scottish football suspended until further notice |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133750/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51858736|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional football in England was later postponed until the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51962751 |title=Coronavirus: English football suspension extended until at least 30&nbsp;April |website=BBC Sport |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319132255/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51962751|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The day also saw the cancellation of the Wales\u2013Scotland Six Nations match scheduled for 14 March<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/wales-v-scotland-six-nations-match-called-off-coronavirus-rugby-union |title=Wales v Scotland Six Nations match called off 24 hours before kick-off |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Paul |last=Rees |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134611/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/wales-v-scotland-six-nations-match-called-off-coronavirus-rugby-union|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the postponement of the [[London Marathon|London]], [[Greater Manchester Marathon|Manchester]] and [[Brighton Marathon]]s from their April dates until the autumn.<ref name=\"BBC-LM-13Mar2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143346/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe next five days saw a flurry of further sporting cancellations. Five fixtures set to be played on Saturday 14 March in the [[National League (English football)|National League]] were postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51877974 |title=Coronavirus: Five National League games on Saturday called off following outbreak |website=BBC Sport |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210942/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51877974|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with all matches across both the National League and the [[Northern Premier League]] suspended two days later and the [[Football Association]] recommending the postponement of grassroots level football \"for the foreseeable future\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/16/national-league-shuts-down-as-fa-puts-all-english-grassroots-football-on-hold |title=National League shuts down as FA puts all English grassroots football on hold |website=The Guardian |agency=PA Media |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317182216/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/16/national-league-shuts-down-as-fa-puts-all-english-grassroots-football-on-hold|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Welsh Rugby Union]] discontinued all rugby matches across Wales from Saturday evening until the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51889671 |title=Welsh rugby: WRU announce suspension until end of March |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210942/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51889671|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On Sunday 15 March the [[Netball Superleague]] was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/netball/news/12415/11957895/coronavirus-vitality-netball-superleague-postponed-with-immediate-effect |title=Coronavirus: Vitality Netball Superleague postponed with immediate effect |website=Sky Sports |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318212310/https://www.skysports.com/netball/news/12415/11957895/coronavirus-vitality-netball-superleague-postponed-with-immediate-effect|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Premiership Rugby]] was suspended for five weeks on Monday 16 March, with all rugby activities in England being delayed until 14 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/16/rugby-premiership-suspended-for-five-weeks-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Premiership Rugby suspended for five weeks over coronavirus pandemic |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Paul |last=Rees |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318043714/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/16/rugby-premiership-suspended-for-five-weeks-over-coronavirus-pandemic|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Monday additionally saw the cancellation of the [[2020 Grand National|Grand National]],<ref name=\"BBC GN Mar2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/horse-racing/51930209 |title=Coronavirus: Horse racing in Great Britain suspended until end of April |website=BBC Sport |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041609/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/horse-racing/51930209|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the postponement of the [[Edinburgh Marathon]] from May to September,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/health/edinburgh-marathon-festival-2020-confirmed-date-postponed-race-marathon-route-and-how-enter-2450122 |title=Edinburgh Marathon Festival 2020: confirmed date for postponed race, marathon route and how to enter |website=Edinburgh Evening News |first=Rhona |last=Shennan |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317171121/https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/health/edinburgh-marathon-festival-2020-confirmed-date-postponed-race-marathon-route-and-how-enter-2450122|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the first peacetime cancellation of the [[Boat Race]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2020/03/16/coronavirus-forces-first-boat-race-cancellation-outside-world/ |title=Coronavirus forces first Boat Race cancellation outside of a world war |newspaper=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |first=Rachel |last=Quarrell |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> On Tuesday 17 March all motor racing events sanctioned by the national governing body [[Motorsport UK]] were suspended until May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148702/no-motorsport-uksanctioned-events-until-may |title=No Motorsport UK-sanctioned events until May due to coronavirus |website=Autosport |first=Stephen |last=Lickorish |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318211841/https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148702/no-motorsport-uksanctioned-events-until-may|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All horse racing events were similarly suspended the following day,<ref name=\"BBC GN Mar2020\"/> as were all boxing tournaments until further notice subject to a [[British Boxing Board of Control]] review in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11958895/coronavirus-british-boxing-board-of-control-cancels-all-events-due-to-pandemic |title=Coronavirus: British Boxing Board of Control cancels all events due to pandemic |website=Sky Sports |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319022433/https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11958895/coronavirus-british-boxing-board-of-control-cancels-all-events-due-to-pandemic|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Royal family===\nOn 4 March, the 93-year-old Queen [[Elizabeth II]] wore long gloves while awarding honours at a public [[investiture]] ceremony, prompting some to speculate the measure as a precaution against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foster |first1=Max |last2=Wilkinson |first2=David |last3=Guy |first3=Jack |title=Queen Elizabeth wears gloves, sparking coronavirus speculation |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/04/uk/queen-gloves-ceremony-scli-intl-gbr/index.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen's long gloves at palace ceremony 'sensible precaution' |url=https://news.sky.com/story/queens-long-gloves-at-palace-ceremony-sensible-precaution-against-coronavirus-11948752 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Sky News |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March the Queen left London for [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Queen leaves London and moves to Windsor Castle amid outbreak |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/queen-coronavirus-royal-family-cancelled-windsor-easter-buckingham-palace-a9406926.html |work=The Independent |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320163644/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/queen-coronavirus-royal-family-cancelled-windsor-easter-buckingham-palace-a9406926.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day she issued a message to the nation noting that the country and the world was entering a period of great concern and uncertainty.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=A message from Her Majesty The Queen, 19th&nbsp;March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=The Royal Household |url=https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-19th-march-2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319181434/https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-19th-march-2020 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Her grandsons Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Harry]] both sent messages out via social media.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Heffer |first=Greg |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-prince-william-and-prince-harry-pay-tribute-to-awe-inspiring-public-response-11959943 |title=Coronavirus: Prince William and Prince Harry pay tribute to 'awe-inspiring' public response |date=19 March 2020 |work=Sky News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319181423/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-prince-william-and-prince-harry-pay-tribute-to-awe-inspiring-public-response-11959943 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Princess Beatrice of York|Princess Beatrice]] cancelled her wedding reception at [[Buckingham Palace]] and took further advice on whether to carry on with a private [[Wedding of Princess Beatrice and Edoardo Mapelli Mozzi|wedding ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-princess-beatrice-cancels-buckingham-palace-wedding-reception-11959792 |title=Coronavirus: Princess Beatrice cancels Buckingham Palace wedding reception |date=18 March 2020 |work=Sky News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318202959/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-princess-beatrice-cancels-buckingham-palace-wedding-reception-11959792 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] greeted people with the [[Namaste]] hand gesture instead of a handshake at the Commonwealth Service at Westminster Abbey to avoid the spread of the virus, and did the same for the Prince's Trust Awards on 11 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Charles greets investiture recipients with namaste amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-12/prince-charles-meets-recipients-with-namaste-greeting-amid-coronavirus-fears-investiture-ceremony-at-buckingham-palace/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 March, Charles met [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], who later came down with the infection.<ref name=\"Charles3\">{{cite news |last2=Sykes |first2=Tom |first1=Jamie |last1=Ross |title=Fears for the Queen as Prince Charles Contracts COVID-19 |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/prince-charles-tests-positive-for-coronavirus |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Daily Beast |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 25 March, it was announced that he had received a positive test result for COVID-19 and was suffering mild symptoms. He self-isolated at [[Birkhall]] on the [[Balmoral Castle]] estate.<ref name=\"Charles1\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Charles2\">{{cite news |last1=Reynolds |first1=Emma |last2=Foster |first2=Max |last3=Wilkinson |first3=David |title=Prince Charles tests positive for novel coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/25/europe/prince-charles-coronavirus-gbr-intl/index.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Concerns were raised for the health of the entire Royal Family, as well as concerns that he may have unwittingly become a [[super-spreader]] of the disease due to the vast number of people he regularly meets. Charles last saw the Queen on 12 March, just one day before the earliest date medical experts believe he would have been contagious.<ref name=\"Charles3\"/> The [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]] tested negative, but self-isolated.<ref name=\"Charles1\"/><ref name=\"Charles2\"/> On 30 March [[Clarence House]], the Prince's official residence, confirmed that he had come out of self-isolation after seven days having recovered from the illness.<ref name=\"Charles4\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles out of virus self-isolation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52088684 |work=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Charles5\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles has recovered from coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/coronavirus-prince-charles-test-positive-recovered-self-isolation-royal-family-a9434951.html |work=The Independent |date=30 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 6 April, the Duchess came out of self-isolation after showing no symptoms for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/coronavirus-camilla-duchess-of-cornwall-self-isolation-prince-charles-a9449636.html|title=Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall out of self-isolation after Prince Charles recovers from coronavirus|publisher=The Independent|first=Sabrina|last=Barr|date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the [[William, Duke of Cambridge|Duke]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]] gave their support to a [[Public Health England]] campaign to protect people's mental health during the outbreak. The campaign encourages people to stay in touch with family and friends via telephone and social media.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52081021|title=Royals back coronavirus mental health campaign|work=BBC News|date=29 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, the Queen held the first 'virtual' meeting with the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in history due to the ongoing pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/royal-family/2020/04/03/queen-holds-first-virtual-privy-council-history-due-coronavirus/|title=The Queen holds first 'virtual' Privy Council in history due to coronavirus|newspaper=The Telegraph|first=Camilla|last=Tominey|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\n\n[[File:Empty M4 Motorway in Cardiff due to COVID-19 (1) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|An empty [[M4 motorway]] in [[Cardiff]] on the afternoon of Saturday 28 March 2020]]\n\n==== Aviation ====\nFrom the latter half of January, [[Heathrow Airport]] received additional clinical support and tightened surveillance of the three direct flights that it receives from Wuhan every week; each were to be met by a Port Health team.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\"/> Later, airlines including [[British Airways]] and [[Ryanair]] announced a number of flight cancellations for March.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020/>\n\nRegional airline [[Flybe]] had been brought to the brink of collapse following prior financial trouble earlier in the year. This, combined with decreased ticket sales as a result of the outbreak, caused the airline to stop ticket sales on 4 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |website=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305000425/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/flybe-news-flights-administration-collapse-coronavirus-outbreak-bust-latest-news-a9376421.html |title=Flybe collapses as coronavirus pandemic takes toll |website=The Independent |first=Simon |last=Calder |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305164758/https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/flybe-news-flights-administration-collapse-coronavirus-outbreak-bust-latest-news-a9376421.html|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The company entered [[Administration in United Kingdom law|administration]] and ceased operations the following day.<ref name=Baldwin2020>{{Cite book |last=Baldwin |first=Richard|chapter-url=https://cepr.org/sites/default/files/news/COVID-19.pdf |title=Economics in the time of COVID-19 |last2=Weder di Mauro |first2=Beatrice |publisher=CEPR Press |year=2020 |isbn=978-1-912179-28-2|editor-last=Baldwin|editor-first=Richard |location=London |page=18 |chapter=Introduction|editor-last2=Weder di Mauro|editor-first2=Beatrice}}</ref> Despite some calls for a bailout, led mainly by [[Virgin Atlantic]], the Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, said that the government would only come into the picture as \"a last resort\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/virgin-atlantic-boss-urges-boris-johnson-to-sanction-7-5bn-airline-bailout-11957708 |title=Virgin Atlantic boss urges Boris Johnson to sanction \u00a37.5bn airline bailout |website=Sky News |language=en |date=15 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52027342 |title=No extra help for airlines, chancellor says |date=24 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, [[London City Airport]] announced it would temporarily close due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=\"BBC-25Mar2020\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: London City Airport to shut due to outbreak |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52038293 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Heathrow Airport closed one runway from 6 April, while [[Gatwick Airport]] closed one of its two terminals, and said its runway would open for scheduled flights only between 2pm and 10pm.<ref name=\"Morrison-03Apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Morrison |first1=Sean |title=London Heathrow to close runway as it scales back operations due to coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/london-heathrow-to-close-runway-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic-a4405711.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Evening Standard |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Most other UK airports also significantly scaled back operations.<ref name=\"Reid-27Mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Reid |first1=Jenni |title=Gatwick Airport to close North Terminal |url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/03/27/gatwick-airport-to-close-north-terminal/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Business Traveller |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Public transport ====\nOn 20 March, [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]] became the first [[train operating company]] to announce a reduced timetable, which would come into use from 23 March.<ref>[https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 Kent Coronavirus southeastern makes major] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201805/https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 |date=20 March 2020 }} ''www.kentlive.news''</ref> On that day the government announced emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise agreements]] nationalised for at least six months to prevent train operating companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=Sky News}}</ref> From 30 March, [[open-access operator]] [[Hull Trains]] suspended all services,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/coronavirus-hull-trains-uk-rail-operator-suspend-service-a9434431.html|title=Hull Trains becomes the first UK rail operator to suspend all services amid coronavirus pandemic|last=Xie|first=Qin|date=2020-03-30|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> with [[Gatwick Express]] and [[Grand Central (train operating company)|Grand Central]] following shortly afterwards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/news/politics/coronavirus-gatwick-express-trains-suspended-further-reductions-southern-and-thameslink-services-2518652|title=Coronavirus: Gatwick Express trains suspended with further reductions to Southern and Thameslink services|last=Powling|first=Joshua|date=2020-03-26|website=Hastings & St Leonards Observer|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/uk/grand-central-follows-hull-trains-in-suspending-open-access-services/56183.article|title=Grand Central follows Hull Trains in suspending open access services|date=2020-04-06|website=Railway Gazette UK|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[Sheffield Supertram|Stagecoach Supertram]] light rail network in [[Sheffield]] announced that they would be switching to a modified Sunday service from 23 March until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus-changes-made-supertram-service-sheffield-2502449 |title=Coronavirus: changes made to the Supertram service in Sheffield |website=www.thestar.co.uk|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201755/https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus-changes-made-supertram-service-sheffield-2502449|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Local bus operators [[First South Yorkshire]] and [[Stagecoach Yorkshire]], which operate across the same area, announced that they would also be switching to a reduced timetable from 23 March.<ref>[https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/transport/coronavirus-bus-timetables-change-sheffield-doncaster-and-south-yorkshire-2502683 Coronavirus bus timetables change Sheffield Doncaster and South Yorkshire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201759/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/transport/coronavirus-bus-timetables-change-sheffield-doncaster-and-south-yorkshire-2502683 |date=20 March 2020 }} ''www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref>\n[[File:Stay at home and social distancing notices London Underground 27 March 2020.jpg|thumb|\"Stay at home\" and \"Please  keep your distance\" notices on the London Underground, 27 March 2020.]]\n[[Transport for London]] (TfL) services were reduced in stages. All [[Night Overground]] and [[Night Tube]] services, as well as all services on the [[Waterloo & City line]], were suspended from 20 March, and 40 tube stations were closed on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814 |title=Coronavirus: London cuts Tube trains and warns 'don't travel unless you really have to' |website=Sky News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321052444/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Mayor of London]] and TfL urged people to only use public transport if absolutely essential, so that it could be used by critical workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2020/march/planned-services-to-support-london-s-critical-workers |title=Planned services to support London's critical workers |last=Matters |first=Transport for London {{!}} Every Journey|website=Transport for London|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201755/https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2020/march/planned-services-to-support-london-s-critical-workers|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The London Underground brought in new measures on 25 March to combat the spread of the virus, by slowing the flow of passengers onto platforms. Measures included the imposition of queuing at ticket gates and turning off some escalators.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-52023580 |title=New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential trips |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n[[National Express Coaches|National Express]] suspended all its long-distance coach services from 6 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/national-express-coach-cancelled-suspended-bus-ticket-refund-a9442221.html|title=National Express to suspend all coach services|last=Xie|first=Qin|date=2020-04-02|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Spread to other countries and territories ==\n[[Sophie Gr\u00e9goire Trudeau]], the wife of Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], tested positive for COVID-19 upon her return from [[WE Day]] events in the UK; on 12 March 2020 the Trudeau family entered two weeks of self-isolation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/gr%C3%A9goire-trudeau-self-isolating-1.5495419 |title=Sophie Gr\u00e9goire Trudeau's coronavirus infection comes after attending U.K. event |website=CBC News |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |first=John Paul |last=Tasker |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318154958/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/gr%C3%A9goire-trudeau-self-isolating-1.5495419|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first patient in [[Mauritius]] was a 59-year-old man who returned from the United Kingdom on 7 March 2020. When he arrived in Mauritius, the Mauritian had no symptoms.<ref name=\"Defi\">{{Cite news |url=https://defimedia.info/covid-19-trois-mauriciens-testes-positifs-zot-pe-gayn-tou-tretman-ki-bizin-rassure-le-pm |title=Covid-19 : trois Mauriciens test\u00e9s positifs ; \"zot pe gayn tou tretman ki bizin\", rassure le PM |date=19 March 2020 |work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] |first=St\u00e9phanie |last=Mompl\u00e9|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319191648/https://defimedia.info/covid-19-trois-mauriciens-testes-positifs-zot-pe-gayn-tou-tretman-ki-bizin-rassure-le-pm|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other cases of the novel coronavirus resulting from travel to the UK were subsequently reported in India,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/city-on-covid-19-map-teen-back-from-uk-tests-positive/articleshow/74682249.cms |title=Kolkata on Covid-19 map, teen back from UK tests positive |website=The Times of India |agency=Television News Network |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319045040/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/city-on-covid-19-map-teen-back-from-uk-tests-positive/articleshow/74682249.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/live/2020/mar/19/covid-19-live--i-am-here-to-seek-from-you-your-next-few-weeks-says-pm-in-address-2118519.html |title=COVID-19 LIVE &#124; Telangana confirms 3 new cases, Andhra 1; PM calls for Janta curfew on Mar&nbsp;22 |website=The New Indian Express |publisher=Express Publications |at=08:09am; 10:58am; 04:16pm |date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319160403/https://www.newindianexpress.com/live/2020/mar/19/covid-19-live--i-am-here-to-seek-from-you-your-next-few-weeks-says-pm-in-address-2118519.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-51926323 |title=Coronavirus - Virus: Nigeria don confam new Covid-19 outbreak - See wetin we know so far |website=BBC News |language=Nigerian Pidgin |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe figures in the table below represent laboratory confirmed cases only; and as indicated by the UK Government's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]], it is likely that other cases in the UK are not reflected in these figures (on 12 March 2020 there were 596 confirmed cases, but the total number of cases was estimated at 5,000\u201310,000).<ref name=BBCNews12March2020>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: People with fever or 'continuous' cough told to self-isolate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51857856 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |agency=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313000134/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51857856 |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Death statistics are presented daily, but there may be a delay between death and it entering official statistics so families can be informed first. The delay is usually just a few days, but can be over a week.<ref name=itv-20200330>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-30/what-do-the-statistics-really-tell-us-about-uk-coronavirus-deaths/ |title=What do the statistics really tell us about UK coronavirus deaths? |work=ITV News |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=guardian0404/>  For example, on 28 March, the Department of Health and Social Care reported that the total deaths in hospital in England (not the UK) to the end of 27 March was 926. The correct figure is now believed to have been 1,649, which is 78% higher than reported. When the [[Office for National Statistics (United Kingdom)|Office for National Statistics]] has data for deaths from Coronavirus at home, the figure will be increased further.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c07e267b-7bca-418f-ad9e-8631a29854cb?fbclid=IwAR2SWBnb1ZbKMDEz_ICMlnfSIBxo8CgYeYH6iLZLjBV9HSoa2HmapwK721I |title=Deaths from coronavirus far higher in England than first reported |date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDeath figures reflect only deaths from hospitals and not retirement homes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.faz.net/1.6722539 |title=Nach Corona-Erkrankung: Britischer Premierminister Johnson aus Klinik entlassen |date=2020-04-12 |work=FAZ.NET |access-date=2020-04-12 |language=de |issn=0174-4909}}</ref>\nKnown locations of death are shown in brackets.\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases}}\n\n==Graphs==\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=1000\n|colors=#F46D43,#000000,#C4ADA0,#C4ADB0,#C4ADC0\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x= 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=20, 23, 35, 39, 51, 87, 116, 164, 209, 280, 321, 384, 460, 586, 798, 1140, 1391, 1543, 1950, 2626, 3269, 3983, 5018, 5683, 6650, 8077, 9529, 11658, 14548, 17104, 19606, 22271, 25521, 30088, 34610, 39282, 43282, 49481, 53624, 57512, 63377, 68052, 73758, 78991, 84279, 88621\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|y2=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 3, 5, 6, 8, 10, 11, 21, 35, 55, 60, 103, 144, 177, 233, 281, 335, 422, 463, 578, 759, 1019, 1228, 1408, 1789, 2352, 2921, 3605, 4313, 4934, 5373, 6159, 7097, 7978, 8958, 9875, 10612, 11329\n|y2Title=Total deaths\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=1000\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:1\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 