{"title_page": "Brian Roberson", "text_new": "'''Brian Roberson''' is a former record-setting receiver for [[Fresno State University]] and the XFL's [[San Francisco Demons]].<ref>[http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/FB/lib00075,0EAE89A2B7C23B94.html Sacramento Bee]</ref>\n\n==Sylmar High==\nRoberson was a standout receiver/defensive back for the Spartans during the 1990-91 seasons. As a Junior in 1990, Roberson caught 16 passes for 222 yards and 2 touchdowns, while also returning an interception for a touchdown. Roberson was named 1st team All-Valley Pac-8 conference as a junior.\n\nAs a senior in 1991, Roberson recorded 28 receptions for 464 yards and 5 touchdowns. His total of 15 touchdowns included a record-setting performance against Van Nuys, as he scored touchdowns four different ways: 29 yard reception, 30 yard run, 82 yard punt return, and a 98-yard interception return.\n\nRoberson was named All-City 1st team, Valley Pac-8 conference 1st team, and was selected to play in the Daily News and 1st Annual Glendale vs. Burbank All-Star game. Roberson took official recruiting visits to Colorado State, Washington State, and Fresno State.\n\n==Fresno State Bulldogs==\n\nAs a redshirt freshman in 1993, Roberson caught 5 passes for 50 yards, including a touchdown reception from <ref>Sports Illustrated Almanac, 1997</ref>[[Trent Dilfer]]. 1994 set the stage for what would turn out to be one of the most prolific receiving careers in Fresno State history. As a sophomore Roberson began to attract significant attention, catching 50 passes for 900 yards and 4 touchdowns, while earning All-WAC 2nd team honors. As a junior in 1995, Roberson was selected to the WAC 1st team, as he caught 55 balls for 758 yards and 5 touchdowns.\n\nIn 1996 Roberson elevated his game to another level with the departure of Charlie Jones to the NFL. A Pre-season All-American, he caught a Fresno State record 78 passes for 1,248 yards and 5 touchdowns.\n\n==New York Giants (NFL) (1997)==\n\nRoberson signed a free agent contract with the New York Giants in April, 1997. An injury cut short his attempt to become the team's primary punt returner.\n\n==Fargo Freeze (IFL) (2000)==\n\nPlaying for the [[Fargo Freeze]] in North Dakota, Roberson was the team's leading receiver in 2000.\n\n==San Francisco Demons (XFL) (2001)==\n\nRoberson helped guide San Francisco to the title game, catching 36 passes for 395 yards and 2 touchdowns. In his XFL debut he caught an XFL record 12 passes for 127 yards.<ref>[http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/CC/lib01211,10649FA325EAEE04.html]</ref>\n\n==Saskatchewan Roughriders (CFL) (2002)==\n\nAfter the XFL folded, Roberson joined the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]], hauling in 11 balls for 163 yards and a touchdown.\n\n==References==\n<ref>1999 Fresno State Football media guide</ref>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{San Francisco Demons Roster}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberson, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Fresno State Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Saskatchewan Roughriders players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Demons players]]\n[[Category:Canadian football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brian Roberson''' is a former record-setting receiver for [[Fresno State University]] and the XFL's [[San Francisco Demons]].<ref>[http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/FB/lib00075,0EAE89A2B7C23B94.html Sacramento Bee]</ref>\n\n==Sylmar High==\nRoberson was a standout receiver/defensive back for the Spartans during the 1990-91 seasons. As a Junior in 1990, Roberson caught 16 passes for 222 yards and 2 touchdowns, while also returning an interception for a touchdown. Roberson was named 1st team All-Valley Pac-8 conference as a junior.\n\nAs a senior in 1991, Roberson recorded 28 receptions for 464 yards and 5 touchdowns. His total of 15 touchdowns included a record-setting performance against Van Nuys, as he scored touchdowns four different ways: 29 yard reception, 30 yard run, 82 yard punt return, and a 98-yard interception return.\n\nRoberson was named All-City 1st team, Valley Pac-8 conference 1st team, and was selected to play in the Daily News and 1st Annual Glendale vs. Burbank All-Star game. Roberson took official recruiting visits to Colorado State, Washington State, and Fresno State.\n\n==Fresno State Bulldogs==\n\nAs a redshirt freshman in 1993, Roberson caught 5 passes for 50 yards, including a touchdown reception from <ref>Sports Illustrated Almanac, 1997</ref>[[Trent Dilfer]]. 1994 set the stage for what would turn out to be one of the most prolific receiving careers in Fresno State history. As a sophomore Roberson began to attract significant attention, catching 50 passes for 900 yards and 4 touchdowns, while earning All-WAC 2nd team honors. As a junior in 1995, Roberson was selected to the WAC 1st team, as he caught 55 balls for 758 yards and 5 touchdowns.\n\nIn 1996 Roberson elevated his game to another level with the departure of Charlie Jones to the NFL. A Pre-season All-American, he caught a Fresno State record 78 passes for 1,248 yards and 5 touchdowns.\n\n==New York Giants (NFL) (1997)==\n\nRoberson signed a free agent contract with the New York Giants in April, 1997. An injury cut short his attempt to become the teams primary punt returner.\n\n==Fargo Freeze (IFL) (2000)==\n\nPlaying for the [[Fargo Freeze]] in North Dakota, Roberson was the team's leading receiver in 2000.\n\n==San Francisco Demons (XFL) (2001)==\n\nRoberson helped guide San Francisco to the title game, catching 36 passes for 395 yards and 2 touchdowns. In his XFL debut he caught an XFL record 12 passes for 127 yards.<ref>[http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/CC/lib01211,10649FA325EAEE04.html]</ref>\n\n==Saskatchewan Roughriders (CFL) (2002)==\n\nAfter the XFL folded, Roberson joined the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]], hauling in 11 balls for 163 yards and a touchdown.\n\n==References==\n<ref>1999 Fresno State Football media guide</ref>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{San Francisco Demons Roster}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberson, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Fresno State Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Saskatchewan Roughriders players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Demons players]]\n[[Category:Canadian football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNew York Giants (NFL) (1997):Typo fixing, replaced: teams primary \u2192 team's primary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Roberson"}
{"title_page": "Brian Harvey (footballer)", "text_new": "{{For|the Australian player|Brian Harvey (Australian rules footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Brian Harvey\n| fullname =\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1947|01|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1= 1963\n| youthclubs1= [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]\n| years1= 1964\u20131965\n| clubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]]\n| caps1= 1 | goals1 = 0\n| years3 =   \n| clubs3 =  [[South Coast United]]\n| caps3 = \n| goals3 =\n| years4 = 1968\u20131970\n| clubs4 =[[Dallas Tornado]]\n| caps4 = 45\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5= 1971\u20131973\n| clubs5 =[[Caroline Hill FC|Caroline Hill]]\n| caps5  =\n| goals5 =\n| years6 = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs6 =[[Kwong Wah Athletic Association|Kwong Wah]]\n| caps6 = \n| goals6 = \n| years7 = 1974\n| clubs7 =[[Melbourne Hakoah]]\n| caps7 = \n| goals7 = \n| years8 = 1974\u20131977\n| clubs8 = [[Urban Services Department|Urban Services]]\n| caps8 = \n| goals8 = \n| manageryears1       = ?\u20131977\n| managerclubs1       = [[Urban Services Department|Urban Services]] (player-coach)\n| manageryears2       = 1982\u20131984\n| managerclubs2       = [[Oklahoma City Slickers]]\n| manageryears3       = 1985\n| managerclubs3       = [[Tulsa Tornados]]\n| manageryears4       = 1986\u2013\n| managerclubs4       = [[Oklahoma City Stars]]\n| manageryears5       = 1990\u20131992\n| managerclubs5       = [[Oklahoma City Spirit]]\n}}\n'''Brian Harvey''' (born 12 January 1947) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]].<ref name=\"ozf1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Players/H/HARR.html|title=Australian Player Database \u2013 HARR|publisher=ozfootball.net|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref><ref name=\"allf1\">{{cite web|url=http://allfootballers.com/|title=Brian Harvey|publisher=Since 1888|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref><ref name=\"nb1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/chester/chester.html|title=Chester City|publisher=www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref> He is the brother of once-[[cap (sport)|cap]]ped [[England national football team|England]] man [[Colin Harvey]].<ref name = \"Brother\">{{cite news|title=Football's maddest tour EVER: When Dallas Tornado wandered the world in 1967|first=Steve|last=Brenner|date=20 March 2018|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/footballs-maddest-tour-ever-when-dallas-tornado-wandered-world-1967|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Player==\nHarvey played one game for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]] during the 1964\u20131965 season. In 1966,he graduated from [[St. Bonaventure University]]. He then embarked on a career playing in Australia. In 1968, he moved to the United States where he signed with the [[Dallas Tornado]] of the [[North American Soccer League]]. In September 1971, he moved to Caroline Hill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caroline Hill's 'reinforcements' swell the ranks|work= South China Morning Post|date=10 Sep 1971}}</ref>\n\n==Manager==\nIn 1982, Harvey became the head coach of the expansion [[Oklahoma City Slickers]] of the [[American Soccer League (1933-1983)|American Soccer League]]. That season, he took the Slickers to the championship game and was named the 1982 Coach of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1982.html#ASL |title=The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1982 |access-date=27 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128063727/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1982.html#ASL |archive-date=28 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1984, the Slickers moved to the [[United Soccer League (1984\u201385)|United Soccer League]] where it played as the Oklahoma City Stampede. In 1985, the team moved to [[Tulsa]], becoming the [[Tulsa Tornados]]. Harvey remained head coach for each of the team's four seasons.<ref>[http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/01/26/86-oklahoma-city-slickers-oklahoma-city-stampede/ Oklahoma City Slickers / Oklahoma City Stampede / Tulsa Tornado]</ref> In 1986, Harvey established the men's soccer team at [[Oklahoma City University]]. In 1994, he began the women's soccer team.<ref>[http://www.ocusports.com/staff.aspx?staff=22 OCU: Brian Harvey]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrian Harvey is the brother of [[Colin Harvey]], who played for and managed his hometown club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], as well as representing [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], and receiving one [[cap (sport)|cap]] for [[England national football team|England]].<ref name=\"Brother\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nasljerseys.com/Players/H/Harvey.Brian.htm NASL stats]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Brian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Soccer League (1933\u20131983) coaches]]\n[[Category:Dallas Tornado players]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Lone Star Soccer Alliance coaches]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:South Coast United players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:United Soccer League (1984\u201385) coaches]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-midfielder-1940s-stub}}\n{{England-footy-manager-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Australian player|Brian Harvey (Australian rules footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Brian Harvey\n| fullname =\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1947|01|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], England\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1= 1963\n| youthclubs1= [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]\n| years1= 1964\u20131965\n| clubs1 = [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]]\n| caps1= 1 | goals1 = 0\n| years3 =   \n| clubs3 =  [[South Coast United]]\n| caps3 = \n| goals3 =\n| years4 = 1968\u20131970\n| clubs4 =[[Dallas Tornado]]\n| caps4 = 45\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5= 1971\u20131973\n| clubs5 =[[Caroline Hill FC|Caroline Hill]]\n| caps5  =\n| goals5 =\n| years6 = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs6 =[[Kwong Wah Athletic Association|Kwong Wah]]\n| caps6 = \n| goals6 = \n| years7 = 1974\n| clubs7 =[[Melbourne Hakoah]]\n| caps7 = \n| goals7 = \n| years8 = 1974\u20131977\n| clubs8 = [[Urban Services Department|Urban Services]]\n| caps8 = \n| goals8 = \n| manageryears1       = ?\u20131977\n| managerclubs1       = [[Urban Services Department|Urban Services]] (player-coach)\n| manageryears2       = 1982\u20131984\n| managerclubs2       = [[Oklahoma City Slickers]]\n| manageryears3       = 1985\n| managerclubs3       = [[Tulsa Tornados]]\n| manageryears4       = 1986\u2013\n| managerclubs4       = [[Oklahoma City Stars]]\n| manageryears5       = 1990\u20131992\n| managerclubs5       = [[Oklahoma City Spirit]]\n}}\n'''Brian Harvey''' (born 12 January 1947) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]].<ref name=\"ozf1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Players/H/HARR.html|title=Australian Player Database \u2013 HARR|publisher=ozfootball.net|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref><ref name=\"allf1\">{{cite web|url=http://allfootballers.com/|title=Brian Harvey|publisher=Since 1888|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref><ref name=\"nb1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/chester/chester.html|title=Chester City|publisher=www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com|accessdate=2009-07-08}}</ref> He is the brother of once-[[cap (sport)|cap]]ped [[England national football team|England]] man [[Colin Harvey]].<ref name = \"Brother\">{{cite news|title=Football's maddest tour EVER: When Dallas Tornado wandered the world in 1967|first=Steve|last=Brenner|date=20 March 2018|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/footballs-maddest-tour-ever-when-dallas-tornado-wandered-world-1967|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Player==\nHarvey played one game for [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]] during the 1964\u20131965 season. In 1966,he graduated from [[St. Bonaventure University]]. He then embarked on a career playing in Australia. In 1968, he moved to the United States where he signed with the [[Dallas Tornado]] of the [[North American Soccer League]]. In September 1971, he moved to Caroline Hill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caroline Hill's 'reinforcements' swell the ranks|work= South China Morning Post|date=10 Sep 1971}}</ref>\n\n==Manager==\nIn 1982, Harvey became the head coach of the expansion [[Oklahoma City Slickers]] of the [[American Soccer League (1933-1983)|American Soccer League]]. That season, he took the Slickers to the championship game and was named the 1982 Coach of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1982.html#ASL |title=The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1982 |access-date=27 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128063727/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1982.html#ASL |archive-date=28 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1984, the Slickers moved to the [[United Soccer League (1984\u201385)|United Soccer League]] where it played as the Oklahoma City Stampede. In 1985, the team moved to [[Tulsa]], becoming the [[Tulsa Tornados]]. Harvey remained head coach for each of the teams four seasons.<ref>[http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/01/26/86-oklahoma-city-slickers-oklahoma-city-stampede/ Oklahoma City Slickers / Oklahoma City Stampede / Tulsa Tornado]</ref> In 1986, Harvey established the men's soccer team at [[Oklahoma City University]]. In 1994, he began the women's soccer team.<ref>[http://www.ocusports.com/staff.aspx?staff=22 OCU: Brian Harvey]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrian Harvey is the brother of [[Colin Harvey]], who played for and managed his hometown club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], as well as representing [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], and receiving one [[cap (sport)|cap]] for [[England national football team|England]].<ref name=\"Brother\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nasljerseys.com/Players/H/Harvey.Brian.htm NASL stats]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Brian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Soccer League (1933\u20131983) coaches]]\n[[Category:Dallas Tornado players]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Lone Star Soccer Alliance coaches]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:South Coast United players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:United Soccer League (1984\u201385) coaches]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-midfielder-1940s-stub}}\n{{England-footy-manager-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManager:Typo fixing, replaced: teams four \u2192 team's four", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Harvey_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Depression (economics)", "text_new": "{{Globalize|article|Anglophone|2name=[[English-speaking world|the English-speaking world]]|date=October 2012}}\nIn [[economics]], a '''depression''' is a sustained, long-term downturn in economic activity in one or more economies. It is a more severe economic downturn than a [[economic recession|recession]], which is a slowdown in economic activity over the course of a normal [[business cycle]].\n\n'''Depressions''' are characterized by their length, by abnormally large increases in [[unemployment]], falls in the availability of [[credit (finance)|credit]] (often due to some form of banking or financial crisis), shrinking output as buyers dry up and suppliers cut back on production and investment, more [[bankruptcies]] including sovereign debt defaults, significantly reduced amounts of [[trade]] and commerce (especially international trade), as well as highly volatile relative currency value fluctuations (often due to currency [[devaluation]]s). Price [[deflation (economics)|deflation]], [[financial crisis|financial crises]], [[stock market crash]], and [[bank failure]]s are also common elements of a depression that do not normally occur during a recession.\n\n==Definitions==\nIn the [[United States]] the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] determines contractions and expansions in the business cycle, but does not declare depressions.<ref name=\"nber.org\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nber.org/cycles/recessions_faq.html |title=The NBER's Business Cycle Dating Procedure: Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Nber.org |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008141654/http://www.nber.org/cycles/recessions_faq.html |archivedate=2012-10-08 }}</ref> Generally, periods labeled depressions are marked by a substantial and sustained shortfall of the ability to purchase goods relative to the amount that could be produced using current resources and technology ([[potential output]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/history/A0821657.html |title=Private Tutor |publisher=Infoplease.com |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913025403/http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/history/A0821657.html |archivedate=2012-09-13 }}</ref> Another proposed definition of ''depression'' includes two general rules:<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12852043 | work=The Economist | title=Diagnosing depression | date=December 30, 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215002935/http://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12852043 | archivedate=February 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://businesscycles.info/recession-definition/ |title=Home Improvement Tips and Techniques &#124; Business Cycles |accessdate=2009-04-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202110823/http://businesscycles.info/recession-definition/ |archivedate=2009-02-02 }}</ref>\n# a decline in real GDP exceeding 10%, or\n# a recession lasting 2 or more years.\n\nThere are also differences in the duration of depression across definitions. Some economists refer only to the period when economic activity is declining. The more common use, however, also encompasses the time until the economic activity has returned close to normal levels.<ref name=\"nber.org\"/>\n\nA recession is briefly defined as a period of declining economic activity spread across the economy (according to NBER). Under the first definition, each depression will always coincide with a recession, since the difference between a depression and a recession is the severity of the fall in economic activity.  In other words, each depression is always a recession, sharing the same starting and ending dates and having the same duration.\n\nUnder the second definition, depressions and recessions will always be distinct events however, having the same starting dates. This definition of depression implies that a recession and a depression will have different ending dates and thus distinct durations. Under this definition, the length of depression will always be longer than that of the recession starting the same date.\n\nA useful example is a difference in the chronology of the Great Depression in the U.S. under the view of alternative definitions. Using the second definition of depression, most economists refer to the Great Depression, as the period between 1929 and 1941. On the other hand, using the first definition, the depression that started in August 1929 lasted until March 1933. Note that NBER, which publishes the recession (instead of depression) dates for the U.S. economy, has identified two recessions during that period. The first between August 1929 and March 1933 and the second starting in May 1937 and ending in June 1938.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nber.org/cycles/ |title=US Business Cycle Expansions and Contractions |publisher=National Bureau of Economic Research |accessdate=2008-10-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219215409/https://www.nber.org/cycles/ |archivedate=2009-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nToday the term \"depression\" is most often associated with the [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s, but the term had been in use long before then. Indeed, an early major American economic crisis, the [[Panic of 1819]], was described by then-president [[James Monroe]] as \"a depression\",<ref name=\"hnn\">{{cite web|url=http://hnn.us/articles/61931.html|title=When Did the Great Depression Receive Its Name? (And Who Named It?)|website=hnn.us |accessdate=9 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901125648/http://hnn.us/articles/61931.html|archivedate=1 September 2013}}</ref> and the economic crisis immediately preceding the 1930s depression, the [[Depression of 1920\u201321]], was referred to as a \"depression\" by president [[Calvin Coolidge]].\n\nHowever, in the 19th and early 20th centuries, ''financial'' crises were traditionally referred to as \"panics\", e.g., the 'major' [[Panic of 1907]], and the 'minor' [[Panic of 1910\u20131911]], though the 1929 crisis was more commonly called \"The Crash\", and the term \"panic\" has since fallen out of use. At the time of the Great Depression (of the 1930s), the phrase \"The Great Depression\" had already been used to refer to the period 1873\u201396 (in the United Kingdom), or more narrowly 1873\u201379 (in the United States), which has since been renamed the [[Long Depression]].\n\nCommon use of the phrase \"The Great Depression\" for the 1930s crisis is most frequently attributed to British economist [[Lionel Robbins]], whose 1934 book ''The Great Depression'' is credited with 'formalizing' the phrase,<ref name=\"hnn\"/> though US president [[Herbert Hoover]] is widely credited with having 'popularized' the term/phrase,<ref name=\"hnn\" /><ref>''The Glory and the Dream: A Narrative History of America, 1932\u20131972'', William Manchester</ref> informally referring to the downturn as a \"depression\", with such uses as \"Economic depression cannot be cured by legislative action or executive pronouncement\", (December 1930, Message to Congress) and \"I need not recount to you that the world is passing through a great depression\" (1931).\n\n==Occurrence== \nDue to the lack of an agreed definition and the strong negative associations, the characterization of any period as a \"depression\" is contentious. The term was frequently used for regional crises from the early 19th century until the 1930s, and for the more widespread crises of the 1870s and 1930s, but economic crises since 1945 have generally been referred to as \"recessions\", with the 1970s global crisis referred to as \"[[stagflation]]\", but not a depression. The only two eras commonly referred to at the current time as \"depressions\" are the 1870s and 1930s.<ref name=\"krug2010\">{{citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/opinion/28krugman.html | first = Paul | last = Krugman | author-link = Paul Krugman | title = The Third Depression | date = June 27, 2010 | journal = [[The New York Times]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120411051630/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/opinion/28krugman.html | archive-date = April 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nTo some degree this is simply a stylistic change, similar to the decline in the use of \"panic\" to refer to financial crises, but it does also reflect that the [[economic cycle]] \u2013 both in the United States and in most [[OECD]] countries \u2013 though not in all \u2013 has been more moderate since 1945.\n\nThere ''have'' been many periods of prolonged economic underperformance in particular countries/regions since 1945, detailed below, but terming these as \"depressions\" is controversial. The 2008-2009 economic cycle, which has comprised the most significant global crisis since the Great Depression, has at times been termed a depression,<ref name=\"krug2010\" /> but this terminology is not widely used, with the episode instead being referred to by other terms, such as the \"[[Great Recession]]\".\n\n== Notable depressions ==\n\n===The General Crisis of 1640===\n{{main|The General Crisis}}\nThe largest Great Depression of all time occurred during the General Crisis. The Ming Province of China went bankrupt and the Stuart Monarchy was in the civil war on three fronts in Ireland, Scotland, and England. [[Thomas Hobbes]], an English philosopher, created the first recorded explanation of the need for a universal [[Social Contract]] in his 1652 book [[Leviathan]] based on the general misery within society during this period.\n[[File:Past Great Depressions.jpg|thumb|Great Depressions (Mature Capitalisms) and Results ...]]\n\n===Great Depression of 1837===\n\nThis depression is acknowledged to be a worse Great Depression than the later Great Depression of the 1930s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Social History of an American Depression, 1837-1843|journal=The American Historical Review|volume=40|issue=4|pages=662\u2013687|date=1935-07-01|df=|jstor = 1842418|last1 = Rezneck|first1 = Samuel|doi=10.2307/1842418}}</ref> This great depression ended in the United States due to the California Gold Rush and its ten-times addition to the United States' gold reserves. As with most great depressions, it was followed by a thirty-year period of a booming economy in the United States, that is now called the [[Second Industrial Revolution]] (of the 1850s).\n\n===Panic of 1837===\n{{main|Panic of 1837}}\nThe Panic of 1837 was an American [[financial crisis]], built on a [[Speculation|speculative]] real estate market.<ref name=\"politonomist.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politonomist.com/history-of-economic-recessions-00273/3/|title=Panic of 1837 (1837 - 1842) \u2014 History of Economic Recessions|date=2009-01-02|publisher=Politonomist.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406205415/http://www.politonomist.com/history-of-economic-recessions-00273/3/|archivedate=2009-04-06|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref> The bubble burst on May 10, 1837 in [[New York City]], when every [[bank]] stopped payment in [[gold]] and [[silver]] [[coin]]age. The Panic was followed by a five-year depression,<ref name=\"politonomist.com\" /> with the failure of [[bank]]s and record high unemployment levels.<ref name=\"Glasner\">{{Cite book|title=Business cycles and depressions: an encyclopedia|author=Timberlake, Richard H. Jr.|publisher=Garland Publishing|year=1997|isbn=978-0-8240-0944-1|editor1=Glasner, David|location=New York|pages=514\u201316|chapter=Panic of 1837|editor2=Cooley, Thomas F.|chapter-url-access=registration|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/businesscyclesde00glas}}</ref>\n\n=== Long Depression ===\n[[File: Tompkins square riot 1874.jpg|thumb|New York police violently attacking unemployed workers in [[Tompkins Square Riot (1874)|Tompkins Square Park]], 1874]]\n{{details|Long Depression}}\nStarting with the adoption of the [[gold standard]] in Britain and the United States, the [[Long Depression]] (1873\u20131896) was indeed longer than what is now referred to as the Great Depression, but shallower. However, it was known as \"the Great Depression\" until the 1930s.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n===Great Depression===\n{{main|Great Depression}}\nThe [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s affected most national economies in the world.  This depression is generally considered to have begun with the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], and the crisis quickly spread to other national economies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.english.uiuc.edu/maps/depression/about.htm |title=About the Great Depression |publisher=English.uiuc.edu |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220090243/http://www.english.uiuc.edu/maps/depression/about.htm |archivedate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> Between 1929 and 1933, the [[gross national product]] of the [[United States]] decreased by 33% while the rate of [[unemployment]] increased to 25% (with industrial unemployment alone rising to approximately 35% \u2013 U.S. employment was still over 25% agricultural).{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nA long-term effect of the Great Depression was the departure of every major currency from the [[gold standard]], although the initial impetus for this was World War II (see [[Bretton Woods Accord]]).\n\n===Great Depression of 2020 (predicted)===\n\nThe worst economic disaster since the great depression occurred due to the COVID-19 Pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Monetary Fund Head Predicts Coronavirus Will Trigger 'Worst Economic Fallout Since the Great Depression |url=https://time.com/5818819/imf-coronavirus-economic-collapse/ |website=Time Magazine |publisher=Time Magazine}}</ref>  It is predicted by many to be a great depression.<ref>{{cite web |title=We Are Facing A Depression, Not A Recession |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnmauldin/2020/03/23/we-are-facing-a-depression-not-a-recession/#7d4b4a1a4bd3 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ray Dalio predicts a coronavirus depression: \u2018This is bigger than what happened in 2008\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/09/ray-dalio-predicts-coronavirus-depression-this-is-bigger-than-2008.html |website=CNBC |publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The current unemployment rate is estimated to be 13% <ref>{{cite web |title=The Unemployment Rate Is Probably Around 13 Percent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/upshot/coronavirus-jobless-rate-great-depression.html |website=NYTimes |publisher=New York Times}}</ref> Global Economy is estimated to shrink approximately 1%<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 likely to shrink global GDP by almost one per cent in 2020|url=https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/blog/2020/04/covid-19-likely-to-shrink-global-gdp-by-almost-one-per-cent-in-2020/ |website=UN.org |publisher=United Nations}}</ref>\n\n===Greek Depression===\n{{main|European sovereign-debt crisis}}\nBeginning in 2009, Greece sank into a recession that, after two years, [[Greek government-debt crisis|became a depression]]. The country saw an almost 20% drop in economic output, and unemployment soared to near 25%.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/14/greece-gdp-idUSL5E8ME4WM20121114 |title=Greece sinks deeper into depression in third quarter |newspaper=Reuters |date= 2012-11-14|accessdate=2012-11-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114221922/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/14/greece-gdp-idUSL5E8ME4WM20121114 |archivedate=2012-11-14 }}</ref> Greece's high amounts of sovereign debt precipitated the crisis, and the poor performance of its economy since the introduction of severe [[austerity]] measures has slowed the entire eurozone's recovery. Greece's continuing troubles have led to discussions about [[Greek withdrawal from the eurozone|its departure from the eurozone]].\n\n==Other depressions==\n===Global===\nThe late 1910s and early 1920s were marked by an economic depression that unraveled in particularly catastrophic circumstances: The [[Great War]] and its aftermath led to a global nosedive in commodities that ruined many developing nations, while servicemen returning from the trenches found themselves with high unemployment as businesses failed, unable to transition into a peacetime economy. Also, the [[Spanish flu pandemic]] of 1918-20 brought economic activity to a standstill as even more people became incapacitated. Most developed countries had mostly recovered by 1921\u201322, however [[Germany]] saw its economy crippled until 1923-24 because of the hyperinflation crisis.\n\nThe [[1973 oil crisis]], coupled with the rising costs of maintenance of [[welfare state]] in most countries led to a [[1973-75 recession|recession between 1973 and 1975]], followed by a period of [[stagflation|almost minimal growth and rising inflation and unemployment]]. The [[Early 1980s recession|1980-82 recession]] marked the end of the period.\n\nThe [[Savings and loan crisis|savings & loans]] and the [[leveraged buyout]] crises led to a severe depression in mid-to-late 1989, causing a [[Early 1990s recession|recession in 1990-91]] (also fueled by [[1990 oil price shock|the oil price crisis]]), whose effects lasted as late as 1994. This downturn is more remembered for its political effects: [[British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] had to resign in November 1990 as a result of the socioeconomic debacle caused by her later policies; and while his approval ratings were above 60%, [[U.S. President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] lost the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 election]] to [[Bill Clinton]] because of the domestic malady marked by the depression and increasing urban decay.\n\nIn 2005, the [[2000s energy crisis|persistent oil price rises]] and [[economic overheating]] caused by deregulation led to a gradual deterioration of the world economy with inflation and unemployment rising as growth slowed down: The [[housing bubble]] in the U.S. burst in 2007, and the American economy slipped into a [[Great Recession|recession]]. This, in turn, provoked the failure of many prominent financial institutions throughout 2008, most notably [[Lehman Brothers]], leading to the loss of millions of jobs.\n.\n\n===Regional===\nSeveral Latin American countries had severe downturns in the 1980s: by the Kehoe and Prescott definition of a great depression as at least one year with output 20% below trend, [[Economy of Argentina|Argentina]], [[Economic history of Brazil#Stagnation, inflation, and crisis, 1981-94|Brazil]], [[Economy of Chile|Chile]], and [[Economic history of Mexico#1982 crisis and recovery|Mexico]] experienced great depressions in the 1980s, and Argentina experienced [[Argentine economic crisis (1999-2002)|another]] in 1998\u20132002. South American countries fell once again into this in the early-to-mid 2010s.\n\nThis definition also includes the economic performance of [[Economy of New Zealand|New Zealand]] from 1974\u20131992 and [[Economy of Switzerland|Switzerland]] from 1973 to the present, although this designation for Switzerland has been controversial.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Abrahamsen, Y. |author2=Aeppli, R. |author3=Atukeren, E. |author4=Graff, M. |author5=M\u00fcller, C. |author6=Schips, B. |title=The Swiss disease: Facts and artifacts. A reply to Kehoe and Prescott|journal=[[Review of Economic Dynamics]] |volume=8 |year=2005 |issue=3 |pages=749\u2013758 |doi=10.1016/j.red.2004.06.003|hdl=10419/50866 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Kehoe, T. J. |author2=Ruhl, K. J. |year=2005|title=Is Switzerland in a Great Depression?|publisher=[[Review of Economic Dynamics]]|volume=8|pages=759\u2013775}}</ref>\n\nOver the period 1980\u20132000, Sub-Saharan Africa broadly suffered a fall in absolute income levels.<ref name=\"kick\">{{cite magazine |author-link=Ha Joon Chang |last=Chang |first=Ha-Joon |url=http://www.paecon.net/PAEtexts/Chang1.htm |title=Kicking Away the Ladder |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151217161243/http://www.paecon.net/PAEtexts/Chang1.htm |archive-date=2015-12-17 |journal=[[Post-Autistic Economics Review]] |date=September 4, 2002 |number=15 |at=article 3 |access-date=8 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Communism===\nThe economic crisis in the 1990s that struck former members of the [[Soviet Union]] was almost twice as intense as the Great Depression in the countries of [[Western Europe]] and the United States in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |title=What Can Transition Economies Learn from the First Ten Years? A New World Bank Report in Transition Newsletter |url=http://worldbank.org/transitionnewsletter/janfeb2002 |date= |publisher=Worldbank.org |accessdate= }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.k-a.kg/?nid=5&value=6 |title=Kalikova & Associates - Law Firm |language=ru |publisher=K-a.kg |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120907055134/http://www.k-a.kg/?nid=5&value=6 |archivedate=2012-09-07 }}</ref><ref name=Russia>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/books/who-lost-russia.html Who Lost Russia?], ''The New York Times'', October 8, 2000</ref> Average [[Standard of living|standards of living]] registered a catastrophic fall in the early 1990s in many parts of the former [[Eastern Bloc]], most notably in [[post-Soviet states]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/966616.stm |title=Child poverty soars in eastern Europe |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040718232818/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/966616.stm |archive-date=2004-07-18 |url-status=live|work=BBC News |date=October 11, 2000}}</ref> Even before Russia's [[1998 Russian financial crisis|financial crisis]] of 1998, [[Russia]]'s GDP was half of what it had been in the early 1990s.<ref name=Russia/> Some populations are still poorer today than they were in 1989 (e.g. [[Ukraine]], [[Moldova]], [[Serbia]], [[Soviet Central Asia|Central Asia]], [[Caucasus]]).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The collapse of the Soviet planned economy and the [[Shock therapy (economics)|transition to market economy]] resulted in catastrophic declines in GDP of about 45% during the 1990\u20131996 period<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citymayors.com/society/easteurope_cities.html |title=Poverty, crime and migration are acute issues as Eastern European cities continue to grow |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102083735/http://citymayors.com/society/easteurope_cities.html |archive-date=2010-01-02 |type=A report by UN-Habitat |date=January 11, 2005}}</ref> and poverty in the region had increased more than tenfold.<ref>{{Citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/12/world/study-finds-poverty-deepening-in-former-communist-countries.html |title=Study Finds Poverty Deepening in Former Communist Countries |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 12, 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205184219/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/12/world/study-finds-poverty-deepening-in-former-communist-countries.html |archivedate=February 5, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nFinnish economists refer to the [[Early 1990s depression in Finland|Finnish economic decline]] around the breakup of the Soviet Union (1989\u20131994) as a great depression (''suuri lama''). However, the depression was multicausal, with its severity compounded by a coincidence of multiple sudden external shocks, including loss of Soviet trade, the [[savings and loan crisis]] and [[early 1990s recession]] in the West, with the internal overheating that had been brewing throughout the 1980s. Liberalization had resulted in the so-called \"casino economy\". Persistent structural and monetary policy problems had not been solved, leaving the economy vulnerable to even mild external shocks. The depression had lasting effects: the Finnish markka was floated and was eventually replaced by the euro in 1999, ending decades of government control of the economy, but also high, persistent unemployment. Employment has never returned even close to the pre-crisis level.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Great Recession]]\n* [[L-shaped recession]]\n* [[List of recessions]]\n* [[List of recessions in the United States]]\n* [[Recession]]\n* [[Stagflation]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{US recessions}}\n\n[[Category:Economic crises]]\n[[Category:Recessions|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Globalize|article|Anglophone|2name=[[English-speaking world|the English-speaking world]]|date=October 2012}}\nIn [[economics]], a '''depression''' is a sustained, long-term downturn in economic activity in one or more economies. It is a more severe economic downturn than a [[economic recession|recession]], which is a slowdown in economic activity over the course of a normal [[business cycle]].\n\n'''Depressions''' are characterized by their length, by abnormally large increases in [[unemployment]], falls in the availability of [[credit (finance)|credit]] (often due to some form of banking or financial crisis), shrinking output as buyers dry up and suppliers cut back on production and investment, more [[bankruptcies]] including sovereign debt defaults, significantly reduced amounts of [[trade]] and commerce (especially international trade), as well as highly volatile relative currency value fluctuations (often due to currency [[devaluation]]s). Price [[deflation (economics)|deflation]], [[financial crisis|financial crises]], [[stock market crash]], and [[bank failure]]s are also common elements of a depression that do not normally occur during a recession.\n\n==Definitions==\nIn the [[United States]] the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] determines contractions and expansions in the business cycle, but does not declare depressions.<ref name=\"nber.org\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nber.org/cycles/recessions_faq.html |title=The NBER's Business Cycle Dating Procedure: Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Nber.org |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008141654/http://www.nber.org/cycles/recessions_faq.html |archivedate=2012-10-08 }}</ref> Generally, periods labeled depressions are marked by a substantial and sustained shortfall of the ability to purchase goods relative to the amount that could be produced using current resources and technology ([[potential output]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/history/A0821657.html |title=Private Tutor |publisher=Infoplease.com |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913025403/http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/history/A0821657.html |archivedate=2012-09-13 }}</ref> Another proposed definition of ''depression'' includes two general rules:<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12852043 | work=The Economist | title=Diagnosing depression | date=December 30, 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215002935/http://www.economist.com/finance/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12852043 | archivedate=February 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://businesscycles.info/recession-definition/ |title=Home Improvement Tips and Techniques &#124; Business Cycles |accessdate=2009-04-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202110823/http://businesscycles.info/recession-definition/ |archivedate=2009-02-02 }}</ref>\n# a decline in real GDP exceeding 10%, or\n# a recession lasting 2 or more years.\n\nThere are also differences in the duration of depression across definitions. Some economists refer only to the period when economic activity is declining. The more common use, however, also encompasses the time until the economic activity has returned close to normal levels.<ref name=\"nber.org\"/>\n\nA recession is briefly defined as a period of declining economic activity spread across the economy (according to NBER). Under the first definition, each depression will always coincide with a recession, since the difference between a depression and a recession is the severity of the fall in economic activity.  In other words, each depression is always a recession, sharing the same starting and ending dates and having the same duration.\n\nUnder the second definition, depressions and recessions will always be distinct events however, having the same starting dates. This definition of depression implies that a recession and a depression will have different ending dates and thus distinct durations. Under this definition, the length of depression will always be longer than that of the recession starting the same date.\n\nA useful example is a difference in the chronology of the Great Depression in the U.S. under the view of alternative definitions. Using the second definition of depression, most economists refer to the Great Depression, as the period between 1929 and 1941. On the other hand, using the first definition, the depression that started in August 1929 lasted until March 1933. Note that NBER, which publishes the recession (instead of depression) dates for the U.S. economy, has identified two recessions during that period. The first between August 1929 and March 1933 and the second starting in May 1937 and ending in June 1938.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nber.org/cycles/ |title=US Business Cycle Expansions and Contractions |publisher=National Bureau of Economic Research |accessdate=2008-10-01 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219215409/https://www.nber.org/cycles/ |archivedate=2009-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nToday the term \"depression\" is most often associated with the [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s, but the term had been in use long before then. Indeed, an early major American economic crisis, the [[Panic of 1819]], was described by then-president [[James Monroe]] as \"a depression\",<ref name=\"hnn\">{{cite web|url=http://hnn.us/articles/61931.html|title=When Did the Great Depression Receive Its Name? (And Who Named It?)|website=hnn.us |accessdate=9 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901125648/http://hnn.us/articles/61931.html|archivedate=1 September 2013}}</ref> and the economic crisis immediately preceding the 1930s depression, the [[Depression of 1920\u201321]], was referred to as a \"depression\" by president [[Calvin Coolidge]].\n\nHowever, in the 19th and early 20th centuries, ''financial'' crises were traditionally referred to as \"panics\", e.g., the 'major' [[Panic of 1907]], and the 'minor' [[Panic of 1910\u20131911]], though the 1929 crisis was more commonly called \"The Crash\", and the term \"panic\" has since fallen out of use. At the time of the Great Depression (of the 1930s), the phrase \"The Great Depression\" had already been used to refer to the period 1873\u201396 (in the United Kingdom), or more narrowly 1873\u201379 (in the United States), which has since been renamed the [[Long Depression]].\n\nCommon use of the phrase \"The Great Depression\" for the 1930s crisis is most frequently attributed to British economist [[Lionel Robbins]], whose 1934 book ''The Great Depression'' is credited with 'formalizing' the phrase,<ref name=\"hnn\"/> though US president [[Herbert Hoover]] is widely credited with having 'popularized' the term/phrase,<ref name=\"hnn\" /><ref>''The Glory and the Dream: A Narrative History of America, 1932\u20131972'', William Manchester</ref> informally referring to the downturn as a \"depression\", with such uses as \"Economic depression cannot be cured by legislative action or executive pronouncement\", (December 1930, Message to Congress) and \"I need not recount to you that the world is passing through a great depression\" (1931).\n\n==Occurrence== \nDue to the lack of an agreed definition and the strong negative associations, the characterization of any period as a \"depression\" is contentious. The term was frequently used for regional crises from the early 19th century until the 1930s, and for the more widespread crises of the 1870s and 1930s, but economic crises since 1945 have generally been referred to as \"recessions\", with the 1970s global crisis referred to as \"[[stagflation]]\", but not a depression. The only two eras commonly referred to at the current time as \"depressions\" are the 1870s and 1930s.<ref name=\"krug2010\">{{citation | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/opinion/28krugman.html | first = Paul | last = Krugman | author-link = Paul Krugman | title = The Third Depression | date = June 27, 2010 | journal = [[The New York Times]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120411051630/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/28/opinion/28krugman.html | archive-date = April 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nTo some degree this is simply a stylistic change, similar to the decline in the use of \"panic\" to refer to financial crises, but it does also reflect that the [[economic cycle]] \u2013 both in the United States and in most [[OECD]] countries \u2013 though not in all \u2013 has been more moderate since 1945.\n\nThere ''have'' been many periods of prolonged economic underperformance in particular countries/regions since 1945, detailed below, but terming these as \"depressions\" is controversial. The 2008-2009 economic cycle, which has comprised the most significant global crisis since the Great Depression, has at times been termed a depression,<ref name=\"krug2010\" /> but this terminology is not widely used, with the episode instead being referred to by other terms, such as the \"[[Great Recession]]\".\n\n== Notable depressions ==\n\n===The General Crisis of 1640===\n{{main|The General Crisis}}\nThe largest Great Depression of all time occurred during the General Crisis. The Ming Province of China went bankrupt and the Stuart Monarchy was in the civil war on three fronts in Ireland, Scotland, and England. [[Thomas Hobbes]], an English philosopher, created the first recorded explanation of the need for a universal [[Social Contract]] in his 1652 book [[Leviathan]] based on the general misery within society during this period.\n[[File:Past Great Depressions.jpg|thumb|Great Depressions (Mature Capitalisms) and Results ...]]\n\n===Great Depression of 1837===\n\nThis depression is acknowledged to be a worse Great Depression than the later Great Depression of the 1930s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Social History of an American Depression, 1837-1843|journal=The American Historical Review|volume=40|issue=4|pages=662\u2013687|date=1935-07-01|df=|jstor = 1842418|last1 = Rezneck|first1 = Samuel|doi=10.2307/1842418}}</ref> This great depression ended in the United States due to the California Gold Rush and its ten-times addition to the United States' gold reserves. As with most great depressions, it was followed by a thirty-year period of a booming economy in the United States, that is now called the [[Second Industrial Revolution]] (of the 1850s).\n\n===Panic of 1837===\n{{main|Panic of 1837}}\nThe Panic of 1837 was an American [[financial crisis]], built on a [[Speculation|speculative]] real estate market.<ref name=\"politonomist.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politonomist.com/history-of-economic-recessions-00273/3/|title=Panic of 1837 (1837 - 1842) \u2014 History of Economic Recessions|date=2009-01-02|publisher=Politonomist.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406205415/http://www.politonomist.com/history-of-economic-recessions-00273/3/|archivedate=2009-04-06|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-09-07}}</ref> The bubble burst on May 10, 1837 in [[New York City]], when every [[bank]] stopped payment in [[gold]] and [[silver]] [[coin]]age. The Panic was followed by a five-year depression,<ref name=\"politonomist.com\" /> with the failure of [[bank]]s and record high unemployment levels.<ref name=\"Glasner\">{{Cite book|title=Business cycles and depressions: an encyclopedia|author=Timberlake, Richard H. Jr.|publisher=Garland Publishing|year=1997|isbn=978-0-8240-0944-1|editor1=Glasner, David|location=New York|pages=514\u201316|chapter=Panic of 1837|editor2=Cooley, Thomas F.|chapter-url-access=registration|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/businesscyclesde00glas}}</ref>\n\n=== Long Depression ===\n[[File: Tompkins square riot 1874.jpg|thumb|New York police violently attacking unemployed workers in [[Tompkins Square Riot (1874)|Tompkins Square Park]], 1874]]\n{{details|Long Depression}}\nStarting with the adoption of the [[gold standard]] in Britain and the United States, the [[Long Depression]] (1873\u20131896) was indeed longer than what is now referred to as the Great Depression, but shallower. However, it was known as \"the Great Depression\" until the 1930s.{{CN|date=November 2018}}\n\n===Great Depression===\n{{main|Great Depression}}\nThe [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s affected most national economies in the world.  This depression is generally considered to have begun with the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]], and the crisis quickly spread to other national economies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.english.uiuc.edu/maps/depression/about.htm |title=About the Great Depression |publisher=English.uiuc.edu |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220090243/http://www.english.uiuc.edu/maps/depression/about.htm |archivedate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> Between 1929 and 1933, the [[gross national product]] of the [[United States]] decreased by 33% while the rate of [[unemployment]] increased to 25% (with industrial unemployment alone rising to approximately 35% \u2013 U.S. employment was still over 25% agricultural).{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}  \n\nA long-term effect of the Great Depression was the departure of every major currency from the [[gold standard]], although the initial impetus for this was World War II (see [[Bretton Woods Accord]]).\n\n===Great Depression of 2020 (predicted)===\n\nThe worst economic disaster since the great depression occured due to the COVID-19 Pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Monetary Fund Head Predicts Coronavirus Will Trigger 'Worst Economic Fallout Since the Great Depression |url=https://time.com/5818819/imf-coronavirus-economic-collapse/ |website=Time Magazine |publisher=Time Magazine}}</ref>  It is predicted by many to be a great depression.<ref>{{cite web |title=We Are Facing A Depression, Not A Recession |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnmauldin/2020/03/23/we-are-facing-a-depression-not-a-recession/#7d4b4a1a4bd3 |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ray Dalio predicts a coronavirus depression: \u2018This is bigger than what happened in 2008\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/09/ray-dalio-predicts-coronavirus-depression-this-is-bigger-than-2008.html |website=CNBC |publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The current unemployment rate is estimated to be 13% <ref>{{cite web |title=The Unemployment Rate Is Probably Around 13 Percent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/upshot/coronavirus-jobless-rate-great-depression.html |website=NYTimes |publisher=New York Times}}</ref> Global Economy is estimated to shrink approximately 1%<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 likely to shrink global GDP by almost one per cent in 2020|url=https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/blog/2020/04/covid-19-likely-to-shrink-global-gdp-by-almost-one-per-cent-in-2020/ |website=UN.org |publisher=United Nations}}</ref>\n\n===Greek Depression===\n{{main|European sovereign-debt crisis}}\nBeginning in 2009, Greece sank into a recession that, after two years, [[Greek government-debt crisis|became a depression]]. The country saw an almost 20% drop in economic output, and unemployment soared to near 25%.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/14/greece-gdp-idUSL5E8ME4WM20121114 |title=Greece sinks deeper into depression in third quarter |newspaper=Reuters |date= 2012-11-14|accessdate=2012-11-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114221922/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/14/greece-gdp-idUSL5E8ME4WM20121114 |archivedate=2012-11-14 }}</ref> Greece's high amounts of sovereign debt precipitated the crisis, and the poor performance of its economy since the introduction of severe [[austerity]] measures has slowed the entire eurozone's recovery. Greece's continuing troubles have led to discussions about [[Greek withdrawal from the eurozone|its departure from the eurozone]].\n\n==Other depressions==\n===Global===\nThe late 1910s and early 1920s were marked by an economic depression that unraveled in particularly catastrophic circumstances: The [[Great War]] and its aftermath led to a global nosedive in commodities that ruined many developing nations, while servicemen returning from the trenches found themselves with high unemployment as businesses failed, unable to transition into a peacetime economy. Also, the [[Spanish flu pandemic]] of 1918-20 brought economic activity to a standstill as even more people became incapacitated. Most developed countries had mostly recovered by 1921-22, however [[Germany]] saw its economy crippled until 1923-24 because of the hyperinflation crisis.\n\nThe [[1973 oil crisis]], coupled with the rising costs of maintenance of [[welfare state]] in most countries led to a [[1973-75 recession|recession between 1973 and 1975]], followed by a period of [[stagflation|almost minimal growth and rising inflation and unemployment]]. The [[Early 1980s recession|1980-82 recession]] marked the end of the period.\n\nThe [[Savings and loan crisis|savings & loans]] and the [[leveraged buyout]] crises led to a severe depression in mid-to-late 1989, causing a [[Early 1990s recession|recession in 1990-91]] (also fueled by [[1990 oil price shock|the oil price crisis]]), whose effects lasted as late as 1994. This downturn is more remembered for its political effects: [[British Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] had to resign in November 1990 as a result of the socioeconomic debacle caused by her later policies; and while his approval ratings were above 60%, [[U.S. President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] lost the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 election]] to [[Bill Clinton]] because of the domestic malady marked by the depression and increasing urban decay.\n\nIn 2005, the [[2000s energy crisis|persistent oil price rises]] and [[economic overheating]] caused by deregulation led to a gradual deterioration of the world economy with inflation and unemployment rising as growth slowed down: The [[housing bubble]] in the U.S. burst in 2007, and the American economy slipped into a [[Great Recession|recession]]. This, in turn, provoked the failure of many prominent financial institutions throughout 2008, most notably [[Lehman Brothers]], leading to the loss of millions of jobs.\n.\n\n===Regional===\nSeveral Latin American countries had severe downturns in the 1980s: by the Kehoe and Prescott definition of a great depression as at least one year with output 20% below trend, [[Economy of Argentina|Argentina]], [[Economic history of Brazil#Stagnation, inflation, and crisis, 1981-94|Brazil]], [[Economy of Chile|Chile]], and [[Economic history of Mexico#1982 crisis and recovery|Mexico]] experienced great depressions in the 1980s, and Argentina experienced [[Argentine economic crisis (1999-2002)|another]] in 1998\u20132002. South American countries fell once again into this in the early-to-mid 2010s.\n\nThis definition also includes the economic performance of [[Economy of New Zealand|New Zealand]] from 1974\u20131992 and [[Economy of Switzerland|Switzerland]] from 1973 to the present, although this designation for Switzerland has been controversial.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Abrahamsen, Y. |author2=Aeppli, R. |author3=Atukeren, E. |author4=Graff, M. |author5=M\u00fcller, C. |author6=Schips, B. |title=The Swiss disease: Facts and artifacts. A reply to Kehoe and Prescott|journal=[[Review of Economic Dynamics]] |volume=8 |year=2005 |issue=3 |pages=749\u2013758 |doi=10.1016/j.red.2004.06.003|hdl=10419/50866 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Kehoe, T. J. |author2=Ruhl, K. J. |year=2005|title=Is Switzerland in a Great Depression?|publisher=[[Review of Economic Dynamics]]|volume=8|pages=759\u2013775}}</ref>\n\nOver the period 1980\u20132000, Sub-Saharan Africa broadly suffered a fall in absolute income levels.<ref name=\"kick\">{{cite magazine |author-link=Ha Joon Chang |last=Chang |first=Ha-Joon |url=http://www.paecon.net/PAEtexts/Chang1.htm |title=Kicking Away the Ladder |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151217161243/http://www.paecon.net/PAEtexts/Chang1.htm |archive-date=2015-12-17 |journal=[[Post-Autistic Economics Review]] |date=September 4, 2002 |number=15 |at=article 3 |access-date=8 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Communism===\nThe economic crisis in the 1990s that struck former members of the [[Soviet Union]] was almost twice as intense as the Great Depression in the countries of [[Western Europe]] and the United States in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |title=What Can Transition Economies Learn from the First Ten Years? A New World Bank Report in Transition Newsletter |url=http://worldbank.org/transitionnewsletter/janfeb2002 |date= |publisher=Worldbank.org |accessdate= }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.k-a.kg/?nid=5&value=6 |title=Kalikova & Associates - Law Firm |language=ru |publisher=K-a.kg |accessdate=2012-09-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120907055134/http://www.k-a.kg/?nid=5&value=6 |archivedate=2012-09-07 }}</ref><ref name=Russia>[https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/08/books/who-lost-russia.html Who Lost Russia?], ''The New York Times'', October 8, 2000</ref> Average [[Standard of living|standards of living]] registered a catastrophic fall in the early 1990s in many parts of the former [[Eastern Bloc]], most notably in [[post-Soviet states]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/966616.stm |title=Child poverty soars in eastern Europe |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040718232818/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/966616.stm |archive-date=2004-07-18 |url-status=live|work=BBC News |date=October 11, 2000}}</ref> Even before Russia's [[1998 Russian financial crisis|financial crisis]] of 1998, [[Russia]]'s GDP was half of what it had been in the early 1990s.<ref name=Russia/> Some populations are still poorer today than they were in 1989 (e.g. [[Ukraine]], [[Moldova]], [[Serbia]], [[Soviet Central Asia|Central Asia]], [[Caucasus]]).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The collapse of the Soviet planned economy and the [[Shock therapy (economics)|transition to market economy]] resulted in catastrophic declines in GDP of about 45% during the 1990\u20131996 period<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citymayors.com/society/easteurope_cities.html |title=Poverty, crime and migration are acute issues as Eastern European cities continue to grow |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102083735/http://citymayors.com/society/easteurope_cities.html |archive-date=2010-01-02 |type=A report by UN-Habitat |date=January 11, 2005}}</ref> and poverty in the region had increased more than tenfold.<ref>{{Citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/12/world/study-finds-poverty-deepening-in-former-communist-countries.html |title=Study Finds Poverty Deepening in Former Communist Countries |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 12, 2000 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205184219/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/12/world/study-finds-poverty-deepening-in-former-communist-countries.html |archivedate=February 5, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nFinnish economists refer to the [[Early 1990s depression in Finland|Finnish economic decline]] around the breakup of the Soviet Union (1989\u20131994) as a great depression (''suuri lama''). However, the depression was multicausal, with its severity compounded by a coincidence of multiple sudden external shocks, including loss of Soviet trade, the [[savings and loan crisis]] and [[early 1990s recession]] in the West, with the internal overheating that had been brewing throughout the 1980s. Liberalization had resulted in the so-called \"casino economy\". Persistent structural and monetary policy problems had not been solved, leaving the economy vulnerable to even mild external shocks. The depression had lasting effects: the Finnish markka was floated and was eventually replaced by the euro in 1999, ending decades of government control of the economy, but also high, persistent unemployment. Employment has never returned even close to the pre-crisis level.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Great Recession]]\n* [[L-shaped recession]]\n* [[List of recessions]]\n* [[List of recessions in the United States]]\n* [[Recession]]\n* [[Stagflation]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{US recessions}}\n\n[[Category:Economic crises]]\n[[Category:Recessions|*]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: occured \u2192 occurred, 1921-22 \u2192 1921\u201322", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depression_(economics)"}
{"title_page": "Brett Kern", "text_new": "{{short description|American football punter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Brett Kern\n|image=Brett Kern 2018 08-09.jpg\n|image_size=250px\n|alt=\n|caption=Kern in 2018\n|current_team = Tennessee Titans \n|number=6\n|position=[[Punter (American football)|Punter]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1986|2|17|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Grand Island, New York]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 2\n|weight_lbs = 214\n|high_school = [[Grand Island Senior High School (New York)|Grand Island (NY)]]\n|college=[[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n|undraftedyear=2008\n|pastteams=\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n|highlights=\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2018 Pro Bowl|2017]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2008|2008]])\n* [[Mid-American Conference football individual awards|MAC Special Teams Player of the Year]] (2007)\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=Punts\n|statvalue1=912\n|statlabel2=Punting yards\n|statvalue2=41,928\n|statlabel3=Punting average\n|statvalue3=45.9\n|statlabel4=Inside 20\n|statvalue4=355\n|statlabel5=Long\n|statvalue5=79\n|nfl=KER326640\n}}\n'''Brett Alan Kern''' (born February 17, 1986) is an [[American football]] [[Punter (American football)|punter]] for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He was signed by the [[Denver Broncos]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2008. He played [[college football]] at [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]].\n\nAfter being waved by the Broncos after less than two full seasons, he was then acquired by the Titans and has since been a three-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection and a two-time [[All-Pro]].\n\n==High school career==\nKern is a 2004 graduate of Grand Island High School, where he played on the [[high school football|football]] team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Brett-Kern-6997/high-school-12098 |title=Brett Kern, Grand Island Senior, Punter |website=247Sports |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He was named All-New York State as a senior and was a member of the schools Section VI championship. Following graduation from high school, Kern represented New York State in the New York-New Jersey Governor's Bowl played at the [[United States Military Academy]]. He also played basketball and was a long jumper and high hurdler on the track team.\n\n==College career==\nKern played [[college football]] at the University of [[Toledo Rockets|Toledo]] for head coach [[Tom Amstutz]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1.html |title=Brett Kern College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2004 season===\n\n{{See also|2004 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nAs a freshman in 2004, Kern was immediately inserted into the role of punter for the Rockets. In his collegiate debut, he had eight punts for 344 net yards (43.0 average) against [[2004 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-09-04-minnesota.html |title=Toledo at Minnesota Box Score, September 4, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2004 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high nine punts for a season-high 357 net yards (39.7 average).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-09-11-kansas.html |title=Toledo at Kansas Box Score, September 11, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 16, against [[2004 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio]], he had two punts for 101 net yards for a season-high 50.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-16-toledo.html |title=Ohio at Toledo Box Score, October 16, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2004 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]], he recorded his first collegiate pass, a successful 46-yard throw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-23-toledo.html |title=Central Michigan at Toledo Box Score, October 23, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On the season, he had 44 punts for 1,788 net yards for a 40.6 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2004/ |title=Brett Kern 2004 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2005 season===\n\n{{See also|2005 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern continued to contribute in his second season as the Rockets' punter. On September 1, in the season opener against [[Western Illinois Leathernecks football|Western Illinois]], he had three punts for 99 net yards for a 33.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-09-01-toledo.html|title=Western Illinois at Toledo Box Score, September 1, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 27, against [[2005 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]], he had five punts for a season-high 206 net yards for a 41.2 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-09-27-fresno-state.html|title=Toledo at Fresno State Box Score, September 27, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 15, against [[2005 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State]], he had a successful passing attempt for 34 yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-15-ball-state.html|title=Toledo at Ball State Box Score, October 15, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> \nOn October 22 against [[2005 Buffalo Bulls football team|Buffalo]], he had two punts for 91 net yards for a season-high 45.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-22-toledo.html|title=Buffalo at Toledo Box Score, October 22, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2005 season, he had 33 punts for 1,305 yards for a 39.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2005/ |title=Brett Kern 2005 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2006 season===\n\n{{See also|2006 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern's punting career continued into his junior season in 2006. On August 31, against [[2006 Iowa State Cyclones football team|Iowa State]], he had a single punt for 46 yards in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-08-31-iowa-state.html|title=Toledo at Iowa State Box Score, August 31, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 15, against [[2006 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high 12 punts for a season-high 484 net yards for a 40.3 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-09-15-toledo.html|title=Kansas at Toledo Box Score, September 15, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 7, against [[2006 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]], he completed a 25-yard pass.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-10-07-toledo.html|title=Central Michigan at Toledo Box Score, October 7, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2006 season, he had 60 punts for 2,502 net yards for a 41.7 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2006/ |title=Brett Kern 2006 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2007 season===\n\n{{See also|2007 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern's final season with the Rockets was in 2007. On September 1, against [[2007 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]], he had eight punts for 394 net yards for a 49.3 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-01-toledo.html|title=Purdue at Toledo Box Score, September 1, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 15, against [[2007 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high 10 punts for a season-high 420 net yards for a 42.00 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-15-kansas.html|title=Toledo at Kansas Box Score, September 15, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 29, 2007, against [[2007 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]], he had six punts for 323 net yards for a season-high 53.8 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-29-toledo.html|title=Western Michigan at Toledo Box Score, September 29, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 27, against [[2007 Northern Illinois Huskies football team|Northern Illinois]], he had a 50-yard rush in the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-10-27-toledo.html|title=Northern Illinois at Toledo Box Score, October 27, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The MAC Report Online named Kern the Mid-American Conference\u2019s \u2018\u2019Special Teams Player of the Year\u2019\u2019 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utrockets.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=18000&ATCLID=1325065|title=Brett Kern Named MAC Report Online 2007 Special Teams Player of the Year - University of Toledo Rockets Athletics Official Site - UTRockets.com|publisher=www.utrockets.com|accessdate=August 24, 2008|last=|first=}}</ref> Kern was also a finalist for the [[Ray Guy Award]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toledo.scout.com/2/703411.html|title=Brett Kern Named Ray Guy Award Finalist|publisher=ROCKET DIGEST.COM|author=Brian Nowicki|date=November 19, 2007|accessdate=May 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227012728/http://toledo.scout.com/2/703411.html|archive-date=February 27, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> That year, he averaged 46.5 yards per punt, second in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toledo.scout.com/2/696974.html|title=Scout.com: Brett Kern Named Ray Guy Semifinalist|publisher=toledo.scout.com|accessdate=August 24, 2008|last=Nowicki|first=Brian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703161229/http://toledo.scout.com/2/696974.html|archive-date=July 3, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Overall, in his final season, he had 52 total punts for 2,399 yards for a 46.1 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2007 |title=Brett Kern 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! School\n! Class\n! \n! Punts\n! Yards\n! Average\n|-\n| [[2004 NCAA Division I-A football season|2004]]\n| [[2004 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Freshman\n| P\n| 44\n| 1,788\n| 40.6\n|-\n| [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n| [[2005 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Sophomore\n| P\n| 33\n| 1,305\n| 39.5\n|-\n| [[2006 NCAA Division I-A football season|2006]]\n| [[2006 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Junior\n| P\n| 60\n| 2,502\n| 41.7\n|-\n| [[2007 NCAA Division I-A football season|2007]]\n| [[2007 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Senior\n| P\n| 52\n| 2,399\n| 46.1\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | Career\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 189\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 7,994\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 42.3\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Denver Broncos===\n====2008 season: Rookie year====\n{{See also|2008 Denver Broncos season}}\n\nIn 2008, Kern won the starting punter job for the [[2008 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]], winning the job over competitor [[Sam Paulescu]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_10345953 | work=Denver Post | first=Lindsay H. | last=Jones | title=Kern survives punters' war | date=August 31, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDuring his rookie season with the Broncos, Kern attempted 46 punts for an average of 46.7. He made his NFL debut the season opener against the [[2008 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had two punts for 80 net yards for a 40.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809080rai.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Oakland Raiders - September 8th, 2008|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> His longest punt of the year was 64 yards against the [[2008 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] in Week 2.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140den.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at Denver Broncos - September 14th, 2008  |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 5, against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, he had 5 punts for a season-high 248 net yards for a 49.6 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200810050den.htm|title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Denver Broncos - October 5th, 2008|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He gave away one touchdown that year against the Oakland Raiders in Week 12 when [[Johnnie Lee Higgins]] took the punt back 89 yards for the score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200811230den.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Denver Broncos - November 23rd, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2008/ |title=Brett Kern 2008 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2009 season====\n{{See also|2009 Denver Broncos season}}\n[[File:Brett Kern.JPG|thumb|left|225px|Kern in 2009]]\n\nKern remained as the Broncos' punter in his second professional season. In the season opener against the [[2009 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 340 net yards for a 42.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909130cin.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Cincinnati Bengals - September 13th, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 20, against the [[2009 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], he had two punts for 109 net yards for a season-high 54.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909200den.htm|title=Cleveland Browns at Denver Broncos - September 20th, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He finished the 2009 season with 64 punts for 2,910 net yards for a 45.47 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2009/ |title=Brett Kern 2009 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite having the third highest yards per punt average in NFL history,<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/punt_yds_per_punt_career.htm]</ref> Kern was waived by the Broncos.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/broncos/2009/10/26/berger-new-broncos-punter/ |title=Kern waived; Berger new Broncos punter | work=Denver Post | date=October 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\n====2009 season====\n{{See also|2009 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nKern was claimed off waivers by the [[Tennessee Titans]], replacing [[Reggie Hodges]]. At the time Kern was released from the Broncos and claimed by the Titans, the Broncos were [http://www.nfl.com/teams/schedule?team=DEN&season=2009&seasonType=REG 6\u20130] while the Titans were 0\u20136. A subsequent Titans winning streak and Broncos losing streak led to a situation where teams with Kern on the roster had compiled a record of 11\u20130 to begin the season, despite the two teams being a collective 12\u201310 overall in that period.\n\nOn November 1, he made his Titans debut against the [[2009 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He had four punts for 193 net yards for a 48.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911010oti.htm|title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans - November 1st, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOverall, in the 2009 season, he totaled 64 punts for 2,910 yards for a 45.47 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2009/ |title=Brett Kern 2009 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2010 season====\n{{See also|2010 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nKern remained as the Titans' punter in the 2010 season. On September 12, in the season opener against the [[2010 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had four punts for 200 net yards for a season-high 50.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009120oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 12th, 2010|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, in Week 16 against the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 352 net yards for a 44.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012260kan.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - December 26th, 2010|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2010 season, he had 77 punts for 3,302 net yards for a 42.88 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2010 |title=Brett Kern 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\n{{See also|2011 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn February 24, Kern signed a four-year, $5.2 million contract extension with the Titans with $2.1 million guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/Article/Brett-Kern-receives-a-four-year-extension-from-Titans-16346|title=Titans reach deal with punter Kern|last=McCormick|first=Terry|website=247sports.com|date=February 24, 2011 |access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the season opener on September 11, Kern had seven punts for 291 net yards for a 41.57 average against the [[2011 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109110jax.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - September 11th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2011 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he had a 21-yard rush.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109250oti.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Tennessee Titans - September 25th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 30, in Week 8 against the [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 330 net yards for a 41.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110300oti.htm|title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - October 30th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 4, against the [[2011 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], he had five punts for 239 net yards for a season-high 47.8 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040buf.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Buffalo Bills - December 4th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2011 season, he recorded 86 punts for 3,747 net yards for a 43.57 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2011 |title=Brett Kern 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\n{{See also|2012 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season opener on September 9, against the [[2012 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Kern had four punts for 209 net yards for a 52.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090oti.htm|title=New England Patriots at Tennessee Titans - September 9th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 9, against the [[2012 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had three punts for 165 net yards for a season-high 55.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212090clt.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Indianapolis Colts - December 9th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 15 against the [[2012 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], he had a season-high 10 punts for a season-high 391 net yards for a 39.1 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212170oti.htm|title=New York Jets at Tennessee Titans - December 17th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2012 season, he had 81 punts for 3,855 yards for a 47.59 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2012 |title=Brett Kern 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\n\n{{See also|2013 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn September 8, against the [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Kern had five punts for 208 net yards for a 41.6 average in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080pit.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Pittsburgh Steelers - September 8th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[2013 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he had a season-high eight punts for 382 net yards for a 47.75 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309150htx.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Houston Texans - September 15th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 8, against the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he had four punts for 201 net yards for a season-high 50.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201312080den.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Denver Broncos - December 8th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2013 season, he had 78 punts for 3,386 net yards for a 43.41 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2013 |title=Brett Kern 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\n{{See also|2014 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season opener against the [[2014 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Kern had six punts for 304 net yards for a 50.67 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070kan.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - September 7th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On November 9, against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 414 net yards for a 51.75 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411090rav.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Baltimore Ravens - November 9th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 28, against the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had seven punts for 383 net yards for a season-high 54.71 average. In addition, he had a career-long 79-yard punt in the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412280oti.htm|title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - December 28th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the 2014 season, he had 88 punts for 4,118 net yards for a 46.80 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2014 |title=Brett Kern 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n{{See also|2015 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn March 8, 2015, Kern signed a five-year $15 million contract extension with the Titans.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000477236/article/titans-brett-kern-agree-on-multiyear-contract |title=Titans, Brett Kern agree on multiyear contract| work=NFL | date=March 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, against the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had four punts for 189 net yards for a 47.25 average in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130tam.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - September 13th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 20, against the [[2015 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he had five punts for 272 net yards for a season-high 54.4 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200nwe.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - December 20th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 16, on December 27, against the [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he had a season-high nine punts for a season-high 427 net yards for a 47.44 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512270oti.htm|title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - December 27th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2015 season, he recorded 88 punts for 4,175 net yards for a 47.44 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2015 |title=Brett Kern 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{See also|2016 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season-opener against the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Kern had five punts for 231 net yards for a 46.2 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110oti.htm|title=Minnesota Vikings at Tennessee Titans - September 11th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3, against the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had six punts for 311 net yards for a season-high 51.83 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609250oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 25th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 24, in Week 16 against the [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], he had seven punts for a season-high 313 net yards for a 44.71 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612240jax.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - December 24th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the 2016 season, he finished with 77 punts for 3,402 net yards for a 44.18 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2016 |title=Brett Kern 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{See also|2017 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nDuring the season-opener against the [[2017 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Kern had four punts for 188 net yards for a 47 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 10th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 24, in Week 3 against the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], he had six punts for 341 net yards for a season-high 56.83 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709240oti.htm|title=Seattle Seahawks at Tennessee Titans - September 24th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 8, against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], he had a career-high 10 punts for a franchise-record 549 net yards and a 54.9 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710080mia.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Miami Dolphins - October 8th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2017, Kern was named to his first Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> Kern finished the 2017 season with 75 punts for 3,728 net yards for a franchise-record 49.71 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2017 |title=Brett Kern 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He was named second-team All-Pro.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000903015/article/allpro-team-antonio-brown-a-unanimous-selection | title=2017 All-Pro Team | date=January 5, 2018 | accessdate=Jan 5, 2018 | newspaper=[[Associated Press]] }}</ref>\n\nThe Titans finished the 2017 season with a 9\u20137 record and qualified for the playoffs as the #5 seed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/oti/2017.htm |title=2017 Tennessee Titans Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017 |title=2017 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref> In the Wild Card Round against the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Kern made his playoff debut. In the 22\u201321 win, he had three punts for 131 net yards for a 43.7 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801060kan.htm |title=Wild Card - Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - January 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref> In the Divisional Round against the [[2017 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]], he had seven punts for 316 net yards for a 45.14 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n{{See also|2018 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File:BrettKern11-18-18.jpeg|thumb|left|Kern in 2018]]\n\nOn December 18, 2018, Kern was named to his second [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/three-titans-jurrell-casey-taylor-lewan-and-brett-kern-selected-to-pro-bowl-team |title=Three Titans - Jurrel Casey, Taylor Lewan, and Brett Kern - Selected to Pro Bowl Team |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=December 18, 2018 |website=TitansOnline.com |access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref> Kern finished the season punting 74 times with 39 being inside the 20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2018/ |title=Brett Kern 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\n{{see also|2019 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File:Brett Kern.png|thumb|Kern at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] ]]\nOn March 7, 2019, Kern signed a four-year, $12.55 million contract extension with the Titans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.musiccitymiracles.com/2019/3/7/18255355/nfl-tennessee-titans-give-punter-brett-kern-four-year-extension-free-agency-2019 |title=Titans give punter Brett Kern four year extension |last=Lambert |first=Terry A. |date=March 7, 2019 |website=MusicCityMiracles.com}}</ref>  On December 17, 2019, he was selected to his third consecutive [[Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2019/12/17/derrick-henry-brett-kern-titans-pro-bowl/2681124001/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry, Brett Kern named to 2020 Pro Bowl |date=December 17, 2019|agency=The Tennessean |website=www.tennessean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He led the league in punts placed inside the 20-yard line with 37 and was named First-Team All-Pro.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://titanswire.usatoday.com/2020/01/03/titans-brett-kern-derrick-henry-named-all-pros/ |title=Titans P Brett Kern, RB Derrick Henry named All-Pros |date=January 3, 2020|agency=Titans Wire |website=www.titanswire.usatoday.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n|Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n|Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Punts !! Yards !! Long !! Blocks !! Average !! Inside 20\n|-\n| [[2008 NFL season|2008]] || [[2008 Denver Broncos season|DEN]]\n| '''16''' || 46 || 2,150 || 64 || 0 || 46.7 || 13\n|-\n|! rowspan=\"2\" | [[2009 NFL season|2009]] || [[2009 Denver Broncos season|DEN]]\n| 6 || 27 || 1,245 || 64 || 0 || 46.1 || 9\n|-\n| [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| 10 || 37 || 1,665 || 67 || 0 || 45.5 || 18\n|-\n| [[2010 NFL season|2010]] || [[2010 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 77 || 3,302 || 68 || 0 || 42.9 || 24\n|-\n| [[2011 NFL season|2011]] || [[2011 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 86 || 3,747 || 64 || 0 || 43.6 || 31\n|-\n| [[2012 NFL season|2012]] || [[2012 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 81 || 3,855 || 71 || '''2''' || 47.6 || 30\n|-\n| [[2013 NFL season|2013]] || [[2013 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 78 || 3,386 || 63 || 1 || 43.4 || 32\n|-\n| [[2014 NFL season|2014]] || [[2014 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| 14 || '''88''' || 4,118 || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''79''' || 1 || 46.8 || 28\n|-\n| [[2015 NFL season|2015]] || [[2015 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || '''88''' || '''4,175''' || 61 || 0 || 47.4 || 34\n|-\n| [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 77 || 3,402 || 71 || 0 || 44.2 || 32\n|-\n| [[2017 NFL season|2017]] || [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 75 || 3,728 || 74 || 0 || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''49.7''' || 28\n|-\n| [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 74 || 3,483 || 62 || 1 || 47.1 || '''38'''\n|-\n| [[2019 NFL season|2019]] || [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''16''' || 78 || 3,672 || 70 || 0 || 47.1 || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\" | 37\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career || 190 || 912 || 41,928 || 79 || 5 || 45.9 || 355\n|}\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Punts !! Yards !! Long !! Blocks !! Average !! Inside 20\n|-\n| [[2017-18 NFL playoffs|2017]] || [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| 2 || 10 || 447 || 62 || 0 || 44.7 || 4\n|-\n| [[2019-20 NFL playoffs|2019]] || [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''3''' || '''15''' || '''729''' || '''63''' || 0 || '''48.6''' || '''6'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career || 5 || 25 || 1,176 || 63 || 0 || 47.0 || 10\n|}\n\n==Records and achievements==\n\n====Titans/Oilers franchise records====\n* Most Punt Yards (career): 38,533\n* Most Punt Yards (season): 4,175 (2015)\n* Most Punt Yards (game): 549 (2017-10-08 @MIA)\n* Most Yards / Punt (career): 45.9\n* Most Yards / Punt (season): 49.7 (2017)\n* Most Yards / Punt (game): 56.8 (2017-09-24 SEA)\n* Most Yards / Punt (playoff career): 47.1\n\n==Personal life==\nKern is the son of [[Cal Kern]], owner of the amateur [[Niagara Power]] baseball team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/brett-kern-to-host-texas-hold-em-fundraiser-april-13-9829806 |title=Brett Kern to Host Texas Hold 'em Fundraiser April 13 |last=Peters |first=Craig |work=Titans Online |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Kern is married to Tiffany Kern and the couple has three kids, Bryce Jeremiah, Anelle Naomi, and Quinn Eliana. Kern is an avid golfer that sports a +1 handicap. He picked the game up late in his high school years and caddied for three summers at Inverness Golf Club while in college. The course is located in Toledo, Ohio, and has hosted PGA and NCAA Championships. In 2011, Kern competed in The Vinny, a local golf fundraising tournament hosted by singers Vince Gill and Amy Grant, and finished fourth in the event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brett Kern|url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/brett-kern/|website=TitansOnline.com|date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.denverbroncos.com/page.php?id=498&contentID=8675 Denver Broncos bio]\n*[http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000477236/article/titans-brett-kern-agree-on-multiyear-contract]\n{{Tennessee Titans roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kern, Brett}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football punters]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:People from Grand Island, New York]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Erie County, New York]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:Toledo Rockets football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football punter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Brett Kern\n|image=Brett Kern 2018 08-09.jpg\n|image_size=250px\n|alt=\n|caption=Kern in 2018\n|current_team = Tennessee Titans \n|number=6\n|position=[[Punter (American football)|Punter]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1986|2|17|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Grand Island, New York]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 2\n|weight_lbs = 214\n|high_school = [[Grand Island Senior High School (New York)|Grand Island (NY)]]\n|college=[[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n|undraftedyear=2008\n|pastteams=\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2009}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n|highlights=\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2018 Pro Bowl|2017]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2008|2008]])\n* [[Mid-American Conference football individual awards|MAC Special Teams Player of the Year]] (2007)\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=Punts\n|statvalue1=912\n|statlabel2=Punting yards\n|statvalue2=41,928\n|statlabel3=Punting average\n|statvalue3=45.9\n|statlabel4=Inside 20\n|statvalue4=355\n|statlabel5=Long\n|statvalue5=79\n|nfl=KER326640\n}}\n'''Brett Alan Kern''' (born February 17, 1986) is an [[American football]] [[Punter (American football)|punter]] for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He was signed by the [[Denver Broncos]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2008. He played [[college football]] at [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]].\n\nAfter being waved by the Broncos after less than two full seasons, he was then acquired by the Titans and has since been a three-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection and a two-time [[All-Pro]].\n\n==High school career==\nKern is a 2004 graduate of Grand Island High School, where he played on the [[high school football|football]] team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Brett-Kern-6997/high-school-12098 |title=Brett Kern, Grand Island Senior, Punter |website=247Sports |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He was named All-New York State as a senior and was a member of the schools Section VI championship. Following graduation from high school, Kern represented New York State in the New York-New Jersey Governor's Bowl played at the [[United States Military Academy]]. He also played basketball and was a long jumper and high hurdler on the track team.\n\n==College career==\nKern played [[college football]] at the University of [[Toledo Rockets|Toledo]] for head coach [[Tom Amstutz]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1.html |title=Brett Kern College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2004 season===\n\n{{See also|2004 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nAs a freshman in 2004, Kern was immediately inserted into the role of punter for the Rockets. In his collegiate debut, he had eight punts for 344 net yards (43.0 average) against [[2004 Minnesota Golden Gophers football team|Minnesota]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-09-04-minnesota.html |title=Toledo at Minnesota Box Score, September 4, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2004 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high nine punts for a season-high 357 net yards (39.7 average).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-09-11-kansas.html |title=Toledo at Kansas Box Score, September 11, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 16, against [[2004 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio]], he had two punts for 101 net yards for a season-high 50.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-16-toledo.html |title=Ohio at Toledo Box Score, October 16, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2004 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]], he recorded his first collegiate pass, a successful 46-yard throw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2004-10-23-toledo.html |title=Central Michigan at Toledo Box Score, October 23, 2004 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On the season, he had 44 punts for 1,788 net yards for a 40.6 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2004/ |title=Brett Kern 2004 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2005 season===\n\n{{See also|2005 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern continued to contribute in his second season as the Rockets' punter. On September 1, in the season opener against [[Western Illinois Leathernecks football|Western Illinois]], he had three punts for 99 net yards for a 33.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-09-01-toledo.html|title=Western Illinois at Toledo Box Score, September 1, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 27, against [[2005 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]], he had five punts for a season-high 206 net yards for a 41.2 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-09-27-fresno-state.html|title=Toledo at Fresno State Box Score, September 27, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 15, against [[2005 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State]], he had a successful passing attempt for 34 yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-15-ball-state.html|title=Toledo at Ball State Box Score, October 15, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> \nOn October 22 against [[2005 Buffalo Bulls football team|Buffalo]], he had two punts for 91 net yards for a season-high 45.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2005-10-22-toledo.html|title=Buffalo at Toledo Box Score, October 22, 2005|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2005 season, he had 33 punts for 1,305 yards for a 39.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2005/ |title=Brett Kern 2005 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2006 season===\n\n{{See also|2006 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern's punting career continued into his junior season in 2006. On August 31, against [[2006 Iowa State Cyclones football team|Iowa State]], he had a single punt for 46 yards in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-08-31-iowa-state.html|title=Toledo at Iowa State Box Score, August 31, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 15, against [[2006 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high 12 punts for a season-high 484 net yards for a 40.3 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-09-15-toledo.html|title=Kansas at Toledo Box Score, September 15, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 7, against [[2006 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]], he completed a 25-yard pass.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2006-10-07-toledo.html|title=Central Michigan at Toledo Box Score, October 7, 2006|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2006 season, he had 60 punts for 2,502 net yards for a 41.7 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2006/ |title=Brett Kern 2006 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2007 season===\n\n{{See also|2007 Toledo Rockets football team}}\n\nKern's final season with the Rockets was in 2007. On September 1, against [[2007 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]], he had eight punts for 394 net yards for a 49.3 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-01-toledo.html|title=Purdue at Toledo Box Score, September 1, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 15, against [[2007 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], he had a season-high 10 punts for a season-high 420 net yards for a 42.00 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-15-kansas.html|title=Toledo at Kansas Box Score, September 15, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 29, 2007, against [[2007 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]], he had six punts for 323 net yards for a season-high 53.8 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-09-29-toledo.html|title=Western Michigan at Toledo Box Score, September 29, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 27, against [[2007 Northern Illinois Huskies football team|Northern Illinois]], he had a 50-yard rush in the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-10-27-toledo.html|title=Northern Illinois at Toledo Box Score, October 27, 2007|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The MAC Report Online named Kern the Mid-American Conference\u2019s \u2018\u2019Special Teams Player of the Year\u2019\u2019 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utrockets.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=18000&ATCLID=1325065|title=Brett Kern Named MAC Report Online 2007 Special Teams Player of the Year - University of Toledo Rockets Athletics Official Site - UTRockets.com|publisher=www.utrockets.com|accessdate=August 24, 2008|last=|first=}}</ref> Kern was also a finalist for the [[Ray Guy Award]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toledo.scout.com/2/703411.html|title=Brett Kern Named Ray Guy Award Finalist|publisher=ROCKET DIGEST.COM|author=Brian Nowicki|date=November 19, 2007|accessdate=May 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227012728/http://toledo.scout.com/2/703411.html|archive-date=February 27, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> That year, he averaged 46.5 yards per punt, second in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toledo.scout.com/2/696974.html|title=Scout.com: Brett Kern Named Ray Guy Semifinalist|publisher=toledo.scout.com|accessdate=August 24, 2008|last=Nowicki|first=Brian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703161229/http://toledo.scout.com/2/696974.html|archive-date=July 3, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Overall, in his final season, he had 52 total punts for 2,399 yards for a 46.1 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/brett-kern-1/gamelog/2007 |title=Brett Kern 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! School\n! Class\n! \n! Punts\n! Yards\n! Average\n|-\n| [[2004 NCAA Division I-A football season|2004]]\n| [[2004 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Freshman\n| P\n| 44\n| 1,788\n| 40.6\n|-\n| [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n| [[2005 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Sophomore\n| P\n| 33\n| 1,305\n| 39.5\n|-\n| [[2006 NCAA Division I-A football season|2006]]\n| [[2006 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Junior\n| P\n| 60\n| 2,502\n| 41.7\n|-\n| [[2007 NCAA Division I-A football season|2007]]\n| [[2007 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]]\n| Senior\n| P\n| 52\n| 2,399\n| 46.1\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | Career\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 189\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 7,994\n| style=\"font-weight: bold;\" | 42.3\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Denver Broncos===\n====2008 season: Rookie year====\n{{See also|2008 Denver Broncos season}}\n\nIn 2008, Kern won the starting punter job for the [[2008 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]], winning the job over competitor [[Sam Paulescu]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_10345953 | work=Denver Post | first=Lindsay H. | last=Jones | title=Kern survives punters' war | date=August 31, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDuring his rookie season with the Broncos, Kern attempted 46 punts for an average of 46.7. He made his NFL debut the season opener against the [[2008 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had two punts for 80 net yards for a 40.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809080rai.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Oakland Raiders - September 8th, 2008|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> His longest punt of the year was 64 yards against the [[2008 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] in Week 2.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140den.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at Denver Broncos - September 14th, 2008  |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 5, against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, he had 5 punts for a season-high 248 net yards for a 49.6 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200810050den.htm|title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Denver Broncos - October 5th, 2008|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He gave away one touchdown that year against the Oakland Raiders in Week 12 when [[Johnnie Lee Higgins]] took the punt back 89 yards for the score.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200811230den.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Denver Broncos - November 23rd, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2008/ |title=Brett Kern 2008 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2009 season====\n{{See also|2009 Denver Broncos season}}\n[[File:Brett Kern.JPG|thumb|left|225px|Kern in 2009]]\n\nKern remained as the Broncos' punter in his second professional season. In the season opener against the [[2009 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 340 net yards for a 42.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909130cin.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Cincinnati Bengals - September 13th, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 20, against the [[2009 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], he had two punts for 109 net yards for a season-high 54.5 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909200den.htm|title=Cleveland Browns at Denver Broncos - September 20th, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He finished the 2009 season with 64 punts for 2,910 net yards for a 45.47 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2009/ |title=Brett Kern 2009 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite having the third highest yards per punt average in NFL history,<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/punt_yds_per_punt_career.htm]</ref> Kern was waived by the Broncos.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/broncos/2009/10/26/berger-new-broncos-punter/ |title=Kern waived; Berger new Broncos punter | work=Denver Post | date=October 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\n====2009 season====\n{{See also|2009 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nKern was claimed off waivers by the [[Tennessee Titans]], replacing [[Reggie Hodges]]. At the time Kern was released from the Broncos and claimed by the Titans, the Broncos were [http://www.nfl.com/teams/schedule?team=DEN&season=2009&seasonType=REG 6\u20130] while the Titans were 0\u20136. A subsequent Titans winning streak and Broncos losing streak led to a situation where teams with Kern on the roster had compiled a record of 11\u20130 to begin the season, despite the two teams being a collective 12\u201310 overall in that period.\n\nOn November 1, he made his Titans debut against the [[2009 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He had four punts for 193 net yards for a 48.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911010oti.htm|title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans - November 1st, 2009|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOverall, in the 2009 season, he totaled 64 punts for 2,910 yards for a 45.47 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2009/ |title=Brett Kern 2009 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2010 season====\n{{See also|2010 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nKern remained as the Titans' punter in the 2010 season. On September 12, in the season opener against the [[2010 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had four punts for 200 net yards for a season-high 50.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009120oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 12th, 2010|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 26, in Week 16 against the [[2010 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 352 net yards for a 44.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012260kan.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - December 26th, 2010|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2010 season, he had 77 punts for 3,302 net yards for a 42.88 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2010 |title=Brett Kern 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\n{{See also|2011 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn February 24, Kern signed a four-year, $5.2 million contract extension with the Titans with $2.1 million guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/Article/Brett-Kern-receives-a-four-year-extension-from-Titans-16346|title=Titans reach deal with punter Kern|last=McCormick|first=Terry|website=247sports.com|date=February 24, 2011 |access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the season opener on September 11, Kern had seven punts for 291 net yards for a 41.57 average against the [[2011 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109110jax.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - September 11th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2011 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he had a 21-yard rush.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109250oti.htm|title=Denver Broncos at Tennessee Titans - September 25th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 30, in Week 8 against the [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 330 net yards for a 41.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110300oti.htm|title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - October 30th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 4, against the [[2011 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], he had five punts for 239 net yards for a season-high 47.8 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040buf.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Buffalo Bills - December 4th, 2011|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2011 season, he recorded 86 punts for 3,747 net yards for a 43.57 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2011 |title=Brett Kern 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\n{{See also|2012 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season opener on September 9, against the [[2012 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Kern had four punts for 209 net yards for a 52.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090oti.htm|title=New England Patriots at Tennessee Titans - September 9th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 9, against the [[2012 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had three punts for 165 net yards for a season-high 55.0 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212090clt.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Indianapolis Colts - December 9th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 15 against the [[2012 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], he had a season-high 10 punts for a season-high 391 net yards for a 39.1 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212170oti.htm|title=New York Jets at Tennessee Titans - December 17th, 2012|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2012 season, he had 81 punts for 3,855 yards for a 47.59 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2012 |title=Brett Kern 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\n\n{{See also|2013 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn September 8, against the [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Kern had five punts for 208 net yards for a 41.6 average in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080pit.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Pittsburgh Steelers - September 8th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[2013 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he had a season-high eight punts for 382 net yards for a 47.75 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309150htx.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Houston Texans - September 15th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 8, against the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he had four punts for 201 net yards for a season-high 50.25 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201312080den.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Denver Broncos - December 8th, 2013|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2013 season, he had 78 punts for 3,386 net yards for a 43.41 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2013 |title=Brett Kern 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\n{{See also|2014 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season opener against the [[2014 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Kern had six punts for 304 net yards for a 50.67 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070kan.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - September 7th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On November 9, against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], he had a season-high eight punts for a season-high 414 net yards for a 51.75 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411090rav.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Baltimore Ravens - November 9th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 28, against the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had seven punts for 383 net yards for a season-high 54.71 average. In addition, he had a career-long 79-yard punt in the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412280oti.htm|title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans - December 28th, 2014|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the 2014 season, he had 88 punts for 4,118 net yards for a 46.80 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2014 |title=Brett Kern 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n{{See also|2015 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn March 8, 2015, Kern signed a five-year $15 million contract extension with the Titans.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000477236/article/titans-brett-kern-agree-on-multiyear-contract |title=Titans, Brett Kern agree on multiyear contract| work=NFL | date=March 8, 2015}}</ref> \n\nOn September 13, against the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had four punts for 189 net yards for a 47.25 average in the season opener.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130tam.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - September 13th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 20, against the [[2015 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he had five punts for 272 net yards for a season-high 54.4 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200nwe.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - December 20th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 16, on December 27, against the [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he had a season-high nine punts for a season-high 427 net yards for a 47.44 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512270oti.htm|title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans - December 27th, 2015|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the 2015 season, he recorded 88 punts for 4,175 net yards for a 47.44 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2015 |title=Brett Kern 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{See also|2016 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nIn the season-opener against the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Kern had five punts for 231 net yards for a 46.2 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110oti.htm|title=Minnesota Vikings at Tennessee Titans - September 11th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3, against the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he had six punts for 311 net yards for a season-high 51.83 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609250oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 25th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On December 24, in Week 16 against the [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], he had seven punts for a season-high 313 net yards for a 44.71 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612240jax.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars - December 24th, 2016|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In the 2016 season, he finished with 77 punts for 3,402 net yards for a 44.18 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2016 |title=Brett Kern 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{See also|2017 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nDuring the season-opener against the [[2017 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Kern had four punts for 188 net yards for a 47 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100oti.htm|title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 10th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On September 24, in Week 3 against the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], he had six punts for 341 net yards for a season-high 56.83 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709240oti.htm|title=Seattle Seahawks at Tennessee Titans - September 24th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> On October 8, against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], he had a career-high 10 punts for a franchise-record 549 net yards and a 54.9 average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710080mia.htm|title=Tennessee Titans at Miami Dolphins - October 8th, 2017|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> \n\nOn December 19, 2017, Kern was named to his first Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> Kern finished the 2017 season with 75 punts for 3,728 net yards for a franchise-record 49.71 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2017 |title=Brett Kern 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> He was named second-team All-Pro.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000903015/article/allpro-team-antonio-brown-a-unanimous-selection | title=2017 All-Pro Team | date=January 5, 2018 | accessdate=Jan 5, 2018 | newspaper=[[Associated Press]] }}</ref>\n\nThe Titans finished the 2017 season with a 9\u20137 record and qualified for the playoffs as the #5 seed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/oti/2017.htm |title=2017 Tennessee Titans Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017 |title=2017 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref> In the Wild Card Round against the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Kern made his playoff debut. In the 22\u201321 win, he had three punts for 131 net yards for a 43.7 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801060kan.htm |title=Wild Card - Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs - January 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref> In the Divisional Round against the [[2017 New England Patriots|New England Patriots]], he had seven punts for 316 net yards for a 45.14 average.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n{{See also|2018 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File:BrettKern11-18-18.jpeg|thumb|left|Kern in 2018]]\n\nOn December 18, 2018, Kern was named to his second [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/three-titans-jurrell-casey-taylor-lewan-and-brett-kern-selected-to-pro-bowl-team |title=Three Titans - Jurrel Casey, Taylor Lewan, and Brett Kern - Selected to Pro Bowl Team |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=December 18, 2018 |website=TitansOnline.com |access-date=January 20, 2019}}</ref> Kern finished the season punting 74 times with 39 being inside the 20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KernBr20/gamelog/2018/ |title=Brett Kern 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\n{{see also|2019 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File:Brett Kern.png|thumb|Kern at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] ]]\nOn March 7, 2019, Kern signed a four-year, $12.55 million contract extension with the Titans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.musiccitymiracles.com/2019/3/7/18255355/nfl-tennessee-titans-give-punter-brett-kern-four-year-extension-free-agency-2019 |title=Titans give punter Brett Kern four year extension |last=Lambert |first=Terry A. |date=March 7, 2019 |website=MusicCityMiracles.com}}</ref>  On December 17, 2019, he was selected to his third consecutive [[Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2019/12/17/derrick-henry-brett-kern-titans-pro-bowl/2681124001/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry, Brett Kern named to 2020 Pro Bowl |date=December 17, 2019|agency=The Tennessean |website=www.tennesseean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He led the league in punts placed inside the 20-yard line with 37 and was named First-Team All-Pro.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://titanswire.usatoday.com/2020/01/03/titans-brett-kern-derrick-henry-named-all-pros/ |title=Titans P Brett Kern, RB Derrick Henry named All-Pros |date=January 3, 2020|agency=Titans Wire |website=www.titanswire.usatoday.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n|Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n|Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Punts !! Yards !! Long !! Blocks !! Average !! Inside 20\n|-\n| [[2008 NFL season|2008]] || [[2008 Denver Broncos season|DEN]]\n| '''16''' || 46 || 2,150 || 64 || 0 || 46.7 || 13\n|-\n|! rowspan=\"2\" | [[2009 NFL season|2009]] || [[2009 Denver Broncos season|DEN]]\n| 6 || 27 || 1,245 || 64 || 0 || 46.1 || 9\n|-\n| [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| 10 || 37 || 1,665 || 67 || 0 || 45.5 |